{"title_page": "Portrayal of East Asians in American film and theater", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Yellowface|other uses|Yellow Face (disambiguation){{!}}Yellow Face}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n'''Portrayals of East Asians in American film and theatre''' has been a subject of controversy.  These portrayals have frequently reflected an [[ethnocentric]] perception of East Asians rather than realistic and authentic depictions of East Asian cultures, colors, customs, and behaviors.<ref name=\"diversity\"/><ref name=\"vanishing\">{{Citation |last=Kashiwabara |first=Amy |url=http://www.lib.berkeley.edu/MRC/Amydoc.html |title=Vanishing Son: The Appearance, Disappearance, and Assimilation of the Asian-American Man in American Mainstream Media |publisher=UC Berkeley Media Resources Center}}</ref><ref name=\"chin\">{{cite book|first=Frank|last=Chin|first2=Jeffery|last2=Chan|year=1972|title=Seeing Through Shuck|chapter = Racist Love|chapterurl=http://www.dartmouth.edu/~hist32/Hist33/chin%20Racist%20Love.pdf|editor=Richard Kostelanetz|publisher=Ballantine Books|location=New York|page=65}}</ref> Portraying the rich and complex diversity of East Asians and Asian-Americans in a single movie or theatrical show is difficult to do. The 2018 film ''[[Crazy Rich Asians (film)|Crazy Rich Asians]]'' received criticism for only depicting a small segment of the Asian diaspora.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/columns/crazy-rich-asians-representation-1202905965/|title=\u2018Crazy Rich Asians\u2019 Doesn\u2019t Represent All Asians Everywhere, and That\u2019s Fine (Column)|last=Yap|first=Audrey Cleo|date=August 19, 2018|work=Variety|access-date=2018-09-12|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nYellowface, a form of [[theatrical makeup]] used by [[white people|European-American]] performers to represent an [[East Asian person]] (similar to the practice of [[blackface]] used to represent [[Black people|African-American]] performers),<ref name=\"diversity\">{{cite web|url=http://imdiversity.com/villages/asian/yellowface-asians-on-white-screens/|title=Yellowface: Asians on White Screens|website=IMDiversity|first=Yayoi Lena|last=Winfrey|date=November 19, 2012}}</ref> continues to be used in film and theater.<ref name=\"diversity\"/><ref name=\"vanishing\"/> In the 21st century alone, ''[[Grindhouse (film)|Grindhouse]]'' (in a trailer parody of the [[Fu Manchu]] serials), ''[[Balls of Fury]]'', ''[[I Now Pronounce You Chuck and Larry]]'', ''[[Crank: High Voltage]]'', and ''[[Cloud Atlas (film)|Cloud Atlas]]'' all feature yellowface or non-East Asian actors as East Asian [[caricature]]s.<ref>\"The Practice of Yellow Face,\" by Vickie Rozel, TheatreWorks Silicon Valley In The Works [https://web.archive.org/web/20110708181020/http://theatreworks.commercialmedia.com/media/InTheWorks.YellowFace.pdf theatreworks.commercialmedia.com]</ref>\n\n== Early East Asian American film actors ==\n\n=== Sessue Hayakawa ===\nThe Japanese actor [[Sessue Hayakawa]] began appearing in films around 1914.<ref name=\"goldsea\">[http://goldsea.com/Personalities/Hayakawas/hayakawas.html www.goldsea.com] ''Sessue Hayakawa: The Legend''</ref> Signed to [[Paramount Pictures]], he had roles in more than 20 silent films including ''The Wrath of the Gods'' (1914) and ''The Typhoon'' (1914), and was considered to be a Hollywood [[sex symbol]].<ref name=\"goldsea\" /> When Hayakawa's contract with Paramount expired in 1918, the studio still wanted him to star in an upcoming movie, but Hayakawa turned them down in favor of starting his own company.<ref name=\"goldsea\" /> He was at the height of his popularity during that time.<ref name=\"goldsea\" /> His career in the United States suffered a bit due to the advent of talkies, as he had a heavy [[Japanese pitch accent|Japanese accent]]. He became unemployable during the World War II era due to [[anti-Japanese sentiment in the United States|anti-Japanese prejudice]]. He experienced a career revival beginning in 1949 in World War II-themed films, and was nominated for the Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor for his performance in ''[[The Bridge on the River Kwai]]''.<ref name=\"goldsea\" />\n\n=== Anna May Wong ===\n[[Anna May Wong]], considered by many to be the first Chinese-American movie star,<ref name=\"Chang\">Chan, Anthony B. Perpetually Cool: The Many Lives of Anna May Wong (1905\u20131961). Lanham, MD: The Scarecrow Press, 2003. {{ISBN|0-8108-4789-2}} p. xi, p. 42.</ref> was acting by the age of 14 and in 1922, at age 17, she became the first Chinese-American to break Hollywood's miscegenation rule playing opposite a white romantic lead in ''[[The Toll of the Sea]]''. Even though she was internationally known by 1924, her film roles were limited by stereotype and prejudice. Tired of being both typecast and passed over for lead East Asian character roles in favor of European-American actresses, Wong left Hollywood in 1928 for Europe.<ref name=\"Chang\" /> Interviewed by Doris Mackie for ''Film Weekly'' in 1933, Wong complained about her Hollywood roles: \"I was so tired of the parts I had to play.\"<ref name=\"Leong\">Leong, Karen J. The China Mystique: Pearl S. Buck, Anna May Wong, Mayling Soong, and the Transformation of American Orientalism. Berkeley, CA: University of California Press, 2005. {{ISBN|0-520-24422-2}}. pp. 83, 187.</ref><ref name=\"Wollstein\">Wollstein, Hans J. \"Anna May Wong.\" Vixens, Floozies, and Molls: 28 Actresses of late 1920s and 1930s Hollywood. Jefferson, NC: McFarland, 1999. {{ISBN|0-7864-0565-1}}. p. 252.</ref> She commented: \"There seems little for me in Hollywood, because, rather than real Chinese, producers prefer Hungarians, Mexicans, American Indians for Chinese roles.\"<ref name=\"Parish\">Parish, James and William Leonard. \"Anna May Wong.\" Hollywood Players: The Thirties. New Rochelle, NY: Arlington House Publishers, 1976, pp. 532\u2013538. {{ISBN|0-87000-365-8}}.</ref> In 1935, she was considered for the leading role in ''[[The Good Earth (film)|The Good Earth]]'', which went to German actress [[Luise Rainer]]. Wong refused the role of the villainess, a stereotypical Oriental [[Dragon Lady]].\n\n=== Keye Luke ===\n[[Keye Luke]] was a successful actor, starring as the \"Number-One Son\" Lee Chan in the popular [[Charlie Chan]] films, as well as the original [[Kato (The Green Hornet)|Kato]] in the 1940s [[Green Hornet]], and Detective James Lee Wong in ''[[Phantom of Chinatown]]'' (1940), a role previously played by the English actor [[Boris Karloff]].\n\n=== Philip Ahn ===\nKorean-American actor [[Philip Ahn]], after rejection for speaking English too well, braved death threats after playing Japanese villains. Ahn would go on to have a prolific career.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nSome East and South Asian-American actors nonetheless attempted to start careers. [[Merle Oberon]], an [[Anglo-Indian]], was able to get starring roles after concocting a phony story about her origins and using skin whitening make-up. There were others pioneering East Asian-American actors like [[Benson Fong]] (who played the Number Three son in the [[Charlie Chan]] films), [[Victor Sen Yung]] (who played the Number Two son in the [[Charlie Chan]] films), [[Richard Loo]] (who also played many Japanese villain roles), [[Lotus Long]] (known for her role as Lin Wen opposite [[Keye Luke]] in the ''[[Phantom of Chinatown]]''), Suzanna Kim, [[Barbara Jean Wong]], [[Fely Franquelli]], [[Chester Gan]], Honorable Wu, [[Kam Tong]], [[Layne Tom Jr.]], Maurice Liu, [[Rudy Robles]], [[Teru Shimada]], [[Willie Fung]], [[Toshia Mori]] and Wing Foo; all began their film careers in the 1930s and '40s.\n\nWith the number of East Asian-American actors available, actor [[Robert Ito]] wrote an article that described that job protection for Caucasian actors was one reason Asians were portrayed by Caucasians. \"With the relatively small percentage of actors that support themselves by acting, it was only logical that they should try to limit the available talent pool as much as possible. One way of doing this was by placing restrictions on minority actors, which, in the case of Asian actors, meant that they could usually only get roles as houseboys, cooks, laundrymen, and crazed war enemies, with the rare \"white hero's loyal sidekick\" roles going to the big name actors. When the script called for a larger Asian role, it was almost inevitably given to a white actor.\"<ref>[http://www.brightlightsfilm.com/18/18_yellow.html www.brightlightsflim.com] {{webarchive|url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20101212005020/http://www.brightlightsfilm.com/18/18_yellow.html |date=December 12, 2010 }} ''A Certain Slant''</ref>\n\n== Recent East Asian American film actors ==\nThe 2018 film ''[[Crazy Rich Asians (film)|Crazy Rich Asians]]'' starred [[Constance Wu]], [[Henry Golding (actor)|Henry Golding]], [[Michelle Yeoh]], [[Gemma Chan]], [[Lisa Lu]], [[Awkwafina]], [[Harry Shum Jr.]], [[Ken Jeong]], [[Sonoya Mizuno]], [[Chris Pang]], [[Jimmy O. Yang]], [[Ronny Chieng]], [[Remy Hii]], [[Nico Santos (actor)|Nico Santos]], [[Jing Lusi]], [[Carmen Soo]], among others. \n\n==European actors who have played East Asian roles==\nThe Welsh-American [[Myrna Loy]] was the \"go to girl\" for any portrayal of Asian characters and was [[Typecasting (acting)|typecast]] in over a dozen films, while Chinese detective [[Charlie Chan]], who was modeled after [[Chang Apana]], a real-life Chinese Hawaiian detective, was portrayed by several European and European-American actors including [[Warner Oland]], [[Sidney Toler]], and [[Peter Ustinov]]. Loy also appeared in yellowface alongside [[Nick Lucas]] in ''[[The Show of Shows]]''.<ref>{{Citation|title=Myrna Loy|date=2019-11-06|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Myrna_Loy&oldid=924921244|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref>\n\nThe list of actors who have donned \"Yellowface\" to portray East Asians at some point in their career includes: [[Lon Chaney, Sr.]], [[Edward G. Robinson]], [[Paul Muni]], [[Loretta Young]], [[Boris Karloff]], [[Peter Lorre]], [[Anthony Quinn]], [[Shirley MacLaine]], [[Katharine Hepburn]], [[Rita Moreno]], [[Rex Harrison]], [[John Wayne]], [[Mickey Rooney]], [[Marlon Brando]], [[Lupe V\u00e9lez]], [[Alec Guinness]], [[Tony Randall]], [[John Gielgud]], [[Max von Sydow]], [[Linda Hunt]], [[Jamie Lee Curtis]], [[Eddie Murphy]], [[David Carradine]], [[Joel Grey]], [[Peter Sellers]], and many others.<ref>{{Citation|title=Examples of yellowface|date=2019-10-27|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Examples_of_yellowface&oldid=923263206|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref>\n\n==''Madame Butterfly''==\n[[Madame Butterfly (short story)|\"Madame Butterfly\" was originally a short story]] written by Philadelphia attorney [[John Luther Long]].<ref>[http://www.logos-verlag.de/cgi-bin/buch/isbn/1076 www.logos-verlag.de] ''Analysis of John Luther Long's \"Madame Butterfly\"''</ref> It was turned into a one-act play, ''[[Madame Butterfly (play)|Madame Butterfly: A Tragedy of Japan]]'', by [[David Belasco]]. [[Giacomo Puccini]] re-made the play into the Italian opera ''[[Madama Butterfly]]'', set in 1904.<ref name=\"Japantimes\">[http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/fm20050703a1.html japantimes.co.jp] ''Madama Butterfly, Puccini's masterpiece transcends its age'' By Benjamin Woodward</ref> [[Madame Butterfly (1915 film)|The 1915 silent film version]] was directed by [[Sidney Olcott]] and starred [[Mary Pickford]].<ref>{{IMDb title|0005682|Madame Butterfly|(1915)}}</ref>\n\nAll the versions of Madame Butterfly tell the story of a young Japanese woman who has converted to Christianity (for which she is disowned by her family) and marries Benjamin Franklin Pinkerton, a white lieutenant in the U.S. Navy. For him, the marriage is a temporary convenience, but Butterfly's conversion is sincere, and she takes her marriage vows seriously.<ref name=\"news24Puccini\">[http://www.news24.com/Entertainment/International/Puccini-opera-is-racist-20070214 Puccini opera is 'racist': News24: Entertainment: International] news24.com</ref> Pinkerton's naval duties eventually call him away from Japan. He leaves Butterfly behind and she soon gives birth to their son. Pinkerton eventually meets and marries a white American woman (the fact he stopped paying the rent on Butterfly's house amounted to a divorce under Japanese law at the time).<ref name=\"news24Puccini\"/> Pinkerton returns to Japan with his new wife, Kate, to claim his son. Butterfly acquiesces to his request, and then kills herself as Pinkerton rushes into the house, too late to stop her. In the ''original'' story by Long, Butterfly is on the point of killing herself when the presence of her child reminds her of her Christian conversion, and the story ends with Mr and Mrs Pinkerton arriving at the house the next morning to find it completely empty.\n\n==Early film==\n{{See also|Racism in early American film}}\n\n===''Mr. Wu'' (1913)===\n''[[Mr. Wu]]'' was originally a stage play, written by Harold Owen and Harry M. Vernon. It was first staged in London in 1913, with [[Matheson Lang]] in the lead. He became so popular in the role that he starred in a 1919 film version. Lang continued to play Oriental roles (although not exclusively), and his autobiography was titled ''Mr. Wu Looks Back'' (1940). The first U.S. production opened in New York on October 14, 1914. The actor [[Frank Morgan]] was in the original Broadway cast, appearing under his original name Frank Wupperman.\n\n[[Lon Chaney, Sr.]] and [[Ren\u00e9e Ador\u00e9e]] were cast in the 1927 film. Cheekbones and lips were built up with cotton and collodion, the ends of cigar holders were inserted into his nostrils, and the long fingernails were constructed from stripes of painted film stock. Chaney used fishskin to fashion an Oriental cast to his eyes and grey crepe hair was used to create the distinctive Fu-Manchu moustache and goatee.\n\n===''The Forbidden City'' (1918)===\n''[[The Forbidden City]]'' is a 1918 American silent drama film starring Norma Talmadge and Thomas Meighan and directed by Sidney Franklin. A copy of the film is in the Library of Congress and other film archives.The plot centers around an inter-racial romance between a Chinese princess ([[Norma Talmadge]]) and an American. When palace officials discover she has fallen pregnant she is sentenced to death. In the latter part of the film Talmadge plays the now adult daughter of the affair, seeking her father in the Philippines.<ref>{{Citation|title=The Forbidden City|date=2019-04-05|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=The_Forbidden_City&oldid=891065098|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref>\n\n===''Broken Blossoms'' (1919)===\nThe film ''[[Broken Blossoms]]'' is based on a short story, \"The Chink and the Child\", taken from the book ''[[Limehouse Nights]]'' by [[Thomas Burke (author)|Thomas Burke]].<ref name=\"tcmbb\">[http://www.tcm.com/thismonth/article.jsp?cid=157070&mainArticleId=196827 www.tcm.com] ''Spotlight: Broken Blossoms''</ref> It was released in 1919, during a period of strong anti-Chinese feeling in the USA, a fear known as the [[Yellow Peril]]. Griffith changed Burke's original story to promote a message of tolerance. In Burke's story, the Chinese protagonist is a sordid young Shanghai drifter pressed into naval service, who frequents [[opium]] dens and whorehouses; in the film, he becomes a [[Buddhist]] missionary whose initial goal is to spread the [[dharma]] of the [[Buddha]] and peace (although he is also shown frequenting [[opium dens]] when he is depressed). Even at his lowest point, he still prevents his gambling companions from fighting.\n\n===''Flower Drum Song'' (1961)===\n''[[Flower Drum Song (film)|Flower Drum Song]]'' is a 1961 film adaptation of the 1958 Broadway play [[Flower Drum Song]]. This adaptation tells the story of a Chinese woman emigrating to the US and her subsequent arranged marriage. This movie featured the first majority Asian cast in Hollywood cinema; setting a precedent for the following ''[[The Joy Luck Club (film)|The Joy Luck Club]]'' and ''[[Crazy Rich Asians (film)|Crazy Rich Asians]]'' to have a majority Asian casting. It became the first major Hollywood feature film to have a majority Asian cast in a contemporary Asian-American story. \n\n===''The Joy Luck Club'' (1993)===\n''[[The Joy Luck Club (film)|The Joy Luck Club]]'' is a 1993 American drama directed by [[Wayne Wang]]. The story is based the [[The Joy Luck Club (novel)|novel of the same name]] by [[Amy Tan]]. This movie explored the relationship of Chinese immigrant mothers and their first-generation Chinese-American daughters. This movie was only the second in Hollywood cinema to feature an Asian majority casting.\n\n== 2010s in film ==\n{{Refimprovesection|date=June 2019|small=|talk=}}\n\n===''Gook'' (2017)===\n[[Gook (film)|''Gook'']] tells the story of Asian Americans during the [[1992 Los Angeles riots]]. It was released in 2017 with its director [[Justin Chon]], [[David So]], Sang Chon, Curtiss Cook Jr. and Ben Munoz. Unlike the usual depictions of Asian Americans in media, Gook tackles the harsh realities for the minority group despite its status of being [[model minority]].{{Editorializing|date=June 2019}} \n\n=== ''Ghost in the Shell'' (2017) ===\n[[Ghost in the Shell (2017 film)|''Ghost in the Shell'']] is a 2017 American adaptation of the Japanese manga [[Ghost in the Shell (manga)|''Ghost in the Shell'']] by [[Masamune Shirow]]. It was directed by [[Rupert Sanders]] and featured [[Scarlett Johansson]] as the main character. This movie was set in the future and revolved around a story of a cyborg discovering her past. This film was controversial due to the fact that the casting featured a Caucasian with the movie being accused of [[racism]] and [[Whitewashing in film]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Ghost in the Shell (2017 film)|date=2019-10-07|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Ghost_in_the_Shell_(2017_film)&oldid=920052171|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref> \n\n===''Crazy Rich Asians'' (2018)===\n[[Crazy Rich Asians (film)|''Crazy Rich Asians'']] is a 2018 film adaptation of [[Crazy Rich Asians|the book by the same name]] by [[Kevin Kwan]].  Despite being a critical and commercial success, the film received controversy over the casting of mixed race actors and non-Chinese actors in ethnically Chinese roles, as well as portraying the characters speaking British English and American English over [[Singapore English|Singaporean English]].<ref name=\"ST-2017-04-26\">{{cite web|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/viewpoint-colourism-mars-crazy-rich-asians-main-casting|title=Colourism mars Crazy Rich Asians main casting|last=Lui|first=John|date=April 26, 2017|work=The Straits Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180426043625/https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/viewpoint-colourism-mars-crazy-rich-asians-main-casting|archive-date=April 26, 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=February 5, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/film/106395816/crazy-rich-asians-is-not-us-say-singaporeans|title=Crazy Rich Asians is not us, say Singaporeans|last=Han|first=Kirsten|date=August 20, 2018|newspaper=Stuff New Zealand|accessdate=September 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.star2.com/entertainment/2018/05/04/crazy-rich-asians-trailer-controversies/|title='Crazy Rich Asians' criticised for being too Chinese, not Singlish enough|author=Agency|date=May 4, 2018|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|Star2]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620101248/https://www.star2.com/entertainment/2018/05/04/crazy-rich-asians-trailer-controversies/|archive-date=June 20, 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=August 20, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The movie was also criticized for its lack of diversity, with critics stating that the movie did not properly depict the variety of ethnic groups in Singapore.<ref name=\"Econ-1809\">{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/asia/2018/09/01/for-a-different-take-on-crazy-rich-asians-cross-the-pacific|title=For a different take on \"Crazy Rich Asians\", cross the Pacific|author=Banyan|date=September 1, 2018|work=The Economist|accessdate=September 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905120621/https://www.economist.com/asia/2018/09/01/for-a-different-take-on-crazy-rich-asians-cross-the-pacific|archive-date=September 5, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/16/world/asia/crazy-rich-asians-cast-singapore.html|title=For Some Viewers, 'Crazy Rich Asians' Is Not Asian Enough|last=Ives|first=Mike|date=August 16, 2018|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=September 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904042044/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/16/world/asia/crazy-rich-asians-cast-singapore.html|archive-date=September 4, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Lead actress [[Constance Wu]] responded to criticisms, stating that the film would not represent every Asian American given that the majority of characters depicted in the movie were ethnically Chinese and extremely wealthy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/16/world/asia/crazy-rich-asians-cast-singapore.html|title=For Some Viewers, \u2018Crazy Rich Asians\u2019 Is Not Asian Enough|last=Ives|first=Mike|date=2018-08-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-05-21|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Time magazine also noted that the film was the \"first modern story with an all-Asian cast and an Asian-American lead\" since the release of the 1993 film ''[[The Joy Luck Club (film)|Joy Luck Club]]''[[The Joy Luck Club (film)|.]]<ref name=\"Time-KarenHo\">{{cite magazine|last=Ho|first=Karen|date=August 15, 2018|title=''Crazy Rich Asians'' Is Going to Change Hollywood. It's About Time|url=http://time.com/longform/crazy-rich-asians/|url-status=live|magazine=Time|pages=40\u201346|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180902002626/http://time.com/longform/crazy-rich-asians/|archive-date=September 2, 2018|accessdate=August 25, 2018|df=mdy-all}} (physically published in August 27, 2018 issue; digitally published on August 15)</ref>\n\n===''To All the Boys I've Loved Before'' (2018)===\n[[To All the Boys I've Loved Before (film)|''To All the Boys I've Loved Before'']] is a 2018 Netflix Original movie based on [[To All the Boys I've Loved Before|the book by the same name]] by [[Jenny Han]]. The film stars [[Lana Condor]] and [[Noah Centineo]] and has been credited along with ''Crazy Rich Asians'' as helping to garner more representation for Asian Americans in film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/quartzy/1364272/netflixs-to-all-the-boys-crazy-rich-asians-and-the-golden-age-of-asian-rom-coms/|title=A golden age of Asian American rom-coms is dawning|last=Hassan|first=Aisha|website=Quartzy|language=en|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref> Of the film, Han stated that she had to turn down initial offers to adapt the book, as some of the studios wanted a white actress to play the main character of Lara Jean.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/books/to-all-the-boys-ive-loved-before-asian-american-representation/|title=Why 'To All The Boys I\u2019ve Loved Before' Author Jenny Han Had to Fight for an Asian American Star|website=PEOPLE.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n\n===''The Farewell'' (2019)===\n''[[The Farewell (2019 film)|The Farewell]]'' is a 2019 American [[comedy-drama]] film written and directed by [[Lulu Wang (filmmaker)|Lulu Wang]], based on a story called ''What You Don't Know'' that was initially shared by Wang on ''[[This American Life]]'' in April 2016.<ref name=\"thisamericanlife\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thisamericanlife.org/585/in-defense-of-ignorance|title=What You Don't Know|website=[[This American Life]]|date=April 22, 2016|access-date=November 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/the-farewell-lulu-wang-interview-a24-1202158932/|title='The Farewell': Lulu Wang Made the Year's Most Exciting Hit By Refusing to Whitewash It|website=[[IndieWire]]|first=Eric|last=Kohn|date=July 18, 2019|access-date=November 8, 2019}}</ref>  Based on Wang's life experiences, the film stars [[Awkwafina]] as Billi Wang, a Chinese American who upon learning her grandmother has only a short time left to live, is pressured by her family to not tell her while they schedule family gathering before she dies.<ref>https://variety.com/2019/film/features/10-directors-to-watch-lulu-wang-the-farewell-1203099291/</ref>  The film received critical acclaim; the film was nominated for two awards at the [[77th Golden Globe Awards]] including [[Golden Globe Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] and Awkwafina winning for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Best Actress \u2013 Musical or Comedy]], making her the first person of Asian descent to win a Golden Globe Award in any lead actress film category.<ref>https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/05/entertainment/awkwafina-golden-globes/index.html</ref>\n\n== 2020s in film ==\n\n===''Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings'' (2021)===\n''[[Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings]]'' is an upcoming 2021 [[superhero film]] based on the [[Marvel Comics]] character [[Shang-Chi]], set in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]].  Starring [[Simu Liu]] as Shang-Chi and [[Tony Leung Chiu-wai|Tony Leung]] as the [[Mandarin (character)|Mandarin]], the film will be Marvel's first superhero movie tentpole franchise with an Asian protagonist.  A film based on Shang-Chi was planned in 2006, but development did not begin in earnest until December 2018, following the success of ''Crazy Rich Asians''.<ref>https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2005-sep-06-fi-marvel6-story.html</ref><ref>https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/marvel-developing-shang-chi-movie-as-first-asian-lead-1165752</ref>  The film is expected to modernize the problematic elements of Shang-Chi and the Mandarin's comic book origins, which depicted negative stereotypes of East Asians.<ref>https://deadline.com/2018/12/shang-chi-marvel-studios-first-asian-film-superhero-dave-callaham-kevin-feige-black-panther-1202512660/</ref><ref>https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/how-shang-chi-could-be-marvels-next-black-panther-1166159</ref>  According to producer [[Kevin Feige]], ''Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings'' features a cast that is \"98 Asian\" and will \"be much more than a [[Kung fu film|Kung Fu movie]].\"<ref>https://comicbook.com/marvel/2019/12/30/marvel-studios-shang-chi-legend-ten-rings-98-percent-asian-cast-kevin-feige/?fbclid=IwAR1qFhfvNuWQjnEjH-k5TY9N7fFyjvMSkjAWxwFhdE9GXVI2dRrlTAmDiD8</ref>\n\n== 2010s television ==\n{{Unreferenced|section|date=June 2019}}\n\n=== ''Fresh Off the Boat'' (2015-2020) ===\n''[[Fresh Off the Boat]]'' is an American sitcom created by [[Nahnatchka Khan]]; a loose adaptation of author [[Eddie Huang]]'s ''Fresh off the Boat''. This show followed the life of an Asian-American family in the early 1990s. It is the first Asian-American sitcom to be featured prime time in America. It was released on February 2015 and has been renewed several times, ending with a two-part finale on February 21, 2020.  The success of this show led to other shows such as ''Dr. Ken'' to be produced for the American audience.<ref>{{Citation|title=Fresh Off the Boat|date=2019-11-08|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Fresh_Off_the_Boat&oldid=925253283|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Dr. Ken'' (2015-2017) ===\n''[[Dr. Ken]]'' is an American sitcom created by actor and writer [[Ken Jeong]]. This show followed the story of an Asian American doctor and his family. This show aired between October 2, 2015 and March 31, 2017. \n\n=== ''Kim's Convenience'' (2016-present) ===\n''[[Kim's Convenience (TV series)|''Kim's Convenience]]'' is a Canadian TV series created by [[Ins Choi]]'s 2011 play [[Kim's Convenience (play)|by the same name]]. This show revolves around the life of a family and their family-run convenience store located in Toronto. It debuted in October 2016 and has since been renewed for a fourth season. This show has been globally brought to attention with [[Netflix]] securing rights to broadcast it outside of Canada.\n\n=== ''Warrior'' (2019-present) ===\n''[[Warrior (TV series)|Warrior]]'' is an American action-drama television series executive-produced by [[Shannon Lee]] and [[Justin Lin]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cecchini |first1=Mike |title=Warrior: First Teaser for Bruce Lee Inspired TV Series |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/tv/warrior/153683/warrior-justin-lin-cinemax |website=Denofgeek |date=August 22, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Premiere\">{{cite web |last1=Li |first1=Shirley |title=Justin Lin talks bringing Bruce Lee's passion project to life in Warrior first look photos |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/02/08/justin-lin-bruce-lee-warrior-first-look/ |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=March 9, 2019 |date=February 8, 2019}}</ref>; based on an original concept and treatment by Lee's father [[Bruce Lee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/bruce-lee-warrior-tong-wars-drama-series-cinemax-justin-lin-jonathan-tropper-1202108759/|title=Bruce Lee-Inspired Tong Wars Drama \u2018Warrior\u2019 From Justin Lin & \u2018Banshee\u2019 Co-Creator Gets Cinemax Series Order|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=June 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/08/warrior-bruce-lee-inspired-crime-drama-pilot-cinemax-justin-lin-1201810722/|title=Bruce Lee-Inspired Crime Drama \u2018Warrior\u2019 From Justin Lin & \u2018Banshee\u2019 Co-Creator Gets Cinemax Pilot Order|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=August 30, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"developing\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/05/bruce-lee-crime-drama-warrior-justin-lin-cinemax-1201430580/|title=Cinemax Developing Bruce Lee-Inspired Crime Drama \u2018Warrior\u2019 From Justin Lin|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=May 21, 2015}}</ref>  The show follows a martial arts prodigy and his involvement in the [[Tong Wars]] of 1870s [[San Francisco]].  Bruce Lee developed the show in 1971, but had trouble pitching it to [[Warner Bros.]] and [[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uXOtmhA6Nvw \"From The Pierre Berton Show December 8, 1971] (comments near end of part 2 & early in part 3)</ref>  Lee's concept was retooled as ''[[Kung Fu (TV series)|Kung Fu]]'', with [[David Carradine]], a white actor, cast in the lead role; Warner Bros. gave Lee no credit.<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1975a|p=}}</ref>  The show premiered on [[Cinemax]] on April 5, 2019 and was subsequently renewed for a second season.<ref>https://deadline.com/2019/04/warrior-renewed-season-2-cinemax-tong-wars-drama-series-bruce-lee-justin-lin-1202600027/</ref>\n\n==Classic Hollywood cinema==\n===''Fu Manchu''===\nIn 1929, the character [[Fu Manchu]] made his American film debut in ''[[The Mysterious Dr. Fu Manchu]]'' played by the Swedish-American actor [[Warner Oland]]. Oland repeated the role in 1930s ''[[The Return of Dr. Fu Manchu]]'' and 1931's ''[[Daughter of the Dragon]]''. Oland appeared in character in the 1931 musical, ''[[Paramount on Parade]]'' where the Devil Doctor was seen to murder both [[Philo Vance]] and [[Sherlock Holmes]].\n\nIn 1932, [[Boris Karloff]] took over the character in the film ''[[The Mask of Fu Manchu]]''.<ref>{{IMDb title|id=0023194|title=The Mask of Fu Manchu}}</ref> The film's tone has long been considered racist and offensive,<ref name=\"mank\">Gregory William Mank, ''Hollywood Cauldron: 13 Horror Films from the Genres's Golden Age''. McFarland, 2001 (pp. 53-89); {{ISBN|0-7864-1112-0}}</ref><ref>[[Christopher Frayling]], quoted in \"Fu Manchu\", in [[Kim Newman|Newman, Kim]] (ed.), ''The BFI Companion to Horror''. London, Cassell,1996, pp. 131-32; {{ISBN|0-304-33216-X}}</ref> but that only added to its cult status alongside its humor and [[Grand Guignol]] sets and torture sequences. The film was suppressed for many years, but has since received critical re-evaluation and been released on DVD uncut.\n\n===Charlie Chan===\n{{Main|Charlie Chan}}\nIn a series of films in the 1930s and '40s, Chinese-American detective Charlie Chan was played by white actors [[Warner Oland]], [[Sidney Toler]] and [[Roland Winters]]. The Swedish-born Oland, unlike his two successors in the Chan role, actually looked somewhat Chinese, and according to his contemporaries, he did not use special makeup in the role. He also played East Asians in other films, including ''[[Shanghai Express (film)|Shanghai Express]]'', ''[[The Painted Veil (1934 film)|The Painted Veil]]'', and ''[[Werewolf of London]]''. (Decades later, Afro-European American TV actor [[Khigh Dhiegh]], though of African and European descent, was generally cast as an East Asian because of his appearance, and he was often included on lists of East Asian actors.)\n\n===''The Good Earth''===\n[[File:Luise Rainer in The Good Earth trailer 2.jpg|right|thumb]]\n''[[The Good Earth (film)|The Good Earth]]'' (1937) is a [[feature film|film]] about [[China|Chinese]] farmers who struggle to survive.<ref>[http://www.asian-studies.org/EAA/hayford.htm www.asian-studies.org] ''What's So Bad About \"The Good Earth\"'' by Charles W. Hayford.</ref> It was adapted by [[Talbot Jennings]], [[Tess Slesinger]], and [[Claudine West]] from the play by [[Donald Davis (writer)|Donald Davis]] and [[Owen Davis]], which was itself based on the 1931 novel ''[[The Good Earth]]'' by [[Nobel Prize]]-winning author [[Pearl S. Buck]]. The film was directed by [[Sidney Franklin (director)|Sidney Franklin]], [[Victor Fleming]] (uncredited) and [[Gustav Machaty]] (uncredited).\n\nThe film's budget was $2.8 million, relatively expensive for the time, and took three years to make. Although Pearl Buck intended the film to be cast with all Chinese or Chinese-American actors, the studio opted to use established American stars, tapping Europeans [[Paul Muni]] and [[Luise Rainer]] for the lead roles. Both had won Oscars the previous year; Rainer for her role in ''[[The Great Ziegfeld]]'' and Muni for the lead in ''[[The Story of Louis Pasteur]]''. When questioned about his choice of the actors, producer [[Irving Thalberg]] responded by saying, \"I'm in the business of creating illusions.\"<ref name=\"Davies2016\">{{cite book|author=Peter Ho Davies|title=The Fortunes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mOslCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT140|date=August 25, 2016|publisher=Hodder & Stoughton|isbn=978-1-4447-1056-4|page=140}}</ref>\n\n[[Anna May Wong]] had been considered a top contender for the role of O-lan, the Chinese heroine of the novel. However, because Paul Muni was a white man, the [[Hays Code]]'s [[Anti-miscegenation laws|anti-miscegenation]] rules required the actress who played his wife to be a white woman. So, MGM gave the role of O-lan to a European actress and offered Wong the role of Lotus, the story's villain. Wong refused to be the only Chinese-American, playing the only negative character, stating: \"I won't play the part. If you let me play O-lan, I'll be very glad. But you're asking me \u2013 with Chinese blood \u2013 to do the only unsympathetic role in the picture featuring an all-American cast portraying Chinese characters.\"<ref>[http://www.asiaarts.ucla.edu/article.asp?parentid=6132 www.asiaarts.ucla.edu] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090801170834/http://www.asiaarts.ucla.edu/article.asp?parentid=6132 |date=August 1, 2009 }} ''Profile of Anna May Wong: Remembering The Silent Star'' by Kenneth Quan</ref> MGM's refusal to consider Wong for this most high-profile of Chinese characters in U.S. film is remembered today as \"one of the most notorious cases of casting discrimination in the 1930s\".<ref name=\"FischerLandy2004\">{{cite book|author1=Lucy Fischer|author2=Marcia Landy|title=Stars: The Film Reader|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jl8Nu4IlqMMC&pg=PA189|year=2004|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-415-27892-8|page=189}}</ref>\n\n''The Good Earth'' was nominated for five [[Academy Awards]] including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Best Direction]] ([[Sidney Franklin (director)|Sidney Franklin]]), [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]] ([[Karl Freund]]), and [[Academy Award for Best Film Editing|Best Film Editing]] (Basil Wrangell). In addition to the [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] award (Luise Rainer), the film won for [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]].<ref>[http://www.tcm.com/thismonth/article.jsp?cid=27609&mainArticleId=196827 tcm.com] ''Spotlight: The Good Earth''</ref> The year ''The Good Earth'' came out, Wong appeared on the cover of ''[[Look (American magazine)|Look]]'' magazine's second issue, which labeled her \"The World's Most Beautiful Chinese Girl.\"<ref>Corliss, Richard. [http://content.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,1022536,00.html ''Anna May Wong Did It Right''], ''Time'' magazine, January 29, 2005, accessed May 22, 2018</ref> Stereotyped in America as a [[dragon lady]], the cover photo had her holding a dagger.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\n===''Breakfast at Tiffany's''===\n{{main|I. Y. Yunioshi}}\nThe 1961 film ''[[Breakfast at Tiffany's (film)|Breakfast at Tiffany's]]'' has been criticized for its portrayal of the character Mr. Yunioshi, Holly's bucktoothed, stereotyped Japanese neighbor. [[Mickey Rooney]] wore makeup to change his features to a caricatured approximation of a Japanese person. In the 45th anniversary edition DVD release, producer [[Richard Shepherd (producer)|Richard Shepherd]] repeatedly apologizes, saying, \"If we could just change Mickey Rooney, I'd be thrilled with the movie\".<ref name=\"makingof\">''Breakfast at Tiffany's'': The Making of a Classic</ref> Director [[Blake Edwards]] stated, \"Looking back, I wish I had never done it&nbsp;... and I would give anything to be able to recast it, but it's there, and onward and upward\".<ref name=\"makingof\"/> In a 2008 interview about the film, 87-year-old Rooney said he was heartbroken about the criticism and that he had never received any complaints about his portrayal of the character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sacbee.com/121/story/1220270.html |title=Sacramento Bee: Racism in reel life |last=Calvert |first=Bruce |date=September 9, 2008 |publisher=sacbee.com |accessdate=2008-11-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121034154/http://www.sacbee.com/121/story/1220270.html |archivedate=November 21, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n=== ''Sixteen Candles'' ===\nThe 1984 American film ''[[Sixteen Candles]]'' has been criticized for the character of [[Long Duk Dong]]. This Asian character became an \"Asian American stereotype for a new generation\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/codeswitch/2015/02/06/384307677/whats-so-cringe-worthy-about-long-duk-dong-in-sixteen-candles|title=What's So 'Cringeworthy' About Long Duk Dong in 'Sixteen Candles'?|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref> Long Duk Dong displayed a variety of stereotypes in the film such being socially awkward and difficult to understand, and the \"lecherous but sexually inept loser\"<ref name=\":1\" />. The idea of Asians being more feminine and therefore \"weaker\" is further exemplified through Long Duk Dong's romantic relationship with one of the characters in the film. He assumes the more feminine role while the American girl becomes the more masculine of two in the relationship. This shows how the Asian characters are far inferior compared to their Western counterparts.\n\n==Theater==\n\"Yellowface\" in theatre has been called \"the practice of white actors donning overdone face paint and costumes that serves as a caricatured representation of traditional Asian garb.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dallas Summer Musicals' THE KING AND I Casting Causes Controversy |url = http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Dallas-Summer-Musicals-THE-KING-AND-I-Casting-Causes-Controversy-20150125|website = BroadwayWorld.com|accessdate = 2015-11-25}}</ref> Founded in 2011, an organization known as, \"The Asian American Performers Action Coalition\" or the AAPAC work in an effort to, \"expand the perception of Asian American performers in order to increase their access to and representation on New York City's stages.\" This group works to address and discuss \"Yellowface\" controversies and occurrences.<ref>{{Cite web|title = AAPAC|url = http://www.aapacnyc.org/|website = AAPAC|accessdate = 2015-11-25}}</ref>{{non-primary source needed|date=November 2015}}\n\n===''Miss Saigon''===\n{{main|Miss Saigon}}\n''Miss Saigon'', a musical with music by Claude-Michel Sch\u00f6nberg, lyrics by Alain Boublil and Richard Maltby, Jr. and book by Boublil and Sch\u00f6nberg, is a modern adaptation of Giacomo Puccini's opera \"Madame Butterfly\". Miss Saigon tells the story of a doomed romance involving a Vietnamese woman and an American soldier set in the time of the Vietnam War.<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Heat Is On: Touring Production of Miss Saigon Met With Protests at Minnesota's Ordway Theater|url = http://www.playbill.com/news/article/the-heat-is-on-touring-production-of-miss-saigon-met-with-protests-at-minne-210375|website = Playbill|accessdate = 2015-11-25}}</ref>\n\nWhen ''Miss Saigon'' premiered at the Theatre Royal, Drury Lane, London on September 20, 1989, Welsh actor [[Jonathan Pryce]] wore heavy prosthetic eyelids and skin darkening cream in playing The Engineer, a mixed-race French-Vietnamese pimp.<ref>{{Cite web|title = \"A Certain Slant\": A Brief History of Hollywood Yellowface - Bright Lights Film Journal|url = http://brightlightsfilm.com/certain-slant-brief-history-hollywood-yellowface/#.VlKNx2SrS2y|website = Bright Lights Film Journal|accessdate = 2015-11-25|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://archive.is/20140503000205/http://brightlightsfilm.com/certain-slant-brief-history-hollywood-yellowface/#.VlKNx2SrS2y|archivedate = May 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOnce the London production came to Broadway in 1990, Pryce was slated to reprise his role as The Engineer, causing a major rift in American theater circles and sparking public outcry. Tony Award-winning playwright [[David Henry Hwang]] wrote a letter to the Actors' Equity Association protesting this portrayal of a Eurasian character being played by a White actor.<ref>{{Cite news|title = 'Yellow Face' at Theatre J explores Asian representation in the theater world|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/express/wp/2014/01/30/yellow-face-at-theatre-j-explores-asian-representation-in-the-theater-world/|newspaper = The Washington Post|date = January 30, 2014|access-date = 2015-11-25|issn = 0190-8286|language = en-US|first = Christina|last = Cauterucci}}</ref>\n\nDespite these protests, Pryce performed the Engineer to great acclaim and ''Miss Saigon'' became one of Broadway's longest-running hits.<ref>{{cite news|title = David Henry Hwang: racial casting has evolved \u2013 and so have my opinions|url = https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2014/may/12/david-henry-hwang-miss-saigon-yellow-face-racial-casting|work=The Guardian|location=London|accessdate = 2015-11-25|first = David Henry|last = Hwang}}</ref>\n\n===''The Mikado''===\n{{main|The Mikado}}\n''[[The Mikado]]'' is a comic operetta, with music by [[Arthur Sullivan]] and libretto by [[W. S. Gilbert]], premiered in 1885 in London and still performed frequently in the English-speaking world and beyond.<ref>Kenrick, John. [http://www.musicals101.com/gilbert3.htm \"The Gilbert & Sullivan Story: Part III\"], Musicals101.com, accessed November 11, 2016</ref><ref name=Steinberg>Steinberg, Neil.  [http://www.suntimes.com/news/steinberg/2706603-452/mikado-production-opera-chicago-lyric.html \"Updated ''Mikado'' promises to be as rousing as ever\"].  ''Chicago Sun-Times'', December 6, 2010</ref> In setting the opera in a fictionalized 19th century Japan, Gilbert used the veneer of Far Eastern exoticism to soften the impact of his pointed satire of British institutions and politics.<ref name=Steinberg/><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20061029085114/http://www.lyricoperasandiego.com/Education/MikadoGenesis.htm \"Mikado Genesis\"], Lyric Opera San Diego</ref>\n\nNumerous 21st century US productions of ''The Mikado'' have been criticized for the use of Yellowface in their casting: New York (2004 and 2015), Los Angeles (2007 and 2009), Boston (2007), Austin (2011), Denver (2013), and Seattle (2014)<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = Stereotypes in 'The Mikado' Stir Controversy in Seattle - NBC News|url = https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/stereotypes-mikado-stir-controversy-seattle-n157306|website = NBC News|accessdate = 2015-11-25}}</ref> The press noted that the Seattle Gilbert & Sullivan Society cast the 10 principal roles and the chorus with white actors, with the exception of two Latino actors.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2015, the [[New York Gilbert and Sullivan Players]] cancelled a production of ''The Mikado'' that was set to feature their repertory company of mostly White actors, due to complaints from the East Asian-American community.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Following Outcry from the Asian Community, The Mikado (With Caucasian Actors) Canceled|url = http://www.playbill.com/news/article/following-outcry-from-the-asian-community-the-mikado-with-caucasian-actors-canceled-362959|website = Playbill|accessdate = 2015-11-25}}</ref> The company redesigned its production in collaboration with an advisory group of East Asian-American theater professionals and debuted the new concept in 2016,<ref>[http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/New-York-Gilbert-Sullivan-Players-Reveals-Concepts-for-Reimagined-THE-MIKADO-Kelvin-Moon-Loh-Joins-Creative-Team-20161006# \"New York Gilbert & Sullivan Players Reveals Concepts for Reimagined ''The Mikado''; Kelvin Moon Loh Joins Creative Team!\"], BroadwayWorld.com, October 6, 2016</ref> receiving a warm review in ''The New York Times''.<ref>Fonseca-Wollheim, Corinna da. [https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/30/arts/music/review-gilbert-and-sullivan-the-mikado.html \"Is ''The Mikado'' Too Politically Incorrect to Be Fixed? Maybe Not.\"], December 30, 2016</ref> After [[Lamplighters Music Theatre]] of San Francisco planned a 2016 production, objections by the East Asian-American community prompted them to re-set the operetta in [[Duchy of Milan|Renaissance-era Milan]], replacing all references to Japan with Milan.<ref>Tran, Diep. [http://www.americantheatre.org/2016/04/20/building-a-better-mikado-minus-the-yellowface \"Building a Better ''Mikado'', Minus the Yellowface\"], ''American Theatre'', April 20, 2016</ref> Reviewers felt that the change resolved the issue.<ref>Kosman, Joshua. [http://www.sfgate.com/music/article/Lamplighters-transplanted-Mikado-retains-9129437.php \"Lamplighters' transplanted ''Mikado'' retains its charm\"], ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'', August 8, 2016; and Hurwitt, Sam. [http://www.mercurynews.com/entertainment/ci_30220924/review-guilt-free-mikado-unveiled-by-lamplighters \"Review: Guilt-free ''Mikado'' unveiled by Lamplighters\"], ''[[The Mercury News]]'', August 8, 2016</ref>\n\n===''The King and I''===\n{{main|The King and I}}\n''The King and I'' is a musical by Richard Rodgers (composer) and Oscar von Hammerstein II (lyricist). Based on the 1944 novel ''Anna and the King of Siam'' by Margaret Landon, the story illustrates the clash of Eastern and Western cultures by relaying the experiences of Anna, a British schoolteacher hired as part of the King's drive to modernize his country. The relationship between the King and Anna is marked by conflict and constant bickering throughout the musical, as well as by a love that neither can confess.\n\nThe 2015 Dallas Summer Musical's production of the musical caused controversy in the casting of a European-American actor as King Mongkut. In an open letter to Dallas Summer Musicals, the AAPAC criticized the choice, saying \"the casting of a white King dramaturgically undermines a story about a clash between Western and Eastern cultures\"; moreover, \"Asian impersonation denies Asians our own subjecthood. It situates all the power within a Caucasian-centric world view.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dallas Summer Musicals' THE KING AND I Casting Causes Controversy|url = http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Dallas-Summer-Musicals-THE-KING-AND-I-Casting-Causes-Controversy-20150125|website = BroadwayWorld.com|accessdate = 2015-11-25}}</ref>\n\n==Other examples in Western media==\n{{Main|Examples of yellowface}}\n[[File:Nancy Kwan & David Carradine in Kung Fu.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Actors [[Nancy Kwan]] and [[David Carradine]] in the 1970s TV series, ''[[Kung Fu (TV series)|Kung Fu]]''.]]\nA prominent example of the [[Whitewashing in film|whitewashing]] of Asian roles is the 1970s TV series, ''[[Kung Fu (TV series)|Kung Fu]]'', in which the leading character \u2013 a Chinese monk and martial arts master who fled China after having accidentally slain the emperor's nephew \u2013 is portrayed by European-American actor, [[David Carradine]]. The film ''[[Dragon: The Bruce Lee Story]]'' describes to some extent the struggles that ensued when Hollywood moguls attempted to cast [[Bruce Lee]] in the starring role of Caine but were overruled. The American film adaptation of the manga series [[Ghost in the Shell (manga)]] faced controversy over its casting of [[Scarlett Johansson]] as the main character Major who is depicted as Japanese looking in the anime and manga. American actress [[Emma Stone]] played a half-Asian character in the film [[Aloha (2015 film)]]. In the film [[Cloud Atlas (film)]] every major male character in the Korean story line was played by a non-Asian actor made up in yellow face makeup<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/oct/26/cloud-atlas-under-fire-yellowface|title=Cloud Atlas under fire for casting white actors in 'yellowface' makeup|last=Brooks|first=Xan|date=2012-10-26|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-06-12|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>.\n\n[[Michael Derrick Hudson]], an American poet, used a Chinese female ''[[nom de plume]]''.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Film}}\n*[[Blackface]] and [[Blackface in contemporary art]]\n*[[Covert racism]]\n*[[Examples of yellowface]]\n*''[[Reel Bad Arabs]]''\n*''[[Reel Injun]]''\n*[[Stereotypes of East Asians in the United States]]\n*[[Whiteface (performance)]]\n* [[Whitewashing in film]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite book |first=Graham Russell|last=Hodges|title=Anna May Wong: From Laundryman's Daughter to Hollywood Legend|url=https://archive.org/details/annamaywongfroml0000hodg|url-access=registration|location=New York|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|date=2004}}\n*{{cite book |first=Gina|last=Marchetti|title=Romance and the \"Yellow Peril\" Race, Sex, and Discursive Strategies in Hollywood Fiction|url=https://archive.org/details/romanceyellowper00gina|url-access=registration|location=Berkeley|publisher=University of California Press|date=1993}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Ito|first=Robert B.|url=http://brightlightsfilm.com/certain-slant-brief-history-hollywood-yellowface/|title=A Certain Slant: A Brief History of Hollywood Yellowface|journal=[[Bright Lights Film Journal]]|accessdate=May 2, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140503000205/http://brightlightsfilm.com/certain-slant-brief-history-hollywood-yellowface/|archivedate=May 3, 2014}}\n* {{cite book |last=Moon |first=Krystyn R. |title= Yellowface: Creating the Chinese in American Popular Music and Performance, 1850s\u20131920s (New Brunswick, N.J.: Rutgers University Press, 2006).}}\n* {{cite book |last=Paul |first=John Steven |title=Misreading the Chinese Character: Images of the Chinese in Euroamerican Drama to 1925 (review) Asian Theatre Journal|volume=18|issue=1|pages=117\u2013119|date=Spring 2001|publisher=University of Hawai'i Press }}\n* {{cite book |last=Prasso |first=Sheridan |title= The Asian Mystique: dragon ladies, geisha girls, & our fantasies of the exotic orient |date=2005 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Wang|first=Yiman|editor=Catherine Russell|title=Camera Obscura 60: New Women of the Silent Screen: China, Japan, Hollywood|chapter=The Art of Screen Passing: [[Anna May Wong]]'s Yellow Yellowface Performance in the Art Deco Era|pages=159\u2013191|year=2005|publisher=Duke University Press|location=Durham, N.C.|isbn=978-0-8223-6624-9}}\n* Metzger, Sean. \"Charles Parsloe's Chinese Fetish: An Example of Yellowface Performance in Nineteenth-Century American Melodrama.\" Theatre Journal 56, no. 4 (2004): 627-51. <nowiki>https://www.jstor.org/stable/25069532</nowiki>.\n* Young, Cynthia Ann. \"AfroAsian Encounters: Culture, History, Politics (review).\" Journal of Asian American Studies 10, no. 3 (2007): 316-18. {{doi|10.1353/jaas.2007.0033}}.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080724174617/http://www.deepfocusproductions.com/HollywoodChinese ''Hollywood Chinese''], a 2007 documentary film about the portrayals of Chinese men and women in Hollywood productions\n* [http://www.imdiversity.com/Villages/Asian/arts_culture_media/archives/winfrey_yellowface_asians_hollywood.asp \"Yellowface: Asians on White Screens\"], by Yayoi Lena Winfrey, ''IM Diversity.com''\n* [https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20101212005020/http://www.brightlightsfilm.com/18/18_yellow.html \"A Certain Slant\"] by Robert B. Ito, ''Bright Lights Film Journal''\n* [http://www.goldsea.com/Mediawatch/mediawatch.html \"Monitoring Asians in the American mass media\"] at Asian American Media Watch\n* [http://www.tcm.com/thismonth/article/?cid=201608&mainArticleId=196827 \"Asian Images in Film: Introduction\"] at TCM\n* [https://www.npr.org/sections/codeswitch/2014/08/14/339559520/roundtable-the-past-and-present-of-yellowface \"Roundtable: The Past and Present of 'Yellowface'\"], at [[NPR]]\n\n[[Category:History of racism in the cinema of the United States]]\n[[Category:Cultural appropriation]]\n[[Category:Asian-American culture]]\n[[Category:Asian-American issues]]\n[[Category:Ethnic and racial stereotypes in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Yellowface|other uses|Yellow Face (disambiguation){{!}}Yellow Face}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n'''Portrayals of East Asians in American film and theatre''' has been a subject of controversy.  These portrayals have frequently reflected an [[ethnocentric]] perception of East Asians rather than realistic and authentic depictions of East Asian cultures, colors, customs, and behaviors.<ref name=\"diversity\"/><ref name=\"vanishing\">{{Citation |last=Kashiwabara |first=Amy |url=http://www.lib.berkeley.edu/MRC/Amydoc.html |title=Vanishing Son: The Appearance, Disappearance, and Assimilation of the Asian-American Man in American Mainstream Media |publisher=UC Berkeley Media Resources Center}}</ref><ref name=\"chin\">{{cite book|first=Frank|last=Chin|first2=Jeffery|last2=Chan|year=1972|title=Seeing Through Shuck|chapter = Racist Love|chapterurl=http://www.dartmouth.edu/~hist32/Hist33/chin%20Racist%20Love.pdf|editor=Richard Kostelanetz|publisher=Ballantine Books|location=New York|page=65}}</ref> Portraying the rich and complex diversity of East Asians and Asian-Americans in a single movie or theatrical show is difficult to do. The 2018 film ''[[Crazy Rich Asians (film)|Crazy Rich Asians]]'' received criticism for only depicting a small segment of the Asian diaspora.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/columns/crazy-rich-asians-representation-1202905965/|title=\u2018Crazy Rich Asians\u2019 Doesn\u2019t Represent All Asians Everywhere, and That\u2019s Fine (Column)|last=Yap|first=Audrey Cleo|date=August 19, 2018|work=Variety|access-date=2018-09-12|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nYellowface, a form of [[theatrical makeup]] used by [[white people|European-American]] performers to represent an [[East Asian person]] (similar to the practice of [[blackface]] used to represent [[Black people|African-American]] performers),<ref name=\"diversity\">{{cite web|url=http://imdiversity.com/villages/asian/yellowface-asians-on-white-screens/|title=Yellowface: Asians on White Screens|website=IMDiversity|first=Yayoi Lena|last=Winfrey|date=November 19, 2012}}</ref> continues to be used in film and theater.<ref name=\"diversity\"/><ref name=\"vanishing\"/> In the 21st century alone, ''[[Grindhouse (film)|Grindhouse]]'' (in a trailer parody of the [[Fu Manchu]] serials), ''[[Balls of Fury]]'', ''[[I Now Pronounce You Chuck and Larry]]'', ''[[Crank: High Voltage]]'', and ''[[Cloud Atlas (film)|Cloud Atlas]]'' all feature yellowface or non-East Asian actors as East Asian [[caricature]]s.<ref>\"The Practice of Yellow Face,\" by Vickie Rozel, TheatreWorks Silicon Valley In The Works [https://web.archive.org/web/20110708181020/http://theatreworks.commercialmedia.com/media/InTheWorks.YellowFace.pdf theatreworks.commercialmedia.com]</ref>\n\n== Early East Asian American film actors ==\n\n=== Sessue Hayakawa ===\nThe Japanese actor [[Sessue Hayakawa]] began appearing in films around 1914.<ref name=\"goldsea\">[http://goldsea.com/Personalities/Hayakawas/hayakawas.html www.goldsea.com] ''Sessue Hayakawa: The Legend''</ref> Signed to [[Paramount Pictures]], he had roles in more than 20 silent films including ''The Wrath of the Gods'' (1914) and ''The Typhoon'' (1914), and was considered to be a Hollywood [[sex symbol]].<ref name=\"goldsea\" /> When Hayakawa's contract with Paramount expired in 1918, the studio still wanted him to star in an upcoming movie, but Hayakawa turned them down in favor of starting his own company.<ref name=\"goldsea\" /> He was at the height of his popularity during that time.<ref name=\"goldsea\" /> His career in the United States suffered a bit due to the advent of talkies, as he had a heavy [[Japanese pitch accent|Japanese accent]]. He became unemployable during the World War II era due to [[anti-Japanese sentiment in the United States|anti-Japanese prejudice]]. He experienced a career revival beginning in 1949 in World War II-themed films, and was nominated for the Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor for his performance in ''[[The Bridge on the River Kwai]]''.<ref name=\"goldsea\" />\n\n=== Anna May Wong ===\n[[Anna May Wong]], considered by many to be the first Chinese-American movie star,<ref name=\"Chang\">Chan, Anthony B. Perpetually Cool: The Many Lives of Anna May Wong (1905\u20131961). Lanham, MD: The Scarecrow Press, 2003. {{ISBN|0-8108-4789-2}} p. xi, p. 42.</ref> was acting by the age of 14 and in 1922, at age 17, she became the first Chinese-American to break Hollywood's miscegenation rule playing opposite a white romantic lead in ''[[The Toll of the Sea]]''. Even though she was internationally known by 1924, her film roles were limited by stereotype and prejudice. Tired of being both typecast and passed over for lead East Asian character roles in favor of European-American actresses, Wong left Hollywood in 1928 for Europe.<ref name=\"Chang\" /> Interviewed by Doris Mackie for ''Film Weekly'' in 1933, Wong complained about her Hollywood roles: \"I was so tired of the parts I had to play.\"<ref name=\"Leong\">Leong, Karen J. The China Mystique: Pearl S. Buck, Anna May Wong, Mayling Soong, and the Transformation of American Orientalism. Berkeley, CA: University of California Press, 2005. {{ISBN|0-520-24422-2}}. pp. 83, 187.</ref><ref name=\"Wollstein\">Wollstein, Hans J. \"Anna May Wong.\" Vixens, Floozies, and Molls: 28 Actresses of late 1920s and 1930s Hollywood. Jefferson, NC: McFarland, 1999. {{ISBN|0-7864-0565-1}}. p. 252.</ref> She commented: \"There seems little for me in Hollywood, because, rather than real Chinese, producers prefer Hungarians, Mexicans, American Indians for Chinese roles.\"<ref name=\"Parish\">Parish, James and William Leonard. \"Anna May Wong.\" Hollywood Players: The Thirties. New Rochelle, NY: Arlington House Publishers, 1976, pp. 532\u2013538. {{ISBN|0-87000-365-8}}.</ref> In 1935, she was considered for the leading role in ''[[The Good Earth (film)|The Good Earth]]'', which went to German actress [[Luise Rainer]]. Wong refused the role of the villainess, a stereotypical Oriental [[Dragon Lady]].\n\n=== Keye Luke ===\n[[Keye Luke]] was a successful actor, starring as the \"Number-One Son\" Lee Chan in the popular [[Charlie Chan]] films, as well as the original [[Kato (The Green Hornet)|Kato]] in the 1940s [[Green Hornet]], and Detective James Lee Wong in ''[[Phantom of Chinatown]]'' (1940), a role previously played by the English actor [[Boris Karloff]].\n\n=== Philip Ahn ===\nKorean-American actor [[Philip Ahn]], after rejection for speaking English too well, braved death threats after playing Japanese villains. Ahn would go on to have a prolific career.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nSome East and South Asian-American actors nonetheless attempted to start careers. [[Merle Oberon]], an [[Anglo-Indian]], was able to get starring roles after concocting a phony story about her origins and using skin whitening make-up. There were others pioneering East Asian-American actors like [[Benson Fong]] (who played the Number Three son in the [[Charlie Chan]] films), [[Victor Sen Yung]] (who played the Number Two son in the [[Charlie Chan]] films), [[Richard Loo]] (who also played many Japanese villain roles), [[Lotus Long]] (known for her role as Lin Wen opposite [[Keye Luke]] in the ''[[Phantom of Chinatown]]''), Suzanna Kim, [[Barbara Jean Wong]], [[Fely Franquelli]], [[Chester Gan]], Honorable Wu, [[Kam Tong]], [[Layne Tom Jr.]], Maurice Liu, [[Rudy Robles]], [[Teru Shimada]], [[Willie Fung]], [[Toshia Mori]] and Wing Foo; all began their film careers in the 1930s and '40s.\n\nWith the number of East Asian-American actors available, actor [[Robert Ito]] wrote an article that described that job protection for Caucasian actors was one reason Asians were portrayed by Caucasians. \"With the relatively small percentage of actors that support themselves by acting, it was only logical that they should try to limit the available talent pool as much as possible. One way of doing this was by placing restrictions on minority actors, which, in the case of Asian actors, meant that they could usually only get roles as houseboys, cooks, laundrymen, and crazed war enemies, with the rare \"white hero's loyal sidekick\" roles going to the big name actors. When the script called for a larger Asian role, it was almost inevitably given to a white actor.\"<ref>[http://www.brightlightsfilm.com/18/18_yellow.html www.brightlightsflim.com] {{webarchive|url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20101212005020/http://www.brightlightsfilm.com/18/18_yellow.html |date=December 12, 2010 }} ''A Certain Slant''</ref>\n\n== Recent East Asian American film actors ==\nThe 2018 film ''[[Crazy Rich Asians (film)|Crazy Rich Asians]]'' starred [[Constance Wu]], [[Henry Golding (actor)|Henry Golding]], [[Michelle Yeoh]], [[Gemma Chan]], [[Lisa Lu]], [[Awkwafina]], [[Harry Shum Jr.]], [[Ken Jeong]], [[Sonoya Mizuno]], [[Chris Pang]], [[Jimmy O. Yang]], [[Ronny Chieng]], [[Remy Hii]], [[Nico Santos (actor)|Nico Santos]], [[Jing Lusi]], [[Carmen Soo]], among others. \n\n==European actors who have played East Asian roles==\nThe Welsh-American [[Myrna Loy]] was the \"go to girl\" for any portrayal of Asian characters and was [[Typecasting (acting)|typecast]] in over a dozen films, while Chinese detective [[Charlie Chan]], who was modeled after [[Chang Apana]], a real-life Chinese Hawaiian detective, was portrayed by several European and European-American actors including [[Warner Oland]], [[Sidney Toler]], and [[Peter Ustinov]]. Loy also appeared in yellowface alongside [[Nick Lucas]] in ''[[The Show of Shows]]''.<ref>{{Citation|title=Myrna Loy|date=2019-11-06|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Myrna_Loy&oldid=924921244|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref>\n\nThe list of actors who have donned \"Yellowface\" to portray East Asians at some point in their career includes: [[Lon Chaney, Sr.]], [[Edward G. Robinson]], [[Paul Muni]], [[Loretta Young]], [[Boris Karloff]], [[Peter Lorre]], [[Anthony Quinn]], [[Shirley MacLaine]], [[Katharine Hepburn]], [[Rita Moreno]], [[Rex Harrison]], [[John Wayne]], [[Mickey Rooney]], [[Marlon Brando]], [[Lupe V\u00e9lez]], [[Alec Guinness]], [[Tony Randall]], [[John Gielgud]], [[Max von Sydow]], [[Linda Hunt]], [[Jamie Lee Curtis]], [[Eddie Murphy]], [[David Carradine]], [[Joel Grey]], [[Peter Sellers]], and many others.<ref>{{Citation|title=Examples of yellowface|date=2019-10-27|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Examples_of_yellowface&oldid=923263206|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref>\n\n==''Madame Butterfly''==\n[[Madame Butterfly (short story)|\"Madame Butterfly\" was originally a short story]] written by Philadelphia attorney [[John Luther Long]].<ref>[http://www.logos-verlag.de/cgi-bin/buch/isbn/1076 www.logos-verlag.de] ''Analysis of John Luther Long's \"Madame Butterfly\"''</ref> It was turned into a one-act play, ''[[Madame Butterfly (play)|Madame Butterfly: A Tragedy of Japan]]'', by [[David Belasco]]. [[Giacomo Puccini]] re-made the play into the Italian opera ''[[Madama Butterfly]]'', set in 1904.<ref name=\"Japantimes\">[http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/fm20050703a1.html japantimes.co.jp] ''Madama Butterfly, Puccini's masterpiece transcends its age'' By Benjamin Woodward</ref> [[Madame Butterfly (1915 film)|The 1915 silent film version]] was directed by [[Sidney Olcott]] and starred [[Mary Pickford]].<ref>{{IMDb title|0005682|Madame Butterfly|(1915)}}</ref>\n\nAll the versions of Madame Butterfly tell the story of a young Japanese woman who has converted to Christianity (for which she is disowned by her family) and marries Benjamin Franklin Pinkerton, a white lieutenant in the U.S. Navy. For him, the marriage is a temporary convenience, but Butterfly's conversion is sincere, and she takes her marriage vows seriously.<ref name=\"news24Puccini\">[http://www.news24.com/Entertainment/International/Puccini-opera-is-racist-20070214 Puccini opera is 'racist': News24: Entertainment: International] news24.com</ref> Pinkerton's naval duties eventually call him away from Japan. He leaves Butterfly behind and she soon gives birth to their son. Pinkerton eventually meets and marries a white American woman (the fact he stopped paying the rent on Butterfly's house amounted to a divorce under Japanese law at the time).<ref name=\"news24Puccini\"/> Pinkerton returns to Japan with his new wife, Kate, to claim his son. Butterfly acquiesces to his request, and then kills herself as Pinkerton rushes into the house, too late to stop her. In the ''original'' story by Long, Butterfly is on the point of killing herself when the presence of her child reminds her of her Christian conversion, and the story ends with Mr and Mrs Pinkerton arriving at the house the next morning to find it completely empty.\n\n==Early film==\n{{See also|Racism in early American film}}\n\n===''Mr. Wu'' (1913)===\n''[[Mr. Wu]]'' was originally a stage play, written by Harold Owen and Harry M. Vernon. It was first staged in London in 1913, with [[Matheson Lang]] in the lead. He became so popular in the role that he starred in a 1919 film version. Lang continued to play Oriental roles (although not exclusively), and his autobiography was titled ''Mr. Wu Looks Back'' (1940). The first U.S. production opened in New York on October 14, 1914. The actor [[Frank Morgan]] was in the original Broadway cast, appearing under his original name Frank Wupperman.\n\n[[Lon Chaney, Sr.]] and [[Ren\u00e9e Ador\u00e9e]] were cast in the 1927 film. Cheekbones and lips were built up with cotton and collodion, the ends of cigar holders were inserted into his nostrils, and the long fingernails were constructed from stripes of painted film stock. Chaney used fishskin to fashion an Oriental cast to his eyes and grey crepe hair was used to create the distinctive Fu-Manchu moustache and goatee.\n\n===''The Forbidden City'' (1918)===\n''[[The Forbidden City]]'' is a 1918 American silent drama film starring Norma Talmadge and Thomas Meighan and directed by Sidney Franklin. A copy of the film is in the Library of Congress and other film archives.The plot centers around an inter-racial romance between a Chinese princess ([[Norma Talmadge]]) and an American. When palace officials discover she has fallen pregnant she is sentenced to death. In the latter part of the film Talmadge plays the now adult daughter of the affair, seeking her father in the Philippines.<ref>{{Citation|title=The Forbidden City|date=2019-04-05|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=The_Forbidden_City&oldid=891065098|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref>\n\n===''Broken Blossoms'' (1919)===\nThe film ''[[Broken Blossoms]]'' is based on a short story, \"The Chink and the Child\", taken from the book ''[[Limehouse Nights]]'' by [[Thomas Burke (author)|Thomas Burke]].<ref name=\"tcmbb\">[http://www.tcm.com/thismonth/article.jsp?cid=157070&mainArticleId=196827 www.tcm.com] ''Spotlight: Broken Blossoms''</ref> It was released in 1919, during a period of strong anti-Chinese feeling in the USA, a fear known as the [[Yellow Peril]]. Griffith changed Burke's original story to promote a message of tolerance. In Burke's story, the Chinese protagonist is a sordid young Shanghai drifter pressed into naval service, who frequents [[opium]] dens and whorehouses; in the film, he becomes a [[Buddhist]] missionary whose initial goal is to spread the [[dharma]] of the [[Buddha]] and peace (although he is also shown frequenting [[opium dens]] when he is depressed). Even at his lowest point, he still prevents his gambling companions from fighting.\n\n===''Flower Drum Song'' (1961)===\n''[[Flower Drum Song (film)|Flower Drum Song]]'' is a 1961 film adaptation of the 1958 Broadway play [[Flower Drum Song]]. This adaptation tells the story of a Chinese woman emigrating to the US and her subsequent arranged marriage. This movie featured the first majority Asian cast in Hollywood cinema; setting a precedent for the following ''[[The Joy Luck Club (film)|The Joy Luck Club]]'' and ''[[Crazy Rich Asians (film)|Crazy Rich Asians]]'' to have a majority Asian casting. It became the first major Hollywood feature film to have a majority Asian cast in a contemporary Asian-American story. \n\n===''The Joy Luck Club'' (1993)===\n''[[The Joy Luck Club (film)|The Joy Luck Club]]'' is a 1993 American drama directed by [[Wayne Wang]]. The story is based the [[The Joy Luck Club (novel)|novel of the same name]] by [[Amy Tan]]. This movie explored the relationship of Chinese immigrant mothers and their first-generation Chinese-American daughters. This movie was only the second in Hollywood cinema to feature an Asian majority casting.\n\n== 2010s in film ==\n{{Refimprovesection|date=June 2019|small=|talk=}}\n\n===''Gook'' (2017)===\n[[Gook (film)|''Gook'']] tells the story of Asian Americans during the [[1992 Los Angeles riots]]. It was released in 2017 with its director [[Justin Chon]], [[David So]], Sang Chon, Curtiss Cook Jr. and Ben Munoz. Unlike the usual depictions of Asian Americans in media, Gook tackles the harsh realities for the minority group despite its status of being [[model minority]].{{Editorializing|date=June 2019}} \n\n=== ''Ghost in the Shell'' (2017) ===\n[[Ghost in the Shell (2017 film)|''Ghost in the Shell'']] is a 2017 American adaptation of the Japanese manga [[Ghost in the Shell (manga)|''Ghost in the Shell'']] by [[Masamune Shirow]]. It was directed by [[Rupert Sanders]] and featured [[Scarlett Johansson]] as the main character. This movie was set in the future and revolved around a story of a cyborg discovering her past. This film was controversial due to the fact that the casting featured a Caucasian with the movie being accused of [[racism]] and [[Whitewashing in film]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Ghost in the Shell (2017 film)|date=2019-10-07|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Ghost_in_the_Shell_(2017_film)&oldid=920052171|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref> \n\n===''Crazy Rich Asians'' (2018)===\n[[Crazy Rich Asians (film)|''Crazy Rich Asians'']] is a 2018 film adaptation of [[Crazy Rich Asians|the book by the same name]] by [[Kevin Kwan]].  Despite being a critical and commercial success, the film received controversy over the casting of mixed race actors and non-Chinese actors in ethnically Chinese roles, as well as portraying the characters speaking British English and American English over [[Singapore English|Singaporean English]].<ref name=\"ST-2017-04-26\">{{cite web|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/viewpoint-colourism-mars-crazy-rich-asians-main-casting|title=Colourism mars Crazy Rich Asians main casting|last=Lui|first=John|date=April 26, 2017|work=The Straits Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180426043625/https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/viewpoint-colourism-mars-crazy-rich-asians-main-casting|archive-date=April 26, 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=February 5, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/film/106395816/crazy-rich-asians-is-not-us-say-singaporeans|title=Crazy Rich Asians is not us, say Singaporeans|last=Han|first=Kirsten|date=August 20, 2018|newspaper=Stuff New Zealand|accessdate=September 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.star2.com/entertainment/2018/05/04/crazy-rich-asians-trailer-controversies/|title='Crazy Rich Asians' criticised for being too Chinese, not Singlish enough|author=Agency|date=May 4, 2018|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|Star2]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620101248/https://www.star2.com/entertainment/2018/05/04/crazy-rich-asians-trailer-controversies/|archive-date=June 20, 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=August 20, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The movie was also criticized for its lack of diversity, with critics stating that the movie did not properly depict the variety of ethnic groups in Singapore.<ref name=\"Econ-1809\">{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/asia/2018/09/01/for-a-different-take-on-crazy-rich-asians-cross-the-pacific|title=For a different take on \"Crazy Rich Asians\", cross the Pacific|author=Banyan|date=September 1, 2018|work=The Economist|accessdate=September 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905120621/https://www.economist.com/asia/2018/09/01/for-a-different-take-on-crazy-rich-asians-cross-the-pacific|archive-date=September 5, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/16/world/asia/crazy-rich-asians-cast-singapore.html|title=For Some Viewers, 'Crazy Rich Asians' Is Not Asian Enough|last=Ives|first=Mike|date=August 16, 2018|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=September 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904042044/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/16/world/asia/crazy-rich-asians-cast-singapore.html|archive-date=September 4, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Lead actress [[Constance Wu]] responded to criticisms, stating that the film would not represent every Asian American given that the majority of characters depicted in the movie were ethnically Chinese and extremely wealthy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/16/world/asia/crazy-rich-asians-cast-singapore.html|title=For Some Viewers, \u2018Crazy Rich Asians\u2019 Is Not Asian Enough|last=Ives|first=Mike|date=2018-08-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-05-21|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Time magazine also noted that the film was the \"first modern story with an all-Asian cast and an Asian-American lead\" since the release of the 1993 film ''[[The Joy Luck Club (film)|Joy Luck Club]]''[[The Joy Luck Club (film)|.]]<ref name=\"Time-KarenHo\">{{cite magazine|last=Ho|first=Karen|date=August 15, 2018|title=''Crazy Rich Asians'' Is Going to Change Hollywood. It's About Time|url=http://time.com/longform/crazy-rich-asians/|url-status=live|magazine=Time|pages=40\u201346|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180902002626/http://time.com/longform/crazy-rich-asians/|archive-date=September 2, 2018|accessdate=August 25, 2018|df=mdy-all}} (physically published in August 27, 2018 issue; digitally published on August 15)</ref>\n\n===''To All the Boys I've Loved Before'' (2018)===\n[[To All the Boys I've Loved Before (film)|''To All the Boys I've Loved Before'']] is a 2018 Netflix Original movie based on [[To All the Boys I've Loved Before|the book by the same name]] by [[Jenny Han]]. The film stars [[Lana Condor]] and [[Noah Centineo]] and has been credited along with ''Crazy Rich Asians'' as helping to garner more representation for Asian Americans in film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/quartzy/1364272/netflixs-to-all-the-boys-crazy-rich-asians-and-the-golden-age-of-asian-rom-coms/|title=A golden age of Asian American rom-coms is dawning|last=Hassan|first=Aisha|website=Quartzy|language=en|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref> Of the film, Han stated that she had to turn down initial offers to adapt the book, as some of the studios wanted a white actress to play the main character of Lara Jean.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/books/to-all-the-boys-ive-loved-before-asian-american-representation/|title=Why 'To All The Boys I\u2019ve Loved Before' Author Jenny Han Had to Fight for an Asian American Star|website=PEOPLE.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n\n===''The Farewell'' (2019)===\n''[[The Farewell (2019 film)|The Farewell]]'' is a 2019 American [[comedy-drama]] film written and directed by [[Lulu Wang (filmmaker)|Lulu Wang]], based on a story called ''What You Don't Know'' that was initially shared by Wang on ''[[This American Life]]'' in April 2016.<ref name=\"thisamericanlife\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thisamericanlife.org/585/in-defense-of-ignorance|title=What You Don't Know|website=[[This American Life]]|date=April 22, 2016|access-date=November 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/the-farewell-lulu-wang-interview-a24-1202158932/|title='The Farewell': Lulu Wang Made the Year's Most Exciting Hit By Refusing to Whitewash It|website=[[IndieWire]]|first=Eric|last=Kohn|date=July 18, 2019|access-date=November 8, 2019}}</ref>  Based on Wang's life experiences, the film stars [[Awkwafina]] as Billi Wang, a Chinese American who upon learning her grandmother has only a short time left to live, is pressured by her family to not tell her while they schedule family gathering before she dies.<ref>https://variety.com/2019/film/features/10-directors-to-watch-lulu-wang-the-farewell-1203099291/</ref>  The film received critical acclaim; the film was nominated for two awards at the [[77th Golden Globe Awards]] including [[Golden Globe Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] and Awkwafina winning for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Best Actress \u2013 Musical or Comedy]], making her the first person of Asian descent to win a Golden Globe Award in any lead actress film category.<ref>https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/05/entertainment/awkwafina-golden-globes/index.html</ref>\n\n== 2020s in film ==\n\n===''Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings'' (2021)===\n''[[Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings]]'' is an upcoming 2021 [[superhero film]] based on the [[Marvel Comics]] character [[Shang-Chi]], set in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]].  Starring [[Simu Liu]] as Shang-Chi and [[Tony Leung Chiu-wai|Tony Leung]] as the [[Mandarin (character)|Mandarin]], the film will be Marvel's first superhero movie tentpole franchise with an Asian protagonist.  A film based on Shang-Chi was planned in 2006, but development did not begin in earnest until December 2018, following the success of ''Crazy Rich Asians''.<ref>https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2005-sep-06-fi-marvel6-story.html</ref><ref>https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/marvel-developing-shang-chi-movie-as-first-asian-lead-1165752</ref>  The film is expected to modernize the problematic elements of Shang-Chi and the Mandarin's comic book origins, which depicted negative stereotypes of East Asians.<ref>https://deadline.com/2018/12/shang-chi-marvel-studios-first-asian-film-superhero-dave-callaham-kevin-feige-black-panther-1202512660/</ref><ref>https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/how-shang-chi-could-be-marvels-next-black-panther-1166159</ref>  According to producer [[Kevin Feige]], ''Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings'' features a cast that is \"98 Asian\" and will \"be much more than a [[Kung fu film|Kung Fu movie]].\"<ref>https://comicbook.com/marvel/2019/12/30/marvel-studios-shang-chi-legend-ten-rings-98-percent-asian-cast-kevin-feige/?fbclid=IwAR1qFhfvNuWQjnEjH-k5TY9N7fFyjvMSkjAWxwFhdE9GXVI2dRrlTAmDiD8</ref>\n\n== 2010s television ==\n{{Unreferenced|section|date=June 2019}}\n\n=== ''Fresh Off the Boat'' (2015-2020) ===\n''[[Fresh Off the Boat]]'' is an American sitcom created by [[Nahnatchka Khan]]; a loose adaptation of author [[Eddie Huang]]'s ''Fresh off the Boat''. This show followed the life of an Asian-American family in the early 1990's. It is the first Asian-American sitcom to be featured prime time in America. It was released on February 2015 and has been renewed several times, ending with a two-part finale on February 21, 2020.  The success of this show led to other shows such as ''Dr. Ken'' to be produced for the American audience.<ref>{{Citation|title=Fresh Off the Boat|date=2019-11-08|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Fresh_Off_the_Boat&oldid=925253283|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Dr. Ken'' (2015-2017) ===\n''[[Dr. Ken]]'' is an American sitcom created by actor and writer [[Ken Jeong]]. This show followed the story of an Asian American doctor and his family. This show aired between October 2, 2015 and March 31, 2017. \n\n=== ''Kim's Convenience'' (2016-present) ===\n''[[Kim's Convenience (TV series)|''Kim's Convenience]]'' is a Canadian TV series created by [[Ins Choi]]'s 2011 play [[Kim's Convenience (play)|by the same name]]. This show revolves around the life of a family and their family-run convenience store located in Toronto. It debuted in October 2016 and has since been renewed for a fourth season. This show has been globally brought to attention with [[Netflix]] securing rights to broadcast it outside of Canada.\n\n=== ''Warrior'' (2019-present) ===\n''[[Warrior (TV series)|Warrior]]'' is an American action-drama television series executive-produced by [[Shannon Lee]] and [[Justin Lin]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cecchini |first1=Mike |title=Warrior: First Teaser for Bruce Lee Inspired TV Series |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/tv/warrior/153683/warrior-justin-lin-cinemax |website=Denofgeek |date=August 22, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Premiere\">{{cite web |last1=Li |first1=Shirley |title=Justin Lin talks bringing Bruce Lee's passion project to life in Warrior first look photos |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/02/08/justin-lin-bruce-lee-warrior-first-look/ |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=March 9, 2019 |date=February 8, 2019}}</ref>; based on an original concept and treatment by Lee's father [[Bruce Lee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/bruce-lee-warrior-tong-wars-drama-series-cinemax-justin-lin-jonathan-tropper-1202108759/|title=Bruce Lee-Inspired Tong Wars Drama \u2018Warrior\u2019 From Justin Lin & \u2018Banshee\u2019 Co-Creator Gets Cinemax Series Order|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=June 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/08/warrior-bruce-lee-inspired-crime-drama-pilot-cinemax-justin-lin-1201810722/|title=Bruce Lee-Inspired Crime Drama \u2018Warrior\u2019 From Justin Lin & \u2018Banshee\u2019 Co-Creator Gets Cinemax Pilot Order|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=August 30, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"developing\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/05/bruce-lee-crime-drama-warrior-justin-lin-cinemax-1201430580/|title=Cinemax Developing Bruce Lee-Inspired Crime Drama \u2018Warrior\u2019 From Justin Lin|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=May 21, 2015}}</ref>  The show follows a martial arts prodigy and his involvement in the [[Tong Wars]] of 1870s [[San Francisco]].  Bruce Lee developed the show in 1971, but had trouble pitching it to [[Warner Bros.]] and [[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uXOtmhA6Nvw \"From The Pierre Berton Show December 8, 1971] (comments near end of part 2 & early in part 3)</ref>  Lee's concept was retooled as ''[[Kung Fu (TV series)|Kung Fu]]'', with [[David Carradine]], a white actor, cast in the lead role; Warner Bros. gave Lee no credit.<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1975a|p=}}</ref>  The show premiered on [[Cinemax]] on April 5, 2019 and was subsequently renewed for a second season.<ref>https://deadline.com/2019/04/warrior-renewed-season-2-cinemax-tong-wars-drama-series-bruce-lee-justin-lin-1202600027/</ref>\n\n==Classic Hollywood cinema==\n===''Fu Manchu''===\nIn 1929, the character [[Fu Manchu]] made his American film debut in ''[[The Mysterious Dr. Fu Manchu]]'' played by the Swedish-American actor [[Warner Oland]]. Oland repeated the role in 1930's ''[[The Return of Dr. Fu Manchu]]'' and 1931's ''[[Daughter of the Dragon]]''. Oland appeared in character in the 1931 musical, ''[[Paramount on Parade]]'' where the Devil Doctor was seen to murder both [[Philo Vance]] and [[Sherlock Holmes]].\n\nIn 1932, [[Boris Karloff]] took over the character in the film ''[[The Mask of Fu Manchu]]''.<ref>{{IMDb title|id=0023194|title=The Mask of Fu Manchu}}</ref> The film's tone has long been considered racist and offensive,<ref name=\"mank\">Gregory William Mank, ''Hollywood Cauldron: 13 Horror Films from the Genres's Golden Age''. McFarland, 2001 (pp. 53-89); {{ISBN|0-7864-1112-0}}</ref><ref>[[Christopher Frayling]], quoted in \"Fu Manchu\", in [[Kim Newman|Newman, Kim]] (ed.), ''The BFI Companion to Horror''. London, Cassell,1996, pp. 131-32; {{ISBN|0-304-33216-X}}</ref> but that only added to its cult status alongside its humor and [[Grand Guignol]] sets and torture sequences. The film was suppressed for many years, but has since received critical re-evaluation and been released on DVD uncut.\n\n===Charlie Chan===\n{{Main|Charlie Chan}}\nIn a series of films in the 1930s and '40s, Chinese-American detective Charlie Chan was played by white actors [[Warner Oland]], [[Sidney Toler]] and [[Roland Winters]]. The Swedish-born Oland, unlike his two successors in the Chan role, actually looked somewhat Chinese, and according to his contemporaries, he did not use special makeup in the role. He also played East Asians in other films, including ''[[Shanghai Express (film)|Shanghai Express]]'', ''[[The Painted Veil (1934 film)|The Painted Veil]]'', and ''[[Werewolf of London]]''. (Decades later, Afro-European American TV actor [[Khigh Dhiegh]], though of African and European descent, was generally cast as an East Asian because of his appearance, and he was often included on lists of East Asian actors.)\n\n===''The Good Earth''===\n[[File:Luise Rainer in The Good Earth trailer 2.jpg|right|thumb]]\n''[[The Good Earth (film)|The Good Earth]]'' (1937) is a [[feature film|film]] about [[China|Chinese]] farmers who struggle to survive.<ref>[http://www.asian-studies.org/EAA/hayford.htm www.asian-studies.org] ''What's So Bad About \"The Good Earth\"'' by Charles W. Hayford.</ref> It was adapted by [[Talbot Jennings]], [[Tess Slesinger]], and [[Claudine West]] from the play by [[Donald Davis (writer)|Donald Davis]] and [[Owen Davis]], which was itself based on the 1931 novel ''[[The Good Earth]]'' by [[Nobel Prize]]-winning author [[Pearl S. Buck]]. The film was directed by [[Sidney Franklin (director)|Sidney Franklin]], [[Victor Fleming]] (uncredited) and [[Gustav Machaty]] (uncredited).\n\nThe film's budget was $2.8 million, relatively expensive for the time, and took three years to make. Although Pearl Buck intended the film to be cast with all Chinese or Chinese-American actors, the studio opted to use established American stars, tapping Europeans [[Paul Muni]] and [[Luise Rainer]] for the lead roles. Both had won Oscars the previous year; Rainer for her role in ''[[The Great Ziegfeld]]'' and Muni for the lead in ''[[The Story of Louis Pasteur]]''. When questioned about his choice of the actors, producer [[Irving Thalberg]] responded by saying, \"I'm in the business of creating illusions.\"<ref name=\"Davies2016\">{{cite book|author=Peter Ho Davies|title=The Fortunes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mOslCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT140|date=August 25, 2016|publisher=Hodder & Stoughton|isbn=978-1-4447-1056-4|page=140}}</ref>\n\n[[Anna May Wong]] had been considered a top contender for the role of O-lan, the Chinese heroine of the novel. However, because Paul Muni was a white man, the [[Hays Code]]'s [[Anti-miscegenation laws|anti-miscegenation]] rules required the actress who played his wife to be a white woman. So, MGM gave the role of O-lan to a European actress and offered Wong the role of Lotus, the story's villain. Wong refused to be the only Chinese-American, playing the only negative character, stating: \"I won't play the part. If you let me play O-lan, I'll be very glad. But you're asking me \u2013 with Chinese blood \u2013 to do the only unsympathetic role in the picture featuring an all-American cast portraying Chinese characters.\"<ref>[http://www.asiaarts.ucla.edu/article.asp?parentid=6132 www.asiaarts.ucla.edu] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090801170834/http://www.asiaarts.ucla.edu/article.asp?parentid=6132 |date=August 1, 2009 }} ''Profile of Anna May Wong: Remembering The Silent Star'' by Kenneth Quan</ref> MGM's refusal to consider Wong for this most high-profile of Chinese characters in U.S. film is remembered today as \"one of the most notorious cases of casting discrimination in the 1930s\".<ref name=\"FischerLandy2004\">{{cite book|author1=Lucy Fischer|author2=Marcia Landy|title=Stars: The Film Reader|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jl8Nu4IlqMMC&pg=PA189|year=2004|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-415-27892-8|page=189}}</ref>\n\n''The Good Earth'' was nominated for five [[Academy Awards]] including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Best Direction]] ([[Sidney Franklin (director)|Sidney Franklin]]), [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]] ([[Karl Freund]]), and [[Academy Award for Best Film Editing|Best Film Editing]] (Basil Wrangell). In addition to the [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] award (Luise Rainer), the film won for [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]].<ref>[http://www.tcm.com/thismonth/article.jsp?cid=27609&mainArticleId=196827 tcm.com] ''Spotlight: The Good Earth''</ref> The year ''The Good Earth'' came out, Wong appeared on the cover of ''[[Look (American magazine)|Look]]'' magazine's second issue, which labeled her \"The World's Most Beautiful Chinese Girl.\"<ref>Corliss, Richard. [http://content.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,1022536,00.html ''Anna May Wong Did It Right''], ''Time'' magazine, January 29, 2005, accessed May 22, 2018</ref> Stereotyped in America as a [[dragon lady]], the cover photo had her holding a dagger.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\n===''Breakfast at Tiffany's''===\n{{main|I. Y. Yunioshi}}\nThe 1961 film ''[[Breakfast at Tiffany's (film)|Breakfast at Tiffany's]]'' has been criticized for its portrayal of the character Mr. Yunioshi, Holly's bucktoothed, stereotyped Japanese neighbor. [[Mickey Rooney]] wore makeup to change his features to a caricatured approximation of a Japanese person. In the 45th anniversary edition DVD release, producer [[Richard Shepherd (producer)|Richard Shepherd]] repeatedly apologizes, saying, \"If we could just change Mickey Rooney, I'd be thrilled with the movie\".<ref name=\"makingof\">''Breakfast at Tiffany's'': The Making of a Classic</ref> Director [[Blake Edwards]] stated, \"Looking back, I wish I had never done it&nbsp;... and I would give anything to be able to recast it, but it's there, and onward and upward\".<ref name=\"makingof\"/> In a 2008 interview about the film, 87-year-old Rooney said he was heartbroken about the criticism and that he had never received any complaints about his portrayal of the character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sacbee.com/121/story/1220270.html |title=Sacramento Bee: Racism in reel life |last=Calvert |first=Bruce |date=September 9, 2008 |publisher=sacbee.com |accessdate=2008-11-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121034154/http://www.sacbee.com/121/story/1220270.html |archivedate=November 21, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n=== ''Sixteen Candles'' ===\nThe 1984 American film ''[[Sixteen Candles]]'' has been criticized for the character of [[Long Duk Dong]]. This Asian character became an \"Asian American stereotype for a new generation\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/codeswitch/2015/02/06/384307677/whats-so-cringe-worthy-about-long-duk-dong-in-sixteen-candles|title=What's So 'Cringeworthy' About Long Duk Dong in 'Sixteen Candles'?|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref> Long Duk Dong displayed a variety of stereotypes in the film such being socially awkward and difficult to understand, and the \"lecherous but sexually inept loser\"<ref name=\":1\" />. The idea of Asians being more feminine and therefore \"weaker\" is further exemplified through Long Duk Dong's romantic relationship with one of the characters in the film. He assumes the more feminine role while the American girl becomes the more masculine of two in the relationship. This shows how the Asian characters are far inferior compared to their Western counterparts.\n\n==Theater==\n\"Yellowface\" in theatre has been called \"the practice of white actors donning overdone face paint and costumes that serves as a caricatured representation of traditional Asian garb.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dallas Summer Musicals' THE KING AND I Casting Causes Controversy |url = http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Dallas-Summer-Musicals-THE-KING-AND-I-Casting-Causes-Controversy-20150125|website = BroadwayWorld.com|accessdate = 2015-11-25}}</ref> Founded in 2011, an organization known as, \"The Asian American Performers Action Coalition\" or the AAPAC work in an effort to, \"expand the perception of Asian American performers in order to increase their access to and representation on New York City's stages.\" This group works to address and discuss \"Yellowface\" controversies and occurrences.<ref>{{Cite web|title = AAPAC|url = http://www.aapacnyc.org/|website = AAPAC|accessdate = 2015-11-25}}</ref>{{non-primary source needed|date=November 2015}}\n\n===''Miss Saigon''===\n{{main|Miss Saigon}}\n''Miss Saigon'', a musical with music by Claude-Michel Sch\u00f6nberg, lyrics by Alain Boublil and Richard Maltby, Jr. and book by Boublil and Sch\u00f6nberg, is a modern adaptation of Giacomo Puccini's opera \"Madame Butterfly\". Miss Saigon tells the story of a doomed romance involving a Vietnamese woman and an American soldier set in the time of the Vietnam War.<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Heat Is On: Touring Production of Miss Saigon Met With Protests at Minnesota's Ordway Theater|url = http://www.playbill.com/news/article/the-heat-is-on-touring-production-of-miss-saigon-met-with-protests-at-minne-210375|website = Playbill|accessdate = 2015-11-25}}</ref>\n\nWhen ''Miss Saigon'' premiered at the Theatre Royal, Drury Lane, London on September 20, 1989, Welsh actor [[Jonathan Pryce]] wore heavy prosthetic eyelids and skin darkening cream in playing The Engineer, a mixed-race French-Vietnamese pimp.<ref>{{Cite web|title = \"A Certain Slant\": A Brief History of Hollywood Yellowface - Bright Lights Film Journal|url = http://brightlightsfilm.com/certain-slant-brief-history-hollywood-yellowface/#.VlKNx2SrS2y|website = Bright Lights Film Journal|accessdate = 2015-11-25|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://archive.is/20140503000205/http://brightlightsfilm.com/certain-slant-brief-history-hollywood-yellowface/#.VlKNx2SrS2y|archivedate = May 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOnce the London production came to Broadway in 1990, Pryce was slated to reprise his role as The Engineer, causing a major rift in American theater circles and sparking public outcry. Tony Award-winning playwright [[David Henry Hwang]] wrote a letter to the Actors' Equity Association protesting this portrayal of a Eurasian character being played by a White actor.<ref>{{Cite news|title = 'Yellow Face' at Theatre J explores Asian representation in the theater world|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/express/wp/2014/01/30/yellow-face-at-theatre-j-explores-asian-representation-in-the-theater-world/|newspaper = The Washington Post|date = January 30, 2014|access-date = 2015-11-25|issn = 0190-8286|language = en-US|first = Christina|last = Cauterucci}}</ref>\n\nDespite these protests, Pryce performed the Engineer to great acclaim and ''Miss Saigon'' became one of Broadway's longest-running hits.<ref>{{cite news|title = David Henry Hwang: racial casting has evolved \u2013 and so have my opinions|url = https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2014/may/12/david-henry-hwang-miss-saigon-yellow-face-racial-casting|work=The Guardian|location=London|accessdate = 2015-11-25|first = David Henry|last = Hwang}}</ref>\n\n===''The Mikado''===\n{{main|The Mikado}}\n''[[The Mikado]]'' is a comic operetta, with music by [[Arthur Sullivan]] and libretto by [[W. S. Gilbert]], premiered in 1885 in London and still performed frequently in the English-speaking world and beyond.<ref>Kenrick, John. [http://www.musicals101.com/gilbert3.htm \"The Gilbert & Sullivan Story: Part III\"], Musicals101.com, accessed November 11, 2016</ref><ref name=Steinberg>Steinberg, Neil.  [http://www.suntimes.com/news/steinberg/2706603-452/mikado-production-opera-chicago-lyric.html \"Updated ''Mikado'' promises to be as rousing as ever\"].  ''Chicago Sun-Times'', December 6, 2010</ref> In setting the opera in a fictionalized 19th century Japan, Gilbert used the veneer of Far Eastern exoticism to soften the impact of his pointed satire of British institutions and politics.<ref name=Steinberg/><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20061029085114/http://www.lyricoperasandiego.com/Education/MikadoGenesis.htm \"Mikado Genesis\"], Lyric Opera San Diego</ref>\n\nNumerous 21st century US productions of ''The Mikado'' have been criticized for the use of Yellowface in their casting: New York (2004 and 2015), Los Angeles (2007 and 2009), Boston (2007), Austin (2011), Denver (2013), and Seattle (2014)<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = Stereotypes in 'The Mikado' Stir Controversy in Seattle - NBC News|url = https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/stereotypes-mikado-stir-controversy-seattle-n157306|website = NBC News|accessdate = 2015-11-25}}</ref> The press noted that the Seattle Gilbert & Sullivan Society cast the 10 principal roles and the chorus with white actors, with the exception of two Latino actors.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2015, the [[New York Gilbert and Sullivan Players]] cancelled a production of ''The Mikado'' that was set to feature their repertory company of mostly White actors, due to complaints from the East Asian-American community.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Following Outcry from the Asian Community, The Mikado (With Caucasian Actors) Canceled|url = http://www.playbill.com/news/article/following-outcry-from-the-asian-community-the-mikado-with-caucasian-actors-canceled-362959|website = Playbill|accessdate = 2015-11-25}}</ref> The company redesigned its production in collaboration with an advisory group of East Asian-American theater professionals and debuted the new concept in 2016,<ref>[http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/New-York-Gilbert-Sullivan-Players-Reveals-Concepts-for-Reimagined-THE-MIKADO-Kelvin-Moon-Loh-Joins-Creative-Team-20161006# \"New York Gilbert & Sullivan Players Reveals Concepts for Reimagined ''The Mikado''; Kelvin Moon Loh Joins Creative Team!\"], BroadwayWorld.com, October 6, 2016</ref> receiving a warm review in ''The New York Times''.<ref>Fonseca-Wollheim, Corinna da. [https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/30/arts/music/review-gilbert-and-sullivan-the-mikado.html \"Is ''The Mikado'' Too Politically Incorrect to Be Fixed? Maybe Not.\"], December 30, 2016</ref> After [[Lamplighters Music Theatre]] of San Francisco planned a 2016 production, objections by the East Asian-American community prompted them to re-set the operetta in [[Duchy of Milan|Renaissance-era Milan]], replacing all references to Japan with Milan.<ref>Tran, Diep. [http://www.americantheatre.org/2016/04/20/building-a-better-mikado-minus-the-yellowface \"Building a Better ''Mikado'', Minus the Yellowface\"], ''American Theatre'', April 20, 2016</ref> Reviewers felt that the change resolved the issue.<ref>Kosman, Joshua. [http://www.sfgate.com/music/article/Lamplighters-transplanted-Mikado-retains-9129437.php \"Lamplighters' transplanted ''Mikado'' retains its charm\"], ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'', August 8, 2016; and Hurwitt, Sam. [http://www.mercurynews.com/entertainment/ci_30220924/review-guilt-free-mikado-unveiled-by-lamplighters \"Review: Guilt-free ''Mikado'' unveiled by Lamplighters\"], ''[[The Mercury News]]'', August 8, 2016</ref>\n\n===''The King and I''===\n{{main|The King and I}}\n''The King and I'' is a musical by Richard Rodgers (composer) and Oscar von Hammerstein II (lyricist). Based on the 1944 novel ''Anna and the King of Siam'' by Margaret Landon, the story illustrates the clash of Eastern and Western cultures by relaying the experiences of Anna, a British schoolteacher hired as part of the King's drive to modernize his country. The relationship between the King and Anna is marked by conflict and constant bickering throughout the musical, as well as by a love that neither can confess.\n\nThe 2015 Dallas Summer Musical's production of the musical caused controversy in the casting of a European-American actor as King Mongkut. In an open letter to Dallas Summer Musicals, the AAPAC criticized the choice, saying \"the casting of a white King dramaturgically undermines a story about a clash between Western and Eastern cultures\"; moreover, \"Asian impersonation denies Asians our own subjecthood. It situates all the power within a Caucasian-centric world view.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dallas Summer Musicals' THE KING AND I Casting Causes Controversy|url = http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Dallas-Summer-Musicals-THE-KING-AND-I-Casting-Causes-Controversy-20150125|website = BroadwayWorld.com|accessdate = 2015-11-25}}</ref>\n\n==Other examples in Western media==\n{{Main|Examples of yellowface}}\n[[File:Nancy Kwan & David Carradine in Kung Fu.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Actors [[Nancy Kwan]] and [[David Carradine]] in the 1970s TV series, ''[[Kung Fu (TV series)|Kung Fu]]''.]]\nA prominent example of the [[Whitewashing in film|whitewashing]] of Asian roles is the 1970s TV series, ''[[Kung Fu (TV series)|Kung Fu]]'', in which the leading character \u2013 a Chinese monk and martial arts master who fled China after having accidentally slain the emperor's nephew \u2013 is portrayed by European-American actor, [[David Carradine]]. The film ''[[Dragon: The Bruce Lee Story]]'' describes to some extent the struggles that ensued when Hollywood moguls attempted to cast [[Bruce Lee]] in the starring role of Caine but were overruled. The American film adaptation of the manga series [[Ghost in the Shell (manga)]] faced controversy over its casting of [[Scarlett Johansson]] as the main character Major who is depicted as Japanese looking in the anime and manga. American actress [[Emma Stone]] played a half-Asian character in the film [[Aloha (2015 film)]]. In the film [[Cloud Atlas (film)]] every major male character in the Korean story line was played by a non-Asian actor made up in yellow face makeup<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/oct/26/cloud-atlas-under-fire-yellowface|title=Cloud Atlas under fire for casting white actors in 'yellowface' makeup|last=Brooks|first=Xan|date=2012-10-26|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-06-12|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>.\n\n[[Michael Derrick Hudson]], an American poet, used a Chinese female ''[[nom de plume]]''.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Film}}\n*[[Blackface]] and [[Blackface in contemporary art]]\n*[[Covert racism]]\n*[[Examples of yellowface]]\n*''[[Reel Bad Arabs]]''\n*''[[Reel Injun]]''\n*[[Stereotypes of East Asians in the United States]]\n*[[Whiteface (performance)]]\n* [[Whitewashing in film]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite book |first=Graham Russell|last=Hodges|title=Anna May Wong: From Laundryman's Daughter to Hollywood Legend|url=https://archive.org/details/annamaywongfroml0000hodg|url-access=registration|location=New York|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|date=2004}}\n*{{cite book |first=Gina|last=Marchetti|title=Romance and the \"Yellow Peril\" Race, Sex, and Discursive Strategies in Hollywood Fiction|url=https://archive.org/details/romanceyellowper00gina|url-access=registration|location=Berkeley|publisher=University of California Press|date=1993}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Ito|first=Robert B.|url=http://brightlightsfilm.com/certain-slant-brief-history-hollywood-yellowface/|title=A Certain Slant: A Brief History of Hollywood Yellowface|journal=[[Bright Lights Film Journal]]|accessdate=May 2, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140503000205/http://brightlightsfilm.com/certain-slant-brief-history-hollywood-yellowface/|archivedate=May 3, 2014}}\n* {{cite book |last=Moon |first=Krystyn R. |title= Yellowface: Creating the Chinese in American Popular Music and Performance, 1850s\u20131920s (New Brunswick, N.J.: Rutgers University Press, 2006).}}\n* {{cite book |last=Paul |first=John Steven |title=Misreading the Chinese Character: Images of the Chinese in Euroamerican Drama to 1925 (review) Asian Theatre Journal|volume=18|issue=1|pages=117\u2013119|date=Spring 2001|publisher=University of Hawai'i Press }}\n* {{cite book |last=Prasso |first=Sheridan |title= The Asian Mystique: dragon ladies, geisha girls, & our fantasies of the exotic orient |date=2005 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Wang|first=Yiman|editor=Catherine Russell|title=Camera Obscura 60: New Women of the Silent Screen: China, Japan, Hollywood|chapter=The Art of Screen Passing: [[Anna May Wong]]'s Yellow Yellowface Performance in the Art Deco Era|pages=159\u2013191|year=2005|publisher=Duke University Press|location=Durham, N.C.|isbn=978-0-8223-6624-9}}\n* Metzger, Sean. \"Charles Parsloe's Chinese Fetish: An Example of Yellowface Performance in Nineteenth-Century American Melodrama.\" Theatre Journal 56, no. 4 (2004): 627-51. <nowiki>https://www.jstor.org/stable/25069532</nowiki>.\n* Young, Cynthia Ann. \"AfroAsian Encounters: Culture, History, Politics (review).\" Journal of Asian American Studies 10, no. 3 (2007): 316-18. {{doi|10.1353/jaas.2007.0033}}.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080724174617/http://www.deepfocusproductions.com/HollywoodChinese ''Hollywood Chinese''], a 2007 documentary film about the portrayals of Chinese men and women in Hollywood productions\n* [http://www.imdiversity.com/Villages/Asian/arts_culture_media/archives/winfrey_yellowface_asians_hollywood.asp \"Yellowface: Asians on White Screens\"], by Yayoi Lena Winfrey, ''IM Diversity.com''\n* [https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20101212005020/http://www.brightlightsfilm.com/18/18_yellow.html \"A Certain Slant\"] by Robert B. Ito, ''Bright Lights Film Journal''\n* [http://www.goldsea.com/Mediawatch/mediawatch.html \"Monitoring Asians in the American mass media\"] at Asian American Media Watch\n* [http://www.tcm.com/thismonth/article/?cid=201608&mainArticleId=196827 \"Asian Images in Film: Introduction\"] at TCM\n* [https://www.npr.org/sections/codeswitch/2014/08/14/339559520/roundtable-the-past-and-present-of-yellowface \"Roundtable: The Past and Present of 'Yellowface'\"], at [[NPR]]\n\n[[Category:History of racism in the cinema of the United States]]\n[[Category:Cultural appropriation]]\n[[Category:Asian-American culture]]\n[[Category:Asian-American issues]]\n[[Category:Ethnic and racial stereotypes in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portrayal_of_East_Asians_in_American_film_and_theater"}
{"title_page": "Yadviga Poplavskaya", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Yadviga Poplavskaya\n|image = \u041f\u043e\u043f\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u042f\u0434\u0432\u0438\u0433\u0430 \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430.JPG\n| birth_name      = Yadviga Konstantinovna Poplavskaya\n| background      = solo_singer\n| birth_date            = {{birth date and age|1949|5|1|df=yes}}\n|birth_place = [[Dalidavichy]], [[BSSR]]\n| genre = [[Estrada (music genre)|Estrada]], [[Popular music]]\n| occupation = Singer-songwriter\n| instrument = vocals, piano\n| years_active = 1971-present\n| associated_acts = [[Verasy]]\n}}\n\n'''Yadviga Konstantinovna Poplavskaya''' ({{lang-be|\u042f\u0434\u0432\u0456\u0433\u0430 \u041a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0456\u043d\u0430\u045e\u043d\u0430 \u041f\u0430\u043f\u043b\u0430\u045e\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f}}, {{lang-ru|\u042f\u0434\u0432\u0438\u0433\u0430 \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u041f\u043e\u043f\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f}} born 1 May 1949<ref>[http://news.tut.by/culture/136039.html \u042f\u0434\u0432\u0438\u0433\u0430 \u041f\u043e\u043f\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f: \u00ab\u041f\u0430\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442 \u0432\u0440\u0435\u0442\u00a0\u2014 \u043c\u043d\u0435 28!\u00bb]</ref><ref>[http://www.kp.ru/daily/24287.5/482222/ \u042f\u0434\u0432\u0438\u0433\u0430 \u041f\u041e\u041f\u041b\u0410\u0412\u0421\u041a\u0410\u042f: \u00ab\u041f\u0430\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442 \u0432\u0440\u0435\u0442\u00a0\u2014 \u043c\u043d\u0435 28!\u00bb]</ref>) is a Soviet and [[Belarus]]ian singer, member of the first ensemble [[Verasy]] and a People\u2019s Artist of Belarus (2005).\n\n== Biography ==\nBorn into a musical family, her father, choirmaster Konstantin Poplavsky, together with Gennady Tsitovich created Belarusian State Folk Choir.<ref>[http://nn.by/?c=ar&i=127580&lang=ru \u042f\u0434\u0432\u0438\u0433\u0430 \u041f\u043e\u043f\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043e\u0442\u043c\u0435\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u042e\u0431\u0438\u043b\u0435\u0439]</ref>\n\nPoplavskaya graduated from [[Belarusian State Academy of Music|Belarusian Conservatory]] twice - in piano (1972) and separation of composition (1988). In 1971, she was among the founders of the Minsk-based [[Verasy|VIA \"Verasy\"]]. In the ensemble she played keyboards, sung vocals, and wrote arrangements. In 1973, [[Alexander Tikhanovich]] came to the ensemble (bass guitar, vocal, trumpet), who later became the husband of Poplavskaya.\n\nIn 1986, Poplavskaya and Tikhanovich were forced to part ways with the Verasy ensemble, and in 1987 they got into the just-organized State Orchestra of Belarus under the direction of Mikhail Finberg.\n\nAfter winning the 1988 [[Pesnya goda]] with the song \"Happy Occasion\" (music [[Eduard Khanok]], words [[Larisa Rubalskaya]]), Poplavskaya and Tihanovich created a duet of the same name, and later on the basis of a duet a group of the same name was formed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://budzma.by/news/top-25-zhanchyn-muzyki-belarusi.html|title=25 \u0436\u0430\u043d\u0447\u044b\u043d, \u0431\u0435\u0437 \u044f\u043a\u0456\u0445 \u043d\u0435 \u0431\u044b\u043b\u043e \u0431 \u0431\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0440\u0443\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0439 \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0456 (+ \u0430\u045e\u0434\u044b\u0451)|last=\u0411\u0443\u0434\u043a\u0456\u043d|first=\u0421\u044f\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0439|date=2013-05-02|website=|publisher=[[Budzma Belarusians!]]|language=be|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404140113/https://budzma.by/news/top-25-zhanchyn-muzyki-belarusi.html|archivedate=2020-04-04|accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> In the group Lucky Chance, she arranged, played keyboards and was a vocalist. The group participated in the Golden Lyre festival (Belarus), toured in Russia, Belarus, Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia, Germany, Yugoslavia, Poland, Hungary, Finland, France, Canada and Israel.\n\nIn 1988, together with her husband, she organized The Theater of Songs by Yadviga Poplavskaya and Alexander Tikhanovich, through whose studio many young Belarusian performers went through such as [[Alexander Solodukha]], [[Lyapis Trubetskoy]] and others.\n\nThe song \u201cChara\u045enitsa\u201d was included in the repertoire of the duet Poplavskaya and Tihanovich (as well as the \u201cChuk i Gek\u201d group, the song and dance ensemble of the Armed Forces of Belarus). For the arrangement, Poplavskaya and Sergey Sukhomlin became the winners in the nomination \u201cThe Best Arranger of the Year\u201d.<ref>[http://www.zvyazda.minsk.by/second.html?r=5&p=21&archiv=09072005 \u0410\u041d\u0422\u0410\u041b\u041e\u0413I\u042f \u0411\u0415\u041b\u0410\u0420\u0423\u0421\u041a\u0410\u0419 \u041f\u0415\u0421\u041dI.\u00a0\u2014 \u2116\u00a0126 (25458). 9 \u043bi\u043f\u0435\u043d\u044f 2005\u00a0\u0433. (\u0410\u0420\u0425I\u040e)]</ref>\n\n=== Dispute with Eduard Khanok ===\n[[Eduard Khanok]] declared on 28 April 2017 that his copyrights are grossly violated and, as the holder of exclusive rights, from 26 April, he forbids the performance and transmission of works from the repertoire of Poplavskaya and Tihanovich \u201cLucky Chance\u201d to the words of [[Larisa Rubalskaya]]; \u201cI live with my grandmother\u201d in the words of [[Igor Shaferan]]; \u201cZavirukha\u201d to the words of Gennady Buravkin; \"Robin heard a voice\" on the words of [[Anatoly Poperechny]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u0425\u0430\u043d\u043e\u043a \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0438\u043b \u042f\u0440\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u0438 \u041f\u043e\u043f\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0438\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0438 \u043f\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0438 \u0438 \u0433\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0430\u0442\u044c \u043d\u0430 \u043d\u0438\u0445 \u0432 \u0441\u0443\u0434|url=https://news.tut.by/culture/541364.html|work=TUT.BY|accessdate=2017-12-31|language=ru-RU}}</ref>\n\nCommenting on the situation, the Poplavskaya's daughter, the singer Anastasia Tihanovich, revealed the intention of Khanok to receive for the right to perform his songs in the future $25,000 and the impossibility of paying them due to the large expenses for the treatment of her father, Alexander Tikhanovich.<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u0425\u0430\u043d\u043e\u043a \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0438\u043b \u042f\u0440\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u0438 \u041f\u043e\u043f\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u0435\u0442\u044c \u0435\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0438!|first=\u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0439 \u041c\u0410\u041b\u0418\u041d\u041e\u0412\u0421\u041a\u0418\u0419 {{!}} \u0421\u0430\u0439\u0442 \u00ab\u041a\u043e\u043c\u0441\u043e\u043c\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439|last=\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0434\u044b\u00bb|url=https://www.kp.by/daily/26673.7/3695227/|work=KP.BY - \u0441\u0430\u0439\u0442 \u00ab\u041a\u043e\u043c\u0441\u043e\u043c\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0434\u044b\u00bb|date=2017-04-29|accessdate=2017-12-31|language=ru}}</ref>\n\nKhanok also stated that he intends to sue Poplavskaya \u201cin connection with the protection of honor, dignity and business reputation\",<ref>{{Cite news|title=\"\u042d\u0442\u043e \u043d\u0430\u0437\u044b\u0432\u0430\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0432\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\". \u041a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043e\u0437\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u0425\u0430\u043d\u043e\u043a \u043d\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043d \u0441\u0443\u0434\u0438\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f \u0441 \u043f\u0435\u0432\u0446\u0430\u043c\u0438|url=http://naviny.by/article/20170429/1493466997-eto-nazyvaetsya-vorovstvo-kompozitor-hanok-nameren-suditsya-s-pevcami|work=naviny.by|date=2017-04-29|accessdate=2017-12-31}}</ref> noting that not a single Belarusian newspaper, which wrote about the funeral of Tikhanovich, mentioned its authorship \u201cRobin\u201d.<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u042d\u0434\u0443\u0430\u0440\u0434 \u0425\u0430\u043d\u043e\u043a \u043e \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0444\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0442\u0435: \u041e\u043d\u0438 \u0435\u0441\u043b\u0438 \u0438 \u0443\u043f\u043e\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u043c\u0435\u043d\u044f \u043d\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0446\u0435\u0440\u0442\u0430\u0445 \u043a\u0430\u043a \u0430\u0432\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0430 \u043f\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043d, \u0442\u043e \u0441\u043a\u0432\u043e\u0437\u044c \u0437\u0443\u0431\u044b|first=\u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0439 \u041c\u0410\u041b\u0418\u041d\u041e\u0412\u0421\u041a\u0418\u0419 {{!}} \u0421\u0430\u0439\u0442 \u00ab\u041a\u043e\u043c\u0441\u043e\u043c\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439|last=\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0434\u044b\u00bb|url=https://www.kp.by/daily/26673.7/3695357/|work=KP.BY - \u0441\u0430\u0439\u0442 \u00ab\u041a\u043e\u043c\u0441\u043e\u043c\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0434\u044b\u00bb|date=2017-04-29|accessdate=2017-12-31|language=ru}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 May 2017, Khanok refused to sue, expressing the opinion that it was enough for him to ban his songs.<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u0425\u0430\u043d\u043e\u043a \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b\u0441\u044f \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0442\u044c \u0432 \u0441\u0443\u0434. \u042e\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442: \u043f\u043e \u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0438\u0437 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0435\u043d\u0437\u0438\u0439 \u0443 \u043d\u0435\u0433\u043e \u0431\u044b\u043b\u0438 \u0448\u0430\u043d\u0441\u044b \u043d\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0431\u0435\u0434\u0443|url=https://news.tut.by/culture/541845.html|work=TUT.BY|accessdate=2017-12-31|language=ru-RU}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 July 2017, Khanok changed his decision and again shared with journalists the intention to protect his \u201chonor, dignity and business reputation\u201d in court, despite the fact that the ban was not violated.<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u042d\u0434\u0443\u0430\u0440\u0434 \u0425\u0430\u043d\u043e\u043a \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0443\u043c\u0430\u043b \u0438 \u0432\u0441\u0435-\u0442\u0430\u043a\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0432 \u0441\u0443\u0434 \u043d\u0430 \u042f\u0434\u0432\u0438\u0433\u0443 \u041f\u043e\u043f\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0443\u044e \u0438 \u0410\u043d\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0438\u044f \u042f\u0440\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e|url=https://news.tut.by/culture/550121.html|work=TUT.BY|accessdate=2017-12-31|language=ru-RU}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:\u0422\u0438\u0445\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0410\u043d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0438\u044f.JPG|thumb|170px|Anastasia Tikhanovich]]\nPoplavskaya was married to [[Alexander Tikhanovich]]<ref>[http://nn.by/?c=ar&i=127580&lang=ru \u042f\u0434\u0432\u0438\u0433\u0430 \u041f\u043e\u043f\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043e\u0442\u043c\u0435\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u042e\u0431\u0438\u043b\u0435\u0439]</ref> until his death on 28 January 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://eng.belta.by/president/view/lukashenko-expresses-condolences-over-death-of-alexander-tikhanovich-98308-2017/|title=Lukashenko expresses condolences over death of Alexander Tikhanovich|accessdate=31 January 2017}}</ref> Together, they had a daughter, Anastasia (born 1980).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vsr.mil.by/2017/03/11/anastasiya-tixanovich-ya-rada-chto-poyavilas-na-svet-imenno-v-etoj-seme/|title=\u0410\u043d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0438\u044f \u0422\u0438\u0445\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447: \"\u042f \u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430, \u0447\u0442\u043e \u043f\u043e\u044f\u0432\u0438\u043b\u0430\u0441\u044c \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0432\u0435\u0442 \u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e \u0432 \u044d\u0442\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0435\u043c\u044c\u0435\"|accessdate=2017-11-10}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\nAlbums with the ensemble \"Verasy\":\n* \u201cOur disco\u201d\n* \u201cMusic for all\u201d\n\nAlbums of Yadviga Poplavskaya and Alexander Tikhanovich:\n* \u201cHappy Occasion\u201d ([[Melodiya|Firm Melody]], LP, 1989)\n* \u201cMusic of Love\u201d ([[Melodiya|Firm Melody]]; Eddy (Minsk), LP, 1995)\n* \"From\" Robin \"to ...\" (Eddy. CD, 1997)\n* \u201cLife is a wonderful moment\u201d (Master Sound, CD, 1997)\n* \u201cLove is Destiny\u201d ([[West Records]], 2008)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poplavskaya, Yadviga}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Valozhyn District]]\n[[Category:Soviet female singers]]\n[[Category:Belarusian female singers]]\n[[Category:People's Artists of Belarus]]\n[[Category:20th-century women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Yadviga Poplavskaya\n|image = \u041f\u043e\u043f\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u042f\u0434\u0432\u0438\u0433\u0430 \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430.JPG\n| birth_name      = Yadviga Konstantinovna Poplavskaya\n| background      = solo_singer\n| birth_date            = {{birth date and age|1949|5|1|df=yes}}\n|birth_place = [[Dalidavichy]], [[BSSR]]\n| genre = [[Estrada (music genre)|Estrada]], [[Popular music]]\n| occupation = Singer-songwriter\n| instrument = vocals, piano\n| years_active = 1971-present\n| associated_acts = [[Verasy]]\n}}\n\n'''Yadviga Konstantinovna Poplavskaya''' ({{lang-be|\u042f\u0434\u0432\u0456\u0433\u0430 \u041a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0456\u043d\u0430\u045e\u043d\u0430 \u041f\u0430\u043f\u043b\u0430\u045e\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f}}, {{lang-ru|\u042f\u0434\u0432\u0438\u0433\u0430 \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u041f\u043e\u043f\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f}} born 1 May 1949<ref>[http://news.tut.by/culture/136039.html \u042f\u0434\u0432\u0438\u0433\u0430 \u041f\u043e\u043f\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f: \u00ab\u041f\u0430\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442 \u0432\u0440\u0435\u0442\u00a0\u2014 \u043c\u043d\u0435 28!\u00bb]</ref><ref>[http://www.kp.ru/daily/24287.5/482222/ \u042f\u0434\u0432\u0438\u0433\u0430 \u041f\u041e\u041f\u041b\u0410\u0412\u0421\u041a\u0410\u042f: \u00ab\u041f\u0430\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442 \u0432\u0440\u0435\u0442\u00a0\u2014 \u043c\u043d\u0435 28!\u00bb]</ref>) is a Soviet and [[Belarus]]ian singer, member of the first ensemble [[Verasy]] and a People\u2019s Artist of Belarus (2005).\n\n== Biography ==\nBorn into a musical family, her father, choirmaster Konstantin Poplavsky, together with Gennady Tsitovich created Belarusian State Folk Choir.<ref>[http://nn.by/?c=ar&i=127580&lang=ru \u042f\u0434\u0432\u0438\u0433\u0430 \u041f\u043e\u043f\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043e\u0442\u043c\u0435\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u042e\u0431\u0438\u043b\u0435\u0439]</ref>\n\nPoplavskaya graduated from [[Belarusian State Academy of Music|Belarusian Conservatory]] twice - in piano (1972) and separation of composition (1988). In 1971, she was among the founders of the Minsk-based [[Verasy|VIA \"Verasy\"]]. In the ensemble she played keyboards, sung vocals, and wrote arrangements. In 1973, [[Alexander Tikhanovich]] came to the ensemble (bass guitar, vocal, trumpet), who later became the husband of Poplavskaya.\n\nIn 1986, Poplavskaya and Tikhanovich were forced to part ways with the Verasy ensemble, and in 1987 they got into the just-organized State Orchestra of Belarus under the direction of Mikhail Finberg.\n\nAfter winning the 1988 [[Pesnya goda]] with the song \"Happy Occasion\" (music [[Eduard Khanok]], words [[Larisa Rubalskaya]]), Poplavskaya and Tihanovich created a duet of the same name, and later on the basis of a duet a group of the same name was formed. In the group Lucky Chance, she arranged, played keyboards and was a vocalist. The group participated in the Golden Lyre festival (Belarus), toured in Russia, Belarus, Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia, Germany, Yugoslavia, Poland, Hungary, Finland, France, Canada and Israel.\n\nIn 1988, together with her husband, she organized The Theater of Songs by Yadviga Poplavskaya and Alexander Tikhanovich, through whose studio many young Belarusian performers went through such as [[Alexander Solodukha]], [[Lyapis Trubetskoy]] and others.\n\nThe song \u201cChara\u045enitsa\u201d was included in the repertoire of the duet Poplavskaya and Tihanovich (as well as the \u201cChuk i Gek\u201d group, the song and dance ensemble of the Armed Forces of Belarus). For the arrangement, Poplavskaya and Sergey Sukhomlin became the winners in the nomination \u201cThe Best Arranger of the Year\u201d.<ref>[http://www.zvyazda.minsk.by/second.html?r=5&p=21&archiv=09072005 \u0410\u041d\u0422\u0410\u041b\u041e\u0413I\u042f \u0411\u0415\u041b\u0410\u0420\u0423\u0421\u041a\u0410\u0419 \u041f\u0415\u0421\u041dI.\u00a0\u2014 \u2116\u00a0126 (25458). 9 \u043bi\u043f\u0435\u043d\u044f 2005\u00a0\u0433. (\u0410\u0420\u0425I\u040e)]</ref>\n\n=== Dispute with Eduard Khanok ===\n[[Eduard Khanok]] declared on 28 April 2017 that his copyrights are grossly violated and, as the holder of exclusive rights, from 26 April, he forbids the performance and transmission of works from the repertoire of Poplavskaya and Tihanovich \u201cLucky Chance\u201d to the words of [[Larisa Rubalskaya]]; \u201cI live with my grandmother\u201d in the words of [[Igor Shaferan]]; \u201cZavirukha\u201d to the words of Gennady Buravkin; \"Robin heard a voice\" on the words of [[Anatoly Poperechny]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u0425\u0430\u043d\u043e\u043a \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0438\u043b \u042f\u0440\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u0438 \u041f\u043e\u043f\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0438\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0438 \u043f\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0438 \u0438 \u0433\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0430\u0442\u044c \u043d\u0430 \u043d\u0438\u0445 \u0432 \u0441\u0443\u0434|url=https://news.tut.by/culture/541364.html|work=TUT.BY|accessdate=2017-12-31|language=ru-RU}}</ref>\n\nCommenting on the situation, the Poplavskaya's daughter, the singer Anastasia Tihanovich, revealed the intention of Khanok to receive for the right to perform his songs in the future $25,000 and the impossibility of paying them due to the large expenses for the treatment of her father, Alexander Tikhanovich.<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u0425\u0430\u043d\u043e\u043a \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0438\u043b \u042f\u0440\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u0438 \u041f\u043e\u043f\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u0435\u0442\u044c \u0435\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0438!|first=\u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0439 \u041c\u0410\u041b\u0418\u041d\u041e\u0412\u0421\u041a\u0418\u0419 {{!}} \u0421\u0430\u0439\u0442 \u00ab\u041a\u043e\u043c\u0441\u043e\u043c\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439|last=\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0434\u044b\u00bb|url=https://www.kp.by/daily/26673.7/3695227/|work=KP.BY - \u0441\u0430\u0439\u0442 \u00ab\u041a\u043e\u043c\u0441\u043e\u043c\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0434\u044b\u00bb|date=2017-04-29|accessdate=2017-12-31|language=ru}}</ref>\n\nKhanok also stated that he intends to sue Poplavskaya \u201cin connection with the protection of honor, dignity and business reputation\",<ref>{{Cite news|title=\"\u042d\u0442\u043e \u043d\u0430\u0437\u044b\u0432\u0430\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0432\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\". \u041a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043e\u0437\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u0425\u0430\u043d\u043e\u043a \u043d\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043d \u0441\u0443\u0434\u0438\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f \u0441 \u043f\u0435\u0432\u0446\u0430\u043c\u0438|url=http://naviny.by/article/20170429/1493466997-eto-nazyvaetsya-vorovstvo-kompozitor-hanok-nameren-suditsya-s-pevcami|work=naviny.by|date=2017-04-29|accessdate=2017-12-31}}</ref> noting that not a single Belarusian newspaper, which wrote about the funeral of Tikhanovich, mentioned its authorship \u201cRobin\u201d.<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u042d\u0434\u0443\u0430\u0440\u0434 \u0425\u0430\u043d\u043e\u043a \u043e \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0444\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0442\u0435: \u041e\u043d\u0438 \u0435\u0441\u043b\u0438 \u0438 \u0443\u043f\u043e\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u043c\u0435\u043d\u044f \u043d\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0446\u0435\u0440\u0442\u0430\u0445 \u043a\u0430\u043a \u0430\u0432\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0430 \u043f\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043d, \u0442\u043e \u0441\u043a\u0432\u043e\u0437\u044c \u0437\u0443\u0431\u044b|first=\u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0439 \u041c\u0410\u041b\u0418\u041d\u041e\u0412\u0421\u041a\u0418\u0419 {{!}} \u0421\u0430\u0439\u0442 \u00ab\u041a\u043e\u043c\u0441\u043e\u043c\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439|last=\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0434\u044b\u00bb|url=https://www.kp.by/daily/26673.7/3695357/|work=KP.BY - \u0441\u0430\u0439\u0442 \u00ab\u041a\u043e\u043c\u0441\u043e\u043c\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0434\u044b\u00bb|date=2017-04-29|accessdate=2017-12-31|language=ru}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 May 2017, Khanok refused to sue, expressing the opinion that it was enough for him to ban his songs.<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u0425\u0430\u043d\u043e\u043a \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b\u0441\u044f \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0442\u044c \u0432 \u0441\u0443\u0434. \u042e\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442: \u043f\u043e \u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0438\u0437 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0435\u043d\u0437\u0438\u0439 \u0443 \u043d\u0435\u0433\u043e \u0431\u044b\u043b\u0438 \u0448\u0430\u043d\u0441\u044b \u043d\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0431\u0435\u0434\u0443|url=https://news.tut.by/culture/541845.html|work=TUT.BY|accessdate=2017-12-31|language=ru-RU}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 July 2017, Khanok changed his decision and again shared with journalists the intention to protect his \u201chonor, dignity and business reputation\u201d in court, despite the fact that the ban was not violated.<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u042d\u0434\u0443\u0430\u0440\u0434 \u0425\u0430\u043d\u043e\u043a \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0443\u043c\u0430\u043b \u0438 \u0432\u0441\u0435-\u0442\u0430\u043a\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0432 \u0441\u0443\u0434 \u043d\u0430 \u042f\u0434\u0432\u0438\u0433\u0443 \u041f\u043e\u043f\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0443\u044e \u0438 \u0410\u043d\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0438\u044f \u042f\u0440\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e|url=https://news.tut.by/culture/550121.html|work=TUT.BY|accessdate=2017-12-31|language=ru-RU}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:\u0422\u0438\u0445\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0410\u043d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0438\u044f.JPG|thumb|170px|Anastasia Tikhanovich]]\nPoplavskaya was married to [[Alexander Tikhanovich]]<ref>[http://nn.by/?c=ar&i=127580&lang=ru \u042f\u0434\u0432\u0438\u0433\u0430 \u041f\u043e\u043f\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043e\u0442\u043c\u0435\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u042e\u0431\u0438\u043b\u0435\u0439]</ref> until his death on 28 January 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://eng.belta.by/president/view/lukashenko-expresses-condolences-over-death-of-alexander-tikhanovich-98308-2017/|title=Lukashenko expresses condolences over death of Alexander Tikhanovich|accessdate=31 January 2017}}</ref> Together, they had a daughter, Anastasia (born 1980).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vsr.mil.by/2017/03/11/anastasiya-tixanovich-ya-rada-chto-poyavilas-na-svet-imenno-v-etoj-seme/|title=\u0410\u043d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0438\u044f \u0422\u0438\u0445\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447: \"\u042f \u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430, \u0447\u0442\u043e \u043f\u043e\u044f\u0432\u0438\u043b\u0430\u0441\u044c \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0432\u0435\u0442 \u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e \u0432 \u044d\u0442\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0435\u043c\u044c\u0435\"|accessdate=2017-11-10}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\nAlbums with the ensemble \"Verasy\":\n* \u201cOur disco\u201d\n* \u201cMusic for all\u201d\n\nAlbums of Yadviga Poplavskaya and Alexander Tikhanovich:\n* \u201cHappy Occasion\u201d ([[Melodiya|Firm Melody]], LP, 1989)\n* \u201cMusic of Love\u201d ([[Melodiya|Firm Melody]]; Eddy (Minsk), LP, 1995)\n* \"From\" Robin \"to ...\" (Eddy. CD, 1997)\n* \u201cLife is a wonderful moment\u201d (Master Sound, CD, 1997)\n* \u201cLove is Destiny\u201d ([[West Records]], 2008)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poplavskaya, Yadviga}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Valozhyn District]]\n[[Category:Soviet female singers]]\n[[Category:Belarusian female singers]]\n[[Category:People's Artists of Belarus]]\n[[Category:20th-century women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n", "name_user": "Pr12402", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yadviga_Poplavskaya"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York City", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{not to be confused with|2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing pandemic in New York City}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York City\n| width           =\n| image           = File:USNS Comfort passing by Statue of Liberty, March 30, 2020.png\n| image_size      =\n| image_upright   =\n| alt             =\n| caption         = The {{ship|USNS|Comfort}} passing by the [[Statue of Liberty]] in [[New York Harbor]] on March 30\n| map1            = COVID-19 outbreak New York CSA per capita cases map.svg\n| legend1         = Confirmed cases per 10,000 residents in the New York\u2013Newark, NY\u2013NJ\u2013CT\u2013PA Combined Statistical Area\n| map2            =\n| legend2         =\n| map3            =\n| legend3         =\n| map4            =\n| legend4         =\n| map5            =\n| legend5         =\n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[New York City]]\n| first_case      = March 2, 2020\n| arrival_date    =\n| date            =\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| confirmed_cases = {{Unbulleted list\n  |112,086 ([[New York metropolitan area#Combined statistical area|CSA]]; Apr 3)<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Cases US |url=https://www.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=628578697fb24d8ea4c32fa0c5ae1843 |website=www.arcgis.com |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326155740/https://www.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=628578697fb24d8ea4c32fa0c5ae1843 |archive-date=March 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n  |49,707 (NYC; Apr 2)<ref name=\"nyc_gov_data\">{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data.page|title=COVID-19: Data - NyC Health|last=|first=|date=|website=nyc.gov|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401235417/https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data.page|archive-date=April 1, 2020|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>}}\n| suspected_cases =\n| severe_cases    =\n| recovery_cases  =\n| deaths          = 1,562 (Apr 2)<ref name=\"nyc_gov_data\"/>\n| territories     =\n| total_ili       =\n| website         = {{URL|http://www.nyc.gov/coronavirus}}\n}}\n\nThe first [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] case was confirmed in [[New York City]] in March 2020 in a woman who had recently traveled from [[Iran]], a country seriously affected by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|2020 coronavirus pandemic]] at the time. Nearly a month later, the metropolitan area was the worst affected part of the [[United States]], with the medical infrastructure overtaxed and a peak of cases yet to come.<ref name=\"nyti_Coro\">{{Cite news|last1=Goldstein|first1=Joseph|last2=McKinley|first2=Jesse|title=Coronavirus in N.Y.: Manhattan Woman Is First Confirmed Case in State|work=The New York Times|date=March 1, 2020|page=A24|access-date=March 25, 2020|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/01/nyregion/new-york-coronvirus-confirmed.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302012003/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/01/nyregion/new-york-coronvirus-confirmed.html|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"npr._NewY\">{{cite web| title = New York City, U.S. Epicenter, Braces For Peak| author = | work = NPR.org| date = March 24, 2020| access-date = March 26, 2020| url = https://www.npr.org/2020/03/24/820610818/new-york-city-u-s-epicenter-braces-for-peak| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200326185342/https://www.npr.org/2020/03/24/820610818/new-york-city-u-s-epicenter-braces-for-peak| archive-date = March 26, 2020| url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nOn March 1, 2020, the first confirmed case of [[COVID-19]] was confirmed in [[New York State]], a 39-year-old woman [[health care worker]] who lived in [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=West|first=Melanie Grayce|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/first-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-new-york-state-11583111692|title=First Case of Coronavirus Confirmed in New York State|date=March 2, 2020|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=March 9, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303050256/https://www.wsj.com/articles/first-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-new-york-state-11583111692|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> She had returned from [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|Iran]] on February 25, and did not have any symptoms at the time. She went into [[home isolation]] with her husband.<ref>{{cite news |title=New York's first case of coronavirus is a health care worker, and officials say more cases are 'inevitable' |first=Holly |last=Yan |first2=Kristina |last2=Sgueglia |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/02/us/new-york-coronavirus-first-case/index.html |newspaper=CNN |date=March 2, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304002946/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/02/us/new-york-coronavirus-first-case/index.html |archive-date=March 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBy March 25, there were over 17,800 confirmed cases in New York City, and 199 deaths.<ref name=\"nyti_DeBl\">{{cite news| title = De Blasio Calls Stimulus Deal's Treatment of N.Y.C. 'Immoral'| author = | work = nytimes.com| date = March 25, 2020| access-date = March 25, 2020| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/nyregion/coronavirus-new-york-update.html#link-17e20485| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200325112712/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/nyregion/coronavirus-new-york-update.html#link-17e20485| archive-date = March 25, 2020| url-status = live}}</ref> The New York City region was suffering from an [[infection rate]] 5 times higher than the rest of the country, and was the worst-hit district in New York State due to its population density, 56% of known national cases were in New York State,<ref name=\"50 percent\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NBCNews/status/1242107530463019011?s=19|title=NBC News twitter message|last=|first=|date=March 23, 2020|website=|publisher=[[NBC News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 23, 2020|quote=5,707 new coronavirus cases in New York state, Gov. Cuomo announces, bringing state total to 20,875, representing more than half of all US cases}}</ref> with one-third of total known US cases being in New York City.<ref>{{cite news|last=Perlstein|first=Mike|url=https://www.wwltv.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/perl-stats-story/289-f2e70da4-3e5b-48b5-8684-a0dd5dc0361d|title=New Orleans is second only to Seattle in COVID-19 cases per capita|date=March 16, 2020|newspaper=4WWL|accessdate=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317192439/https://www.wwltv.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/perl-stats-story/289-f2e70da4-3e5b-48b5-8684-a0dd5dc0361d|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDuring the month of March, the [[U.S. Army]] dispatched soldiers from [[United States Army Corps of Engineers|Army Corps of Engineers]] field hospitals in [[Fort Campbell, Kentucky]], and [[Fort Hood, Texas]]. to New York City to convert New York City's [[Javits Center|Javits Convention Center]] into a 2,910-bed civilian medical hospital.<ref name=mashcivilian>{{cite web|url=https://www.militarytimes.com/news/your-military/2020/03/27/the-army-corps-of-engineers-has-two-or-three-weeks-to-get-thousands-of-new-hospital-beds-up-and-running/|title=The Army Corps of Engineers has two or three weeks to get thousands of new hospital beds up and running|first=Meghann|last=Myers|date=March 27, 2020|website=Military Times|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330090248/https://www.militarytimes.com/news/your-military/2020/03/27/the-army-corps-of-engineers-has-two-or-three-weeks-to-get-thousands-of-new-hospital-beds-up-and-running/|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> More medical hospitals will be set up by these Army officers in New York City.<ref name=mashcivilian />\n\nOn March 27, infection in New York City surpassed 23,000, with 365 deaths including a nurse in Manhattan and a civilian staff member in the [[New York City Police Department]] (NYPD). [[The Bronx]] had 80 deaths (22% of total deaths in NYC); [[Brooklyn]], 81 (22% of total deaths in NYC); Manhattan, 55 (15% of total deaths in NYC); [[Queens]], 123 (34% of total deaths in NYC); and [[Staten Island]], 26 (7% of total deaths in NYC). A large majority of those who died had underlying health issues.<ref name=\"nyti_N.Y.\">{{cite news| title = N.Y.C. Death Toll Hits 365 as Case Count Tops 23,000| author = | work = nytimes.com| date = March 27, 2020| access-date = March 28, 2020| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/26/nyregion/coronavirus-new-york-update.html| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200328045217/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/26/nyregion/coronavirus-new-york-update.html| archive-date = March 28, 2020| url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28 it was reported that at least 156 [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] workers including chairman [[Pat Foye]] had tested positive, while 1,181 were [[self-quarantine]]d.<ref>{{cite news |authors=Clayton Guse |title=MTA chairman Pat Foye tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/coronavirus/ny-coronavirus-mta-chairman-pat-foye-positive-covid-19-20200328-ku7qifgu2rdi5o4dr5plntgp2i-story.html |publisher=New York Daily News |date=March 28, 2020 |access-date=March 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329110908/https://www.nydailynews.com/coronavirus/ny-coronavirus-mta-chairman-pat-foye-positive-covid-19-20200328-ku7qifgu2rdi5o4dr5plntgp2i-story.html |archive-date=March 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBetween March 28 and 29, the number of deaths in New York City tripled from the previous 24-hour period; 222 people died of the virus bringing the city's fatalities to 672, with 30,765 confirmed cases. Instead of quarantining the city, the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] urged residents in New York, [[New Jersey]], and [[Connecticut]] to refrain from non-essential travel to other states for a period of 14 days.<ref>{{cite news |authors=Jen Chung |title=Coronavirus Updates: 222 COVID-19 Deaths Reported In NYC Over 24 Hours |url=https://gothamist.com/news/coronavirus-updates-222-coronavirus-deaths-nyc-over-24-hours |work=Gothamist |date=March 29, 2020 |access-date=March 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329145514/https://gothamist.com/news/coronavirus-updates-222-coronavirus-deaths-nyc-over-24-hours |archive-date=March 29, 2020 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On March 29, [[CBS News]] reporter [[Maria Mercader]], a New York City resident, died from a COVID-19 related illness.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/video/remembering-cbs-news-journalist-maria-mercader/|title=Remembering CBS News journalist Maria Mercader|accessdate=March 31, 2020|via=www.cbsnews.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330235009/https://www.cbsnews.com/video/remembering-cbs-news-journalist-maria-mercader/|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2020/03/29/coronavirus-cbs-news-maria-mercader-dies-covid-19-age-54/2936246001/|title=CBS mourns longtime journalist Maria Mercader, who died at 54 from coronavirus|first=Hannah|last=Yasharoff|website=USA TODAY|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331021320/https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2020/03/29/coronavirus-cbs-news-maria-mercader-dies-covid-19-age-54/2936246001/|archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[President Trump]] implied on March 29 that there was a black-market for medical equipment in New York City, complaining that [[mask]] usage, which had increased from 20,000 to 300,000 in a week, was \"worse than hoarding.\" \"Where are the masks going, are they going out the backdoor?\" Trump asked. Surgical or [[N95 mask]]s can protect the wearer from 95% of airborne particles and are essential to protecting the health of doctors, nurses, and other health-care providers.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/trump-claims-masks-needed-coronavirus-021110138.html Trump claims masks needed for coronavirus are 'going out the backdoor' of NYC hospitals by the thousands] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330052913/https://news.yahoo.com/trump-claims-masks-needed-coronavirus-021110138.html |date=March 30, 2020 }} by James Pasley, Insider, March 29, 2020</ref> Questioned by [[CNN]]'s [[Jake Tapper]] on ''[[State of the Union]],'' if he thought his messaging may have had something to do with how fast the [[virus]] had spread in the city, Mayor [[Bill de Blasio]] said \"none of us have time to look backward\" and we should concentrate on next week.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/bill-blasio-says-isnt-time-145900084.html Bill de Blasio says there isn't time to focus on coronavirus prevention missteps] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331040341/https://news.yahoo.com/bill-blasio-says-isnt-time-145900084.html |date=March 31, 2020 }} by Tim O'Donnell, The Week, March 29, 2020</ref>\n\nThe {{ship|USNS|Comfort}} hospital ship arrived in [[New York Harbor]] on March 30.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-live-updates-us-death-093743203.html Coronavirus live updates: USNS Comfort arrives in NYC; Anthony Fauci defends extension of social distancing rules; US deaths top 2,500] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330094014/https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-live-updates-us-death-093743203.html |date=March 30, 2020 }} by John Bacon, USA TODAY, March 30, 2020</ref> It was also announced that [[field hospital]]s would be set up in [[Central Park]] in Manhattan and at the [[Billie Jean King National Tennis Center]] in Queens.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/30/824300407/central-park-and-home-of-tennis-us-open-to-house-hospital-beds-for-new-york|title=Central Park And Home Of Tennis' U.S. Open To House Hospital Beds For New York|first=Anastasia|last=Tsioulcas|publisher=NPR|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331113326/https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/30/824300407/central-park-and-home-of-tennis-us-open-to-house-hospital-beds-for-new-york|archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> At hospitals such as [[Lenox Hill Hospital]] on the [[Upper East Side]] of Manhattan, sidewalk morgues were set up on city streets to deal with the overflow of corpses from the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/health/surge-in-deaths-overwhelms-new-yorks-morgues-hospitals |title=Archived copy |access-date=April 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403041350/https://www.pbs.org/newshour/health/surge-in-deaths-overwhelms-new-yorks-morgues-hospitals |archive-date=April 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, it was revealed that New York Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]]'s brother [[Chris Cuomo]], who serves as a [[Cuomo Prime Time|CNN journalist]] and is a New York City resident, was diagnosed with COVID-19, and that the first death of a child from COVID-19 in New York City was recorded.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/e80a98f37714622c5b34d27d94bea8ff|title=NYC sees 1st child virus death; Chris Cuomo tests positive|agency=Associated Press|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331150103/https://apnews.com/e80a98f37714622c5b34d27d94bea8ff|archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/31/media/chris-cuomo-coronavirus/index.html|title=CNN anchor Chris Cuomo diagnosed with coronavirus; he will continue working from home|first=Brian|last=Stelter|publisher=CNN Business|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331155745/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/31/media/chris-cuomo-coronavirus/index.html|archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Response by sector==\n[[File:Coronavirus sign in Brooklyn (60539).jpg|thumb|Woman with a mask walks under a Brooklyn movie theater closed as a non-essential business.]]\n{{seealso|2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)}}\nOn March 2, Mayor Bill de Blasio [[Twitter|tweeted]] that people should ignore the virus and \"go on with your lives + get out on the town despite Coronavirus\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/de-blasio-haunted-by-weeks-old-tweet-urging-people-to-get-out-on-the-town-despite-coronavirus |title=De Blasio haunted by weeks-old tweet urging people to 'get out on the town despite coronavirus' |date=March 25, 2020 |first1=Madison |last1=Dibble |work=[[Washington Examiner]] |access-date=March 28, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329063537/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/de-blasio-haunted-by-weeks-old-tweet-urging-people-to-get-out-on-the-town-despite-coronavirus |archive-date=March 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 7, [[Governor of New York|Governor]] [[Andrew Cuomo]] declared a [[state of emergency]] in New York State after 89 cases had been confirmed in the state, 70 of them in [[Westchester County]], 12 in New York City, and 7 elsewhere.<ref name=\"state-emergency\">{{cite news |last= |first= |date=March 8, 2020 |title=Coronavirus in N.Y.: Cuomo Declares State of Emergency |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/07/nyregion/coronavirus-new-york-queens.html |work=The New York Times |location= |access-date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309082540/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/07/nyregion/coronavirus-new-york-queens.html |archive-date=March 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 9, New York City mayor de Blasio announced that there were 16 confirmed cases of COVID-19 in New York City.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/news/2020/03/09/new-york-city-coronavirus-case-numbers-health-update|title=Mayor: 16 Coronavirus Cases Confirmed in City|website=ny1.com|language=en|access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, as the number of confirmed cases rose to 814 citywide, Mayor de Blasio announced that the city was considering a [[shelter-in-place]] order within the next 48 hours. Across the [[boroughs of New York City]], there were 277 confirmed cases in Manhattan, 248 in Queens, 157 in Brooklyn, 96 in the Bronx, and 36 in Staten Island. Seven city residents had died of the virus.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/politics/2020/03/17/new-york-coronavirus-latest-will-new-york-city-have-to-shelter-in-place-be-on-lockdown|title=De Blasio: New Yorkers Should Prepare for Possible Shelter-in-Place Order in Next 48 Hours|date=March 17, 2020|work=Spectrum News NY1|access-date=March 17, 2020|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317221121/https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/politics/2020/03/17/new-york-coronavirus-latest-will-new-york-city-have-to-shelter-in-place-be-on-lockdown|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, a Brooklyn bar-owner, 56-year-old Vasil Pando, was arrested for defying Governor Andrew Cuomo's ban on bars and restaurants until April 15. Pando was charged with \"illegal sale of alcohol, promoting gambling, and violating the mayor\u2019s {{sic|expected=governor's}} order\".<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-york-speakeasy-bar-owner-135650349.html Coronavirus: New York bar owner becomes first to be arrested for ignoring lockdown] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331140449/https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-york-speakeasy-bar-owner-135650349.html |date=March 31, 2020 }} by Gino Spocchia, The Independent, March 30, 2020</ref>\n\nOn March 30, the mayor announced that most religious buildings had shut down in accordance with quarantine regulations. However, he warned that some churches and synagogues were not in compliance and would be shut down by authorities if they remained open.<ref>{{cite news |title=NYC mayor to synagogues: Close for coronavirus or shut down permanently |url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/NYC-Mayor-to-synagogues-Close-for-coronavirus-or-be-shut-down-permanently-622767 |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330194032/https://www.jpost.com/diaspora/nyc-mayor-to-synagogues-close-for-coronavirus-or-be-shut-down-permanently-622767 |archive-date=March 30, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Public health===\n\nOn January 26, 2020, over a month before the first coronavirus cases were detected in the New York City area, [[Commissioner of Health of the City of New York|New York City Commissioner of Health]] Oxiris Barbot said at a press conference \"We are encouraging New Yorkers to go about their everyday lives and suggest practicing everyday precautions that we do through the flu season\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Goldstein|first=Joseph|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/27/nyregion/new-york-city-coronavirus.html|title=New York Braces for Coronavirus: \u2018It\u2019s Inevitable\u2019|date=January 27, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 29, 2020|last2=Singer|first2=Jeffrey E.|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329201605/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/27/nyregion/new-york-city-coronavirus.html|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On February 2, 2020, Barbot stated \"There is no reason not to take the subway, not to take the bus, not to go out to your favorite restaurant.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fox5ny.com/news/coronavirus-fear-affecting-chinatown-businesses|title=Coronavirus fear affecting Chinatown businesses|date=February 3, 2020|website=FOX 5 NY|language=en-US|access-date=March 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227122827/https://www.fox5ny.com/news/coronavirus-fear-affecting-chinatown-businesses|archive-date=February 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt a press conference on March 3, Barbot said \"We are encouraging New Yorkers to go about their everyday lives\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.silive.com/news/2020/03/coronavirus-risk-remains-low-in-nyc-same-day-testing-now-available-officials-say.html |title=Coronavirus risk \u2018remains low\u2019 in NYC; same-day testing now available, officials say |date=March 3, 2020 |first1=Kyle |last1=Lawson |accessdate=March 28, 2020 |work=[[SILive.com]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328185143/https://www.silive.com/news/2020/03/coronavirus-risk-remains-low-in-nyc-same-day-testing-now-available-officials-say.html |archive-date=March 28, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn response to the increasing number of coronavirus cases at the end of March 2020, several field hospitals were built or proposed, including at [[Javits Center]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/army-helps-make-temporary-hospital-yorks-javits-center/story?id=69845568|title=Army helps make temporary hospital at New York's Javits Center one of the largest in the country|last=Martinez|first=Luis|date=March 27, 2020|website=ABC News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329231758/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/army-helps-make-temporary-hospital-yorks-javits-center/story?id=69845568|archive-date=March 29, 2020|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> [[USTA Billie Jean King National Tennis Center]],<ref>{{Cite news|last=Honan|first=Katie|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/queens-stadium-to-be-converted-into-temporary-hospital-in-coronavirus-fight-11585605068|title=Queens Stadium to Be Converted Into Temporary Hospital in Coronavirus Fight|date=March 30, 2020|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=March 30, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331001258/https://www.wsj.com/articles/queens-stadium-to-be-converted-into-temporary-hospital-in-coronavirus-fight-11585605068|archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and in [[Central Park]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/30/us/new-york-coronavirus-cases-deaths/index.html|title=Central Park becomes a field hospital for New York, where coronavirus deaths have topped 1,000|last=Holcombe|first=Madeline|last2=Yan|first2=Holly|date=March 30, 2020|publisher=CNN|access-date=March 30, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330123931/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/30/us/new-york-coronavirus-cases-deaths/index.html|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Field hospitals were also proposed at [[New York Expo Center]] in the Bronx, [[Aqueduct Racetrack]] in Queens, the [[Brooklyn Cruise Terminal]], and the [[College of Staten Island]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amny.com/coronavirus/governor-calls-on-federal-government-to-authorize-more-field-hospitals-in-new-york-city/|title=Governor calls on federal government to authorize more field hospitals in New York City|date=March 27, 2020|website=amNewYork|access-date=March 30, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329055138/https://www.amny.com/coronavirus/governor-calls-on-federal-government-to-authorize-more-field-hospitals-in-new-york-city/|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> At the request of the Mayor, [[Veterinarian|veterinary clinics]] sent their [[ventilator]]s to human hospitals.<ref name=nyp2020-04-01>{{cite web |last1=Fonrouge |first1=Gabrielle |title=NYC veterinarians forced to choose people over pets in war against coronavirus |url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/01/nyc-vets-forced-to-choose-humans-over-pets-amid-covid-19/ |website=[[New York Post]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403091741/https://nypost.com/2020/04/01/nyc-vets-forced-to-choose-humans-over-pets-amid-covid-19/ |archivedate=April 2, 2020 |language=en |date=April 1, 2020 |quote=Last week, Blue Pearl Veterinary Partners donated seven of their ventilators to New York-Presbyterian Hospital in Manhattan |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Public transport ===\n[[File:Interim MTA NYCT President Sarah Feinberg's First Day (49639838632).jpg|thumb|[[New York City Subway]] passengers on March 9, 2020]]\n[[File:MTA New York City Transit Sanitizes Stations and Subway Cars (49618677077).jpg|thumb|Disinfection of [[New York City Subway rolling stock|New York City Subway cars]] against coronavirus]]\nNew York City issued new commuter guidelines amid the current outbreak, asking sick individuals to stay off public transit, encouraging citizens to avoid densely packed buses, [[New York City Subway|subways]], and trains.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/nyc-issues-new-commuter-guidelines-to-combat-coronavirus-spread/2317584/|title=NYC Issues New Commuter Guidelines to Combat Coronavirus Spread|website=NBC New York|language=en-US|access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> Due to decreasing ridership, amid an existing [[2017 New York City transit crisis|transit crisis]], service on buses, subways, and [[commuter rail]] was reduced starting on March 25.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abc7ny.com/6047040/|title=Coronavirus New York: MTA launches essential schedule amid COVID-19 crisis|date=March 24, 2020|website=ABC7 New York|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326080255/https://abc7ny.com/6047040/|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/mta-suspends-some-lines-of-service-amid-coronavirus-staff-shortages/2341550/|title=MTA Slashes Service, NJ Transit on Reduced Schedules|date=March 24, 2020|website=NBC New York|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326033708/https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/mta-suspends-some-lines-of-service-amid-coronavirus-staff-shortages/2341550/|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\nOn March 8, all school trips were canceled for those in the city.<ref name=\"NewYork38\">[https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2020/03/08/coronavirus-cuomo-testing-kits-connecticut-new-jersey-outbreaks-new-york-cases/ Coronavirus Update: Cuomo Calls For Private Testing To Match Demand, Wife Of New Rochelle Victim Speaks, Schools Close] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309152732/https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2020/03/08/coronavirus-cuomo-testing-kits-connecticut-new-jersey-outbreaks-new-york-cases/ |date=March 9, 2020 }} [[WCBS-TV|CBS 2]]/[[WLNY-TV|WLNY TV 10/55]]</ref>\n\nOn March 13, De Blasio stated that he would keep the schools open, citing the need for [[School meal|meal program]]s to continue and [[child care]] to continue; [[Los Angeles]] and [[Chicago]] had closed their schools at the end of the prior week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/coronavirus-outbreak-nyc-teachers-furious-over-de-blasio-s-policy-n1159491|title=Coronavirus outbreak: NYC teachers 'furious' over de Blasio's policy to keep schools open|last=|first=|date=March 13, 2020|website=|publisher=NBCnews.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325232502/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/coronavirus-outbreak-nyc-teachers-furious-over-de-blasio-s-policy-n1159491|archive-date=March 25, 2020|access-date=}}</ref> On March 14, all [[New York Public Library]] branches in the Bronx, Manhattan and Staten Island were temporarily closed for two weeks.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Schuessler|first=Jennifer|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/14/arts/coronavirus-nypl-closed.html|title=At the Library, Last Call for Beauty and Books|date=March 14, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 26, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326033711/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/14/arts/coronavirus-nypl-closed.html|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Queens Public Library]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://queenseagle.com/all/queens-public-library-closed-until-further-notice|title=Queens Public Library closed until further notice|website=Queens Daily Eagle|language=en-US|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326033712/https://queenseagle.com/all/queens-public-library-closed-until-further-notice|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Brooklyn Public Library]] branches also closed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://patch.com/new-york/prospectheights/brooklyn-public-library-closes-doors-over-coronavirus|title=Brooklyn Public Library Closes Doors Over Coronavirus|date=March 16, 2020|website=Prospect Heights-Crown Heights, NY Patch|language=en|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326033711/https://patch.com/new-york/prospectheights/brooklyn-public-library-closes-doors-over-coronavirus|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The next day, all schools in the [[New York City Department of Education]] system closed until at least mid-April.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shapiro|first=Eliza|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/15/nyregion/nyc-schools-closed.html|title=New York City Public Schools to Close to Slow Spread of Coronavirus|date=March 15, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 26, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326170024/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/15/nyregion/nyc-schools-closed.html|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Closed_playing_courts_at_Golconda_Playground_due_to_CoronaVirus.jpg|thumb|Closed playground in New York City on March 22]]\nOn April 1, Governor Cuomo ordered all playgrounds in the city to be shut in order to promote [[social distancing]]. Parks will remain open.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Barnard |first1=Anne |last2=Schweber |first2=Nate |title=Cooped-Up Children Lose Refuge as N.Y.C. Playgrounds Are Closed |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/01/nyregion/coronavirus-nyc-playgrounds-closed.html?action=click&module=News&pgtype=Homepage |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Crime===\nAt the beginning of March, prior to the confirmation of the first case of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]], and the onset of the coronavirus pandemic in New York City, a 20 percent spike in crime for the first two months of 2020 was reported.<ref>{{cite web|last=DeStefano|first=Anthony M.|url=https://www.newsday.com/news/new-york/nyc-serious-crime-increase-1.42403709|title=Data: NYC serious crimes spikes in first 2 months of 2020|website=[[Newsday]]|date=March 2, 2020|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303190943/https://www.newsday.com/news/new-york/nyc-serious-crime-increase-1.42403709|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> After movement in the city became restricted, [[NYPD]] Commissioner [[Dermot Shea]] stated that the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|public health crisis]] had curtailed crime.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chapman|first=Ben|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-york-city-crime-falls-as-coronavirus-takes-hold-11584998470|title=New York City Crime Falls as Coronavirus Takes Hold|website=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=March 23, 2020|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326034158/https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-york-city-crime-falls-as-coronavirus-takes-hold-11584998470|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> However, by the end of the month, [[9-1-1|911]] calls were at a record high, and 1,048 officers and 145 civilian employees had tested positive for COVID-19. 5,657 uniformed officers, or more than 15% of the force, called out sick on March 31.<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/01/more-than-1000-new-york-city-police-officers-are-infected-with-coronavirus.html More than 1,000 New York City police officers have the coronavirus as 911 calls hit record highs] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401213545/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/01/more-than-1000-new-york-city-police-officers-are-infected-with-coronavirus.html |date=April 1, 2020 }} by William Feuer, [[CNBC]], April 1, 2020</ref>\n\n==Data==\nAdapted from [[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]].<ref name=\"nyc_gov_data\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n! colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center\" | COVID-19 cases in New York City\n|-\n!Date\n!Confirmed cases\n!% change\n!Deaths\n!% change\n|-\n|March 2, 2020\n|1\n|N/A\n|0\n|N/A\n|-\n|March 3, 2020\n|3\n|200\n|0\n|N/A\n|-\n|March 4, 2020\n|13\n|333.33\n|0\n|N/A\n|-\n|March 5, 2020\n|15\n|15.38\n|0\n|N/A\n|-\n|March 6, 2020\n|23\n|53.33\n|0\n|N/A\n|-\n|March 7, 2020\n|36\n|56.52\n|0\n|N/A\n|-\n|March 8, 2020\n|56\n|55.56\n|0\n|N/A\n|-\n|March 9, 2020\n|109\n|94.64\n|0\n|N/A\n|-\n|March 10, 2020\n|179\n|64.22\n|0\n|N/A\n|-\n|March 11, 2020\n|335\n|87.15\n|1\n|N/A\n|-\n|March 12, 2020\n|691\n|106.27\n|1\n|0\n|-\n|March 13, 2020\n|1,302\n|88.42\n|1\n|0\n|-\n|March 14, 2020\n|1,929\n|48.16\n|3\n|200\n|-\n|March 15, 2020\n|2,933\n|52.05\n|8\n|166.67\n|-\n|March 16, 2020\n|4,961\n|69.14\n|17\n|112.5\n|-\n|March 17, 2020\n|7,281\n|46.76\n|24\n|41.18\n|-\n|March 18, 2020\n|10,036\n|37.84\n|45\n|87.5\n|-\n|March 19, 2020\n|13,477\n|34.29\n|68\n|51.11\n|-\n|March 20, 2020\n|17,132\n|27.12\n|111\n|63.24\n|-\n|March 21, 2020\n|19,265\n|12.45\n|144\n|29.73\n|-\n|March 22, 2020\n|21,272\n|10.42\n|188\n|30.56\n|-\n|March 23, 2020\n|24,286\n|14.17\n|263\n|39.89\n|-\n|March 24, 2020\n|27,697\n|14.05\n|341\n|29.66\n|-\n|March 25, 2020\n|31,402\n|13.38\n|443\n|29.91\n|-\n|March 26, 2020\n|34,899\n|11.14\n|582\n|31.38\n|-\n|March 27, 2020\n|38,268\n|9.65\n|730\n|25.43\n|-\n|March 28, 2020\n|40,483\n|5.79\n|888\n|2