n|TVStation=[[ESPN]]\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nThe Cardinals began their 2007 campaign on the road against their NFC West foe, [[2007 San Francisco 49ers season|the San Francisco 49ers]].  In the first quarter, Arizona trailed early as 49ers RB [[Frank Gore]] got a 6-yard TD run for the only score of the period.  In the second quarter, the Cardinals took the lead with kicker [[Neil Rackers]] getting a 35-yard field goal, while RB [[Edgerrin James]] got a 7-yard TD run.  San Francisco would tie the game with kicker [[Joe Nedney]] getting a 33-yard field goal.\n\nIn the third quarter, the 49ers regained the lead with Nedney kicking a 30-yard field goal for the only score of the period.  In the fourth quarter, the Cardinals retook the lead with QB [[Matt Leinart]] completing a 5-yard TD pass to WR [[Anquan Boldin]].  However, late in the game, the Cards' defense failed to hold off San Francisco's ensuing drive, which ended with WR [[Arnaz Battle]] getting a 1-yard TD run.  With just over :20 seconds left in the game, Arizona had one final chance to save the game. Leinart's pass to WR [[Larry Fitzgerald]] was intercepted by 49ers CB [[Shawntae Spencer]].\n\nWith the heartbreaking loss, the Cardinals began their season at 0\u20131.\n\n'''Scoring summary'''\n\nQ1 \u2013 SF \u2013 11:24 \u2013 [[Frank Gore]] 6-yard TD run ([[Joe Nedney]] kick) (SF 7\u20130)\n\nQ2 \u2013 ARI \u2013 12:55 \u2013 [[Neil Rackers]] 35-yard FG (SF 7\u20133)\n\nQ2 \u2013 ARI \u2013 9:15 \u2013 [[Edgerrin James]] 7-yard TD run (Rackers kick) (ARI 10\u20137)\n\nQ2 \u2013 SF \u2013 3:40 \u2013 Joe Nedney 33-yard FG (10\u201310)\n\nQ3 \u2013 SF \u2013 11:20 \u2013 Joe Nedney 30-yard FG (SF 13\u201310)\n\nQ4 \u2013 ARI \u2013 6:46 \u2013 5-yard TD pass from [[Matt Leinart]] to [[Anquan Boldin]] (Rackers kick) (ARI 17\u201313)\n\nQ4 \u2013 SF \u2013 0:26 \u2013 [[Arnaz Battle]] 1-yard TD run (Nedney kick) ('''SF 20\u201317''')\n\n{{-}}\n===Week 2===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Seahawks\n|V1=0 |V2=7 |V3=10 |V4=3\n|Host=Cardinals\n|H1=3 |H2= 14|H3= 0|H4=6\n|Date=September 16\n|Location=[[University of Phoenix Stadium]], [[Glendale, AZ]]\n|StartTime=4:05 p.m.\n|TimeZone=EST\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=64,542\n|Weather=Indoors (roof closed)\n|Referee=[[Ron Winter]]\n|TVAnnouncers=[[Chris Rose]] and [[Terry Donahue]]\n|TVStation=[[NFL on Fox|Fox]]\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nHoping to rebound from their tough divisional road loss to the 49ers, the Cardinals played their Week 2 homeopener against another NFC West foe, [[2007 Seattle Seahawks season|the Seattle Seahawks]].  In the first quarter, the Cards took to the skies first with kicker [[Neil Rackers]] getting a 28-yard field goal for the only score of the period.  In the second quarter, Arizona continued to pound away with QB [[Matt Leinart]] completing a 30-yard TD pass to TE [[Leonard Pope]], along RB [[Edgerrin James]] getting a 17-yard TD run.  The Seahawks would get their only score of the half with QB [[Matt Hasselbeck]] completing a 24-yard TD pass to WR [[Nate Burleson]].\n\nIn the third quarter, the Cardinals' lead was gone with Seattle RB [[Shaun Alexander]] getting a 16-yard TD run and kicker [[Josh Brown (American football)|Josh Brown]] getting a 28-yard field goal.  In the fourth quarter, the Cards trailed as Brown got another 28-yard field goal.  Arizona responded with Rackers kicking a 52-yard field goal.  Late in the game, the Cards defense managed to recover a Seahawk fumble.  It would eventually turn into Rackers' 4th career game-winning field goal as made it from 42 yards out as time ran out.\n\nWith the win, the Cardinals improved to 1\u20131.\n\n'''Scoring summary:'''\n\nQ1 \u2013 ARZ \u2013 1:27 \u2013 [[Neil Rackers]] 28-yard FG (ARZ 3\u20130)\n\nQ2 \u2013 ARZ \u2013 14:07 \u2013 [[Leonard Pope]] 30-yard pass from [[Matt Leinart]] (Neil Rackers kick) (ARZ 10\u20130)\n\nQ2 \u2013 ARZ \u2013 5:43 \u2013 [[Edgerrin James]] 17-yard run (Neil Rackers kick) (ARZ 17\u20130)\n\nQ2 \u2013 SEA \u2013 1:16 \u2013 [[Nate Burleson]] 24-yard pass from [[Matt Hasselbeck]] ([[Josh Brown (American football)|Josh Brown]] kick) (ARZ 17\u20137)\n\nQ3 \u2013 SEA \u2013 8:42 \u2013 [[Shaun Alexander]] 16-yard run (Josh Brown kick) (ARZ 17\u201314)\n\nQ3 \u2013 SEA \u2013 3:34 \u2013 Josh Brown 28-yard FG (17\u201317)\n\nQ4 \u2013 SEA \u2013 9:52 \u2013 Josh Brown 28-yard FG (SEA 20\u201317)\n\nQ4 \u2013 ARZ \u2013 4:44 \u2013 Neil Rackers 52-yard FG (20\u201320)\n\nQ4 \u2013 ARZ \u2013 0:01 \u2013 Neil Rackers 42-yard FG ('''ARZ 23\u201320''')\n\n{{-}}\n\n===Week 3===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Cardinals\n|V1=0 |V2=3 |V3=3 |V4=17\n|Host=Ravens\n|H1=3 |H2=17 |H3=3 |H4=3\n|Date=September 23\n|Location=[[M&T Bank Stadium]], [[Baltimore, MD]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=71,372\n|Weather=Sunny; {{convert|75|\u00b0F|\u00b0C|1}}\n|Referee=[[Jerome Boger]]\n|TVAnnouncers=[[Thom Brennaman]] and [[Tim Hasselbeck]]\n|TVStation=Fox\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nComing off their divisional home win over the Seahawks, the Cardinals flew to [[M&T Bank Stadium]] for an intraconference \u201cbird\u201d battle with [[2007 Baltimore Ravens season|the Baltimore Ravens]]. In the first quarter, the Ravens flew first with kicker [[Matt Stover]] getting a 21-yard field goal for the only score of the period.  In the second quarter, the Ravens increased their lead with Stover's 28-yard field goal.  Arizona would manage to get on the board with kicker [[Neil Rackers]] getting a 48-yard field goal, yet Baltimore managed to put more and more distance from the Cards with QB [[Steve McNair]] completing a 13-yard TD pass to WR [[Derrick Mason]], along with WR/PR [[Yamon Figurs]] returning a punt 75 yards for a touchdown.\n\nIn the third quarter, the Cardinals managed to get a 40-yard field goal from Rackers, yet the Ravens continued its domination with Stover getting a 43-yard field goal.  In the fourth quarter, with QB [[Matt Leinart]] being ineffective, back-up QB [[Kurt Warner]] came in and ignited the Cards' offense with a 5-yard TD pass and a 32-yard TD pass to WR [[Anquan Boldin]].  Afterwards, Arizona tied the game with Rackers getting a 41-yard field goal.  The Ravens got a last-second win with Stover nailing a 46-yard field goal.\n\nWith the loss, the Cardinals fell to 1\u20132.\n\n{{-}}\n\n===Week 4===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Steelers\n|V1=7 |V2=0 |V3=0 |V4=7\n|Host=Cardinals\n|H1=0 |H2=0 |H3= 7|H4=14\n|Date=September 30\n|Location=[[University of Phoenix Stadium]], [[Glendale, AZ]]\n|StartTime=4:15 p.m.\n|TimeZone=EST\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=64,844\n|Weather=Indoors (roof closed)\n|Referee=[[Gene Steratore]]\n|TVAnnouncers=[[Greg Gumbel]] and [[Dan Dierdorf]]\n|TVStation=[[NFL on CBS|CBS]]\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nTrying to rebound from their road loss to the Ravens, the Cardinals went home for another interconference fight, as they would face [[2007 Pittsburgh Steelers season|the Pittsburgh Steelers]]. In the first quarter, Arizona trailed as Steelers QB [[Ben Roethlisberger]] completed a 43-yard TD pass to WR [[Santonio Holmes]] for the only score of the quarter.  However, in the third quarter, the Cards started to fight back.  As starting QB [[Matt Leinart]] struggled, back-up QB [[Kurt Warner]] came in and completed a 6-yard TD pass to WR [[Jerheme Urban]] for the only score of the period.  In the fourth quarter, Leinart was put back in and the Cardinals didn't miss a beat as rookie WR [[Steve Breaston]] returned a punt 73 yards for a touchdown, along with RB [[Edgerrin James]] getting a 2-yard TD pass.  However, Pittsburgh retaliated as Roethlisberger and Holmes hooked up with each other again on a 7-yard TD pass.  Afterwards, Arizona held off an attempt to tie the game and won.\n\nWith the win, the Cardinals improved to 2\u20132.\n\n{{-}}\n\n===Week 5===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Cardinals\n|V1=3 |V2=14 |V3=3 |V4=14\n|Host=Rams\n|H1=3 |H2=10 |H3=7 |H4=11\n|Date=October 7\n|Location=[[Edward Jones Dome]], [[St. Louis, MO]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=61,788\n|Weather=Indoors (dome)\n|Referee=[[Gerald Austin]]\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nComing off their impressive home win over the Steelers, the Cardinals flew to the [[Edward Jones Dome]] for a Week 5 divisional duel with the winless [[2007 St. Louis Rams season|St. Louis Rams]]. In the first quarter, Arizona trailed early with Rams kicker [[Jeff Wilkins]] getting a 46-yard field goal.  The Cards would tie the game with kicker [[Neil Rackers]] getting a 50-yard field goal. In the second quarter, the Cardinals trailed again with QB [[Gus Frerotte]] completing a 16-yard TD pass to WR [[Drew Bennett]].  Arizona would tie the game with RB [[Edgerrin James]] fumbling at the 1-yard line and OG [[Reggie Wells]] recovering the fumble in the endzone for a touchdown.  However, on the Cards next possession, QB [[Matt Leinart]] was sacked by MLB [[Will Witherspoon]], causing his left collarbone to get broken, getting him out for the rest of the game.  Back-up QB [[Kurt Warner]] (former Rams QB) came in for the rest of the game.  Afterwards, St. Louis would respond with Wilkins kicking a 35-yard field goal.  Afterwards, Arizona would end the half with Warner getting a 1-yard TD run.\n\nIn the third quarter, the Rams retook the lead with Frerotte completing an 11-yard TD pass to WR [[Torry Holt]].  Afterwards, the Cards would tie the game with Rackers getting a 32-yard field goal.  In the fourth quarter, the Cards increased its lead with CB [[Roderick Hood]] returning an interception 68 yards for a touchdown.  St. Louis tried to pass the Cardinals for the lead as Wilkins got a 31-yard field goal.  Arizona increased its lead with Warner's 7-yard TD pass to WR [[Larry Fitzgerald]].  The Rams would get close with Frerotte's 29-yard TD pass to TE [[Randy McMichael]], followed up with a successful two-point conversion pass from Frerotte to Holt.  The Cards would emerge victorious.\n\nWith the win, the Cardinals improved to 3\u20132.\n\n{{-}}\n\n===Week 6===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Panthers\n|V1=3 |V2=3 |V3=3 |V4=16\n|Host=Cardinals\n|H1= 0|H2=7 |H3= 3|H4=0\n|Date=October 14\n|Location=[[University of Phoenix Stadium]], [[Glendale, AZ]]\n|StartTime=4:05 p.m.\n|TimeZone=EST\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=64,403\n|Weather=Indoors (roof closed)\n|Referee=[[Walt Anderson (American football official)|Walt Anderson]]\n|TVAnnouncers=[[Ron Pitts]] and [[Tony Boselli]]\n|TVStation=Fox\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nComing off their divisional road win over the Rams, the Cardinals went home for a Week 6 intraconference game against [[2007 Carolina Panthers season|the Carolina Panthers]] and QB [[Vinny Testaverde]], whom Arizona tried to sign for to back up Warner, yet failed.  Backing up Warner for the remainder of the year would be QB [[Tim Rattay]], whom the Cards recently signed.\n\nIn the first quarter, the Cardinals trailed early as Panthers kicker [[John Kasay]] kicked a 33-yard field goal for the only score of the period.  In the second quarter, Arizona continued to trail as Kasay gave Carolina a 43-yard field goal.  The Cards would take the lead with RB [[Edgerrin James]] getting a 23-yard TD run.  In the third quarter, the Panthers jumped back in front again with Kasay getting a 24-yard field goal.  Arizona would retake the lead with kicker [[Neil Rackers]] getting a 50-yard field goal.  In the fourth quarter, the Cards lost control as Carolina took control with Testaverde completing a 65-yard TD pass to WR [[Steve Smith (Carolina Panthers)|Steve Smith]], Kasay nailing a 45-yard field goal, and RB [[DeAngelo Williams]] getting a 13-yard TD run.\n\nWith the loss, not only did the Cardinals fall to 3\u20133, but starting QB [[Kurt Warner]] (2/2 for 21 yards) left the game in the first quarter with a strained left elbow.\n\n{{-}}\n\n===Week 7===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Cardinals\n|V1=0 |V2=6 |V3= 0|V4=13\n|Host=Redskins\n|H1=7 |H2=7 |H3=7 |H4=0\n|Date=October 21\n|Location=[[FedExField]], [[Landover, MD]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=85,640\n|Weather=Sunny; {{convert|75|\u00b0F|\u00b0C|1}}\n|Referee=[[Jeff Triplette]]\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nHoping to rebound from their home loss to the Panthers, the Cardinals flew to [[FedExField]] for a Week 7 duel with former division rival [[2007 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]]. QB [[Kurt Warner]] got the start, despite having a torn left elbow ligament.\n\nIn the first quarter, Arizona trailed early as Redskins RB [[Clinton Portis]] got a 2-yard TD run for the only score of the period.  In the second quarter, things got worse for the Cards as Warner\u2019s second interception was returned by LB [[London Fletcher]] 27 yards for a touchdown.  Arizona would finally respond as Warner threw a 2-yard TD pass to WR [[Anquan Boldin]] (with a failed PAT).\n\nIn the third quarter, the Cards continued to struggle as Portis gave Washington a 1-yard TD run for the only score of the period.  In the fourth quarter, Arizona managed to draw close with Warner and Boldin hooking up with each other again on a 10-yard TD pass, along with back-up QB [[Tim Rattay]] completing a 1-yard TD pass to TE [[Leonard Pope]] (with a failed 2-point conversion).  The Cards would recover their onside kick and even get into position to get a game-winning 55-yard field goal from kicker [[Neil Rackers]].  The kick went wide left, securing their second-straight loss.\n\nWith the loss, the Cardinals entered their bye week at 3\u20134.\n\n{{-}}\n\n===Week 9===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Cardinals\n|V1= 3|V2=0 |V3=0 |V4=7\n|Host=Buccaneers\n|H1=7 |H2= 3|H3=7 |H4=0\n|Date=November 4\n|Location=[[Raymond James Stadium]], [[Tampa, FL]]\n|StartTime=1:00 p.m.\n|TimeZone=EST\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=68,111\n|Weather=Sunny; {{convert|78|\u00b0F|\u00b0C|1}}\n|Referee=[[Terry McAulay]]\n|TVAnnouncers=Ron Pitts and Tony Boselli\n|TVStation=Fox\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\n[[File:Raymond James Stadium American flag.jpg|thumb|An [[American flag]] is unfurled on the field before the game at Tampa Bay]]\n\nComing off their bye week, the Cardinals flew to [[Raymond James Stadium]] for a Week 9 intraconference duel with [[2007 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|the Tampa Bay Buccaneers]].  In the first quarter, the Cards flew first with kicker [[Neil Rackers]] getting a 47-yard field goal.  However, the Buccaneers took the lead with QB [[Jeff Garcia]] completing a 37-yard TD pass to WR [[Joey Galloway]].  In the second quarter, Arizona continued to struggle as Tampa Bay kicker [[Matt Bryant]] nailed a 32-yard field goal for the only score of the period.\n\nIn the third quarter, the Cardinals continued to trail as Buccaneers RB [[Earnest Graham]] got a 2-yard TD run.  In the fourth quarter, Arizona began to fight back as RB [[Edgerrin James]] got a 3-yard TD run.  Late in the game, during the Cards last offensive drive, QB [[Kurt Warner]] would get intercepted by Safety [[Jermaine Phillips]].  Even though replays clearly showed that he didn't stay in bounds, Arizona was out of timeouts and therefore were unable to challenge the play. It would be remembered as the most controversial call in 2007.\n\nWith the loss, the Cardinals fell to 3\u20135.\n\n{{-}}\n\n===Week 10===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Lions\n|V1=7 |V2=0 |V3=7 |V4=7\n|Host=Cardinals\n|H1=3 |H2=14 |H3=7 |H4=7\n|Date=November 11\n|Location=University of Phoenix Stadium, Glendale, AZ\n|StartTime=4:15 p.m.\n|TimeZone=EST\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=64,753\n|Weather=Indoors (roof closed)\n|Referee=Walt Coleman\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=Fox \n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nTrying to snap a three-game losing skid, the Cardinals went home for a Week 10 duel with [[2007 Detroit Lions season|the Detroit Lions]]. In the first quarter, Arizona trailed early as Lions RB [[Kevin Jones (American football)|Kevin Jones]] got a 4-yard TD run.  The Cards would reply with kicker [[Neil Rackers]] nailing a 23-yard field goal. In the second quarter, the Cardinals took the lead with QB [[Kurt Warner]] completing a 1-yard TD pass to WR [[Larry Fitzgerald]], while back-up QB [[Tim Rattay]] completed a 2-yard TD pass to TE [[Leonard Pope]].\n\nIn the third quarter, Arizona continued its scorching as Warner completed a 16-yard TD pass to Pope.  Detroit would respond with Kitna completing a 7-yard TD pass to WR [[Roy Williams (wide receiver)|Roy Williams]].  In the fourth quarter, the Cards pulled away with Warner and Fitzgerald hooking up with each other again on a 20-yard TD pass.  The Lions' last score would be another 7-yard TD pass from Kitna to Williams.\n\nWith the win, the Cardinals improved to 4\u20135.\n\n{{-}}\n\n===Week 11===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Cardinals\n|V1=7 |V2=14 |V3=14 |V4=0\n|Host=Bengals\n|H1= 7|H2=6 |H3=14 |H4=0\n|Date=November 18\n|Location=[[Paul Brown Stadium]], [[Cincinnati, OH]]\n|StartTime=1:00 p.m.\n|TimeZone=EST\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=65,403\n|Weather=Cloudy; {{convert|44|\u00b0F|\u00b0C|1}}\n|Referee=Ron Winter\n|TVAnnouncers=[[Sam Rosen (sportscaster)|Sam Rosen]] and [[Tim Ryan (American football, born 1967)|Tim Ryan]]\n|TVStation=Fox\n}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |FirstEntry=yes |Quarter=Q1 |Time=10:22 |Team=CIN |Event= [[T. J. Houshmandzadeh|Houshmandzadeh]] 19 yard pass from [[Carson Palmer|Palmer]] ([[Shayne Graham|Graham]] kick)|Score= CIN 7\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=Q1 |Time=3:28 |Team=ARI |Event=[[Antrel Rolle|Rolle]] 55 yard interception return ([[Neil Rackers|Rackers]] kick) |Score= Tie 7\u20137}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=Q2 |Time=12:51 |Team=CIN |Event=Graham 41 yard field goal |Score= CIN 10\u20137}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=Q2 |Time=11:05 |Team=ARI |Event=[[Anquan Boldin|Boldin]] 44 yard pass from [[Kurt Warner|Warner]] (Rackers kick) |Score= ARI 14\u201310}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=Q2 |Time= 4:33|Team= CIN|Event=Graham 38 yard field goal |Score= ARI 14\u201313}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=Q2 |Time= :18|Team= ARI|Event=[[Larry Fitzgerald|Fitzgerald]] 5 yard pass from Warner (Rackers kick) |Score= ARI 21\u201313}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=Q3 |Time=13:04 |Team=ARI |Event=[[Edgerrin James|James]] 3 yard run (Rackers kick) |Score= ARI 28\u201313}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=Q3 |Time= 5:08|Team= CIN|Event=[[Chris Henry (wide receiver)|Henry]] 37 yard pass from Palmer (Graham kick) |Score=ARI 28\u201320}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter= Q3|Time= 3:37|Team= CIN|Event=[[DeDe Dorsey|Dorsey]] 19 yard blocked punt return (Graham kick) |Score= ARI 28\u201327}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter= Q3|Time= :35|Team= ARI|Event=Rolle 15 yard interception return (Rackers kick) |Score= ARI 35\u201327|LastEntry=yes}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nComing off their home win over the Lions, the Cardinals flew to [[Paul Brown Stadium]] for a Week 11 interconference duel with [[2007 Cincinnati Bengals|the Cincinnati Bengals]]. In the first quarter, the Cards trailed early as Bengals QB [[Carson Palmer]] completing a 19-yard TD pass to WR [[T. J. Houshmandzadeh|T.J. Houshmandzadeh]]. Arizona responded via CB [[Antrel Rolle]] returning an interception 55 yards for a touchdown. In the second quarter, the Bengals responded with kicker [[Shayne Graham]] getting a 41-yard field goal. The Cardinals would take the lead with QB [[Kurt Warner]] completing a 44-yard TD pass to WR [[Anquan Boldin]].  Cincinnati tried to reply as Graham kicked a 38-yard field goal. Arizona answered with Warner completing a 5-yard TD pass to WR [[Larry Fitzgerald]].\n\nIn the third quarter, the Cards increased their lead with RB [[Edgerrin James]] getting a 3-yard TD run.  The Bengals tried to come back as Palmer completed a 37-yard to WR [[Chris Henry (wide receiver)|Chris Henry]], while RB [[DeDe Dorsey]] returning a blocked punt 19 yards for a touchdown.  Arizona held to win as Rolle returned his second interception 54 yards for a touchdown.\n\nWith the win, the Cardinals improved to 5\u20135.\n\nAntrel Rolle, who was intercepted three times with two of these returned for touchdowns, became the 18th player in NFL history to suffer three interceptions in one game.\n\n{{-}}\n\n===Week 12===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=49ers\n|V1= 7|V2= 10|V3= 7|V4=7 |VOT=6\n|Host=Cardinals\n|H1= 7|H2= 14|H3=0 |H4=10 |HOT=0\n|Date=November 25\n|Location=University of Phoenix Stadium, Glendale, AZ\n|StartTime=4:15 p.m.\n|TimeZone=EST\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=64,483\n|Weather={{convert|65|\u00b0F|\u00b0C|1|disp=or}}\n|Referee=Gerald Austin\n|TVAnnouncers=Ron Pitts and Tony Boselli\n|TVStation=Fox\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nComing off an impressive road win over the Bengals, the Cardinals went home for a Week 12 NFC West rematch with [[2007 San Francisco 49ers season|the San Francisco 49ers]]. In the first quarter, the Cards took flight early as QB [[Kurt Warner]] completed a 28-yard touchdown reception to WR [[Larry Fitzgerald]]. The 49ers responded with QB [[Trent Dilfer]] completing a 2-yard TD pass to TE [[Vernon Davis]]. In the second quarter, San Francisco took the lead via kicker [[Joe Nedney]] hitting a 19-yard field goal and running back [[Frank Gore]] getting an 11-yard TD run. Afterwards, Arizona regained the lead with RB [[Marcel Shipp]] getting a 1-yard TD run & Warner hooking up with Fitzgerald again on a 48-yard TD run.\n\nHowever, in the third quarter, the 49ers retook the lead with Dilfer completing a 57-yard TD pass to WR [[Arnaz Battle]] for the only score of the period.  In the fourth quarter, the Cardinals regained the lead with QB [[Tim Rattay]] completing a 2-yard TD pass to rookie TE [[Ben Patrick]].  Afterwards, San Francisco got the lead again with Gore getting a 35-yard TD run.  Then, the Cards tied the game with kicker [[Neil Rackers]] getting a 19-yard field goal.  In overtime, Arizona had a chance to win the game with a 32-yard field goal.  The kick was good, but a delay of game penalty wiped it away.  On the second try, Rackers missed it wide left.  In the end, the 49ers got the win with Warner fumbling the ball after getting hit in his endzone and LB [[Tully Banta-Cain]] fall on it for the touchdown and the win.\n\nWith the loss, the Cardinals fell to 5\u20136, despite Warner throwing a career-best 484 yards.\n\n{{-}}\n\n===Week 13===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Browns\n|V1=3 |V2=7 |V3=8 |V4=3\n|Host=Cardinals\n|H1= 14|H2=0 |H3=7 |H4=6\n|Date=December 2\n|Location=University of Phoenix, Glendale, AZ\n|StartTime=4:05 p.m.\n|TimeZone=EST\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=64,791\n|Weather=Sunny; {{convert|62|\u00b0F|\u00b0C|1}}\n|Referee=Jerome Boger\n|TVAnnouncers=[[Craig Bolerjack]] and [[Dan Dierdorf]]\n|TVStation=CBS\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nHoping to rebound from their tough divisional home loss to the 49ers, the Cardinals stayed at home for a Week 13 interconference duel with [[2007 Cleveland Browns season|the Cleveland Browns]].  In the first quarter, Arizona jumped out to an early lead as CB [[Roderick Hood]] returned an interception 71 yards for a touchdown, along with QB [[Kurt Warner]]'s 5-yard TD pass to TE [[Leonard Pope]]. The Browns would get on the board with kicker [[Phil Dawson]] getting a 37-yard field goal.  In the second quarter, Cleveland drew close as QB [[Derek Anderson (American football)|Derek Anderson]] completed a 6-yard TD pass to RB [[Jamal Lewis]] for the only score of the period.\n\nIn the third quarter, the Cards responded with Warner completing a 1-yard TD pass to WR [[Bryant Johnson]].  However, the Browns drew closer as Anderson completed a 67-yard TD pass to WR [[Braylon Edwards]] (with WR/KR/PR [[Joshua Cribbs]] completing a 2-point conversion pass to TE [[Kellen Winslow II|Kellen Winslow]]).  In the fourth quarter, Arizona added on to its lead with kicker [[Neil Rackers]] getting a 33-yard field goal, while Dawson gave Cleveland a 22-yard field goal.  Afterwards, the Cards increased its lead with Rackers nailing a 19-yard field goal.  However, the Browns had one final shot towards the end zone.  Anderson's pass to Winslow ended up being caught out of bounds. Replays seemed to indicate Winslow was forced out, which would have been good for a touchdown had it been called on the field. But force-outs are not reviewable, so the touchdown did not count and the Cardinals survived.\n\nWith the win, the Cardinals improved to 6\u20136.\n\n{{-}}\n\n===Week 14===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Cardinals\n|V1= 0|V2= 7|V3=7 |V4=7\n|Host=Seahawks\n|H1= 10|H2= 17|H3=0 |H4=15\n|Date=December 9\n|Location=[[Qwest Field]], [[Seattle, WA]]\n|StartTime=4:15 p.m.\n|TimeZone=EST\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=68,193\n|Weather=Cloudy; {{convert|35|\u00b0F|\u00b0C|1}}\n|Referee=[[Tony Corrente]]\n|TVAnnouncers=Sam Rosen, Tim Ryan and [[Chris Myers]]\n|TVStation=Fox\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nComing off their home win over the Browns, the Cardinals flew to [[Qwest Field]] for a Week 14 NFC West rematch with [[2007 Seattle Seahawks season|the Seattle Seahawks]].  In the first quarter, Arizona trailed early as Seahawks kicker [[Josh Brown (American football)|Josh Brown]] managed to get a 23-yard field goal, along with QB [[Matt Hasselbeck]] completing a 7-yard TD pass to WR [[Nate Burleson]].  In the second quarter, the Cards continued to trail as Hasselbeck completed a 15-yard TD pass to WR [[Bobby Engram]] and a 17-yard TD pass to WR [[Deion Branch]].  The Cardinals would get on the board as QB [[Kurt Warner]] completed a 5-yard TD pass to WR [[Bryant Johnson]], yet Seattle increased their lead prior to halftime with Brown kicking a 41-yard field goal.\n\nIn the third quarter, the Cards tried to rally as Warner completed a 2-yard TD pass to WR [[Jerheme Urban]] for the only score of the period.  However, in the fourth quarter, the Seahawks pulled away as Hasselbeck completed a 3-yard TD pass to TE [[Marcus Pollard]], RB [[Josh Scobey]] tackling Cardinals punter [[Mitch Berger]] in the end zone for a safety, and CB [[Marcus Trufant]] returning an interception 84 yards for a touchdown (with a failed PAT).  Arizona tried to come back as Warner completed an 11-yard TD pass to WR [[Larry Fitzgerald]].  However, Seattle's defense was too much to overcome.\n\nWith the loss, the Cardinals fell to 6\u20137.\n\nDuring this game, Kurt Warner threw a career-worst five interceptions.\n\n{{-}}\n\n===Week 15===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Cardinals\n|V1= 7|V2= 7|V3=7 |V4=3\n|Host=Saints\n|H1= 7|H2= 14|H3=10 |H4=0\n|Date=December 16\n|Location=[[Louisiana Superdome]], [[New Orleans, LA]]\n|StartTime=1:00 p.m.\n|TimeZone=EST\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=70,007\n|Weather=Indoors (dome)\n|Referee=[[Ed Hochuli]]\n|TVAnnouncers=Ron Pitts and Tony Boselli\n|TVStation=Fox\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nHoping to recover from their divisional road loss to the Seahawks, the Cardinals flew to the [[Louisiana Superdome]] for a Week 15 intraconference duel with [[2007 New Orleans Saints season|the New Orleans Saints]].  In the first quarter, the Cardinals took flight as QB [[Kurt Warner]] completed a 1-yard TD pass to TE [[Troy Bienemann]].  The Saints responded with QB [[Drew Brees]] completing a 19-yard TD pass to WR [[Marques Colston]].  In the second quarter, Arizona trailed as RB [[Aaron Stecker]] got a 1-yard TD run.  The Cardinals would tie the game Warner completing an 18-yard TD pass to WR [[Larry Fitzgerald]].  However, New Orleans took the lead with Brees completing a 32-yard TD pass to WR [[David Patten]].\n\nIn the third quarter, the Saints increased their lead as RB [[Aaron Stecker]] managed to get a 6-yard TD run.  The Cards would sneak closer as Warner completed a 3-yard TD pass to rookie TE [[Ben Patrick]].  However, New Orleans answered with kicker [[Mart\u00edn Gram\u00e1tica]] getting a 31-yard field goal.  In the fourth quarter, Arizona tried to mount a comeback as kicker [[Neil Rackers]] nailed a 26-yard field goal.  However, the Saints defense was too much to overcome.\n\nThe Cardinals were officially eliminated from playoff contention the next day, after [[2007 Minnesota Vikings season|the Minnesota Vikings]] defeated [[2007 Chicago Bears season|the Chicago Bears]], meaning again that the home team hosting the Super Bowl would not be participating therein.\n\nWith the loss, the Cardinals fell to 6\u20138.\n\n{{-}}\n\n===Week 16===\n\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Falcons\n|V1= 7|V2=7 |V3=0 |V4=13 |VOT=0\n|Host=Cardinals\n|H1=7 |H2=17 |H3=0 |H4=3 |HOT=3\n|Date=December 23\n|Location=University of Phoenix, Glendale, AZ\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=Ron Pitts and Tony Boselli\n|TVStation=Fox\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nWith the win, the Cardinals improved to 7\u20138.\n\n{{-}}\n\n===Week 17===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Rams\n|V1= 3|V2=3 |V3=13 |V4=0\n|Host=Cardinals\n|H1= 3|H2=21 |H3=7|H4=17\n|Date=December 30\n|Location=University of Phoenix Stadium, Glendale, AZ\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nWith the win, the Cardinals improved to 8\u20138. The 29-point victory allowed the Cardinals to finish the season with a positive point differential (404 scored, 399 allowed) for the first time since [[1993 Phoenix Cardinals season|1993]]. \n\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Arizona Cardinals}}\n{{Arizona Cardinals seasons}}\n{{2007 NFL season by team}}\n\n'''\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2007 Arizona Cardinals Season}}\n[[Category:2007 National Football League season by team|Arizona]]\n[[Category:Arizona Cardinals seasons]]\n[[Category:2007 in sports in Arizona|Arizona]]\n", "name_user": "WOSlinker", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix bold", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2007_Arizona_Cardinals_season"}
{"title_page": "Maria Hadden", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{short description|American politician who has been the alderman of the 49th Ward of Chicago since 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Maria Hadden\n|image       = MariaHadden July2018fundraiser.jpg\n|office      = Member of the [[Chicago City Council]]<br>from the 49th ward\n|term_start  = May 20, 2019\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[Joe Moore (politician)|Joe Moore]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_name  = Maria Elaine Hadden\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1981|1|20}}\n|birth_place = [[Columbus, Ohio]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse      = Natalia Vera\n|education   = [[Ohio State University|Ohio State University, Columbus]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[DePaul University]] {{small|([[Master of Science|MS]])}}\n}}\n'''Maria Elaine Hadden''' is a [[Chicago]] politician and community activist.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mariafor49.org/meet-maria|title=Maria Hadden for 49 {{!}} Meet Maria|website=www.mariafor49.org|language=en|access-date=February 27, 2019}}</ref> She is a member of [[Chicago City Council]], serving as alderman for the city's 49th ward.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Toledo |first1=C\u00e9sar |title=Hadden, Maria |url=https://victoryfund.org/candidate/maria-hadden/ |website=LGBTQ Victory Fund |accessdate=12 June 2019}}</ref> She won election to that office after defeating 28-year incumbent [[Joe Moore (politician)|Joe Moore]] in the [[2019 Chicago aldermanic elections#49th ward|2019 aldermanic elections]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blockclubchicago.org/2019/02/26/shell-49-ward-maria-hadden/|title=Maria Hadden Ousts Longtime Ald. Joe Moore In 49th Ward|last=Ballew|first=Jonathan|website=Block Club Chicago|language=en-US|access-date=February 27, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/news/2019-election-results-alderman-40th-ward-49th-44th-47th/|title=North Side challengers oust Moore in 49th, force O'Connor into runoff in 40th|last=Armentrout|first=Mitchell|website=Chicago Sun-Times|language=en|access-date=February 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chicago.cbslocal.com/2019/02/26/draft-maria-hadden-unseats-incumbent-joe-moore-in-49th-ward/|title=Maria Hadden Unseats Incumbent Joe Moore In 49th Ward|date=February 26, 2019|website=chicago.cbslocal.com|language=en|access-date=February 27, 2019}}</ref> The 49th ward includes most of [[Rogers Park, Chicago|Rogers Park]] and portions of [[West Ridge, Chicago|West Ridge]]. While Hadden is affiliated with the [[Democratic Party (U.S.)|Democratic Party]], she has promised to be an [[Independent politician|independent]] alderman.<ref name=:8/> She is affiliated with the [[Chicago City Council Progressive Reform Caucus|Progressive Caucus]], [[Chicago Aldermanic Black Caucus|Black Caucus]], and [[Chicago City Council LGBT Caucus|LGBT Caucus]] in City Council.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nHadden was born in [[Columbus, Ohio]] in 1981.<ref name=\":0\" /> She earned her bachelor's degree in International Peace and Conflict Studies from the [[Ohio State University]], and subsequently moved to [[Waukegan, Illinois]] to begin a job with the [[AmeriCorps VISTA]] program in 2003.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://scene-chicago.com/scene/index.php/chicago-meet-maria-hadden-civic-leader-board-of-director-member-advocate/|title=Chicago, Meet Maria Hadden Civic Leader, Board of Director Member, Advocate|last=SCENE Magazine|date=April 15, 2018|website=SCENE Chicago|language=en-US|access-date=February 28, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://vote-il.org/Intro.aspx?State=IL&Id=ILHADDENMARIA&nc=1&X=63685757428|title=Maria Hadden {{!}} Previous Candidate for Chicago Ward 49 Board of Aldermen, Chicago Ward 49, Multiple Counties, Illinois {{!}} Vote-IL|website=vote-il.org|access-date=February 27, 2019}}</ref> She moved to Chicago in 2004.<ref name=\":6\" /> She later earned a master's degree in International Public Service Management from [[DePaul University]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Early activist and political career ==\nHadden was a founding board member of the Participatory Budgeting Project, where she worked from 2010 to 2018 to bring [[participatory budgeting]] to cities in the Midwest and the South.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ourcityourvoice.org/who-we-are.html|title=Who We Are|website=Our City Our Voice|language=en|access-date=February 27, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://voqal.org/our-story/leadership/|title=Leadership|website=Voqal|language=en-US|access-date=February 27, 2019}}</ref> She later served as the executive director of the non-profit Our City Our Voice.<ref name=\":2\" /> She also served on the boards of directors of the non-profit Voqal and of [[BYP100|Black Youth Project 100]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.windycitymediagroup.com/lgbt/Maria-Hadden-aiming-to-be-first-Black-queer-Chicago-alderman-in-2019/61624.html|title=Maria Hadden aiming to be first Black queer Chicago alderman, in 2019 - Gay Lesbian Bi Trans News Archive|last=Baudler|first=Liz|website=Windy City Times|access-date=February 27, 2019}}</ref> She has been an active member of Network 49, an independent political organization based in Rogers Park, and of [[United Working Families]].<ref name=\":6\" />[[File:2019 Chicago Hadden logo.jpg|thumb|Logo for Hadden's 2019 campaign for 49th ward alderwoman|alt=]]On January 20, 2018, Hadden announced her campaign to run for alderman in the 49th ward, which covers most of [[Rogers Park, Chicago|Rogers Park]] and portions of [[West Ridge, Chicago|West Ridge]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.windycitymediagroup.com/lgbt/Hadden-holds-fundraiser-ahead-of-2019-elections/61661.html|title=Hadden holds fundraiser ahead of 2019 elections - Gay Lesbian Bi Trans News Archive|last=Baudler|first=Liz|website=Windy City Times|access-date=February 28, 2019}}</ref> After the submission and processing of ballot petitions, Hadden and incumbent Joe Moore were the only candidates to make it on the ballot for the [[2019 Chicago aldermanic elections#49th ward|February 2019 election]]. Hadden's campaign emphasized development without displacement, funding local public schools, and supporting a strong local economy as key issues in the race.<ref name=\":1\" /> She received several endorsements from progressive activist groups, labor unions, and local politicians such [[Chuy Garc\u00eda]] and [[David Orr]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mariafor49.org/endorsements|title=Maria Hadden for 49 {{!}} Endorsements|website=mariafor49.org|language=en|access-date=February 28, 2019}}</ref> Although both candidates self-identified as progressives, observers and media outlets generally characterized Hadden as challenging Moore from [[Left-wing politics|the left]].<ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/blogs/ward-room/49th-ward-alderman-joe-moore-maria-hadden-506106081.html|title=49th Ward Election: Hadden Ousts Moore|last=Bremer|first=Shelby|website=NBC Chicago|language=en|access-date=February 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chicagomag.com/city-life/January-2019/Chicago-Alderman-Races/|title=Ten Chicago City Council Races to Watch|last=McClelland|first=Edward|date=|website=Chicago Magazine|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 28, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/chicago-mayoral-election-results-2019-maria-hadden-elected-49th-ward-alderman|title=Chicago\u2019s Election Signals Break from the Past \u2014 in Wards and at City Hall|last=Dumke|first=Mick|date=February 27, 2019|website=ProPublica|language=en|access-date=February 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/socialists-progressives-chicago-election-rahm-emanuel/|title=Socialists Win Big in Chicago|last=Kampf-Lassin|first=Miles|date=February 28, 2019|access-date=March 2, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0027-8378}}</ref> Hadden won the election on February 26, 2019, with 63% of the vote. She won a majority of the vote in 32 out of 33 precincts in the ward.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rogersedgereporter.com/2019/02/28/hadden-sweep-was-across-the-ward/|title=Hadden Sweep Was Across the Ward|last=rogersedgereporter|date=February 28, 2019|website=RogersEdge Reporter|language=en-US|access-date=March 1, 2019}}</ref> With her win, Hadden is the first [[queer]] [[woman of color]] to be elected to Chicago City Council.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/HeatherCherone/status/1100590390468595713|title=With 75 percent of precincts reporting, and nearly 65 percent of the vote, Hadden declares victory over 49th Ward Ald. Joe Moore, who is in his 28th year in office. She would be the first LGBT woman of color to be elected to the City Council.|last=Cherone|first=Heather|date=February 26, 2019|website=@HeatherCherone|language=en|access-date=February 27, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":8\" />\n\nAfter her election, Hadden said that in her first few months in office, she will pursue a full assessment of infrastructure and services in the ward and set up an advisory committee for community engagement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://loyolaphoenix.com/2019/03/hadden-gears-up-to-take-over-as-alderwoman/|title=Hadden Gears up to Take Over as Alderwoman|last=Yassine|first=Leen|date=2019-03-20|website=Loyola Phoenix|language=en|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref> On April 10, 2019, Hadden joined six other newly-elected members of the City Council in protesting against the approval of [[tax increment financing]] for the [[Lincoln Yards (development)|Lincoln Yards]] and [[The 78]] real estate developments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/business/lincoln-yards-the-78-lori-lightfoot-subsidies/|title=City Council OKs $1.6 billion in subsidies for Lincoln Yards, 'The 78'|last=Spielman|first=Fran|date=April 10, 2019|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/77mI3DzpB?url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/business/lincoln-yards-the-78-lori-lightfoot-subsidies/|archivedate=April 20, 2019|quote=Joining the protesters were seven newly-elected progressive aldermen: [[Daniel La Spata]] (1st); [[Michael Rodriguez (politician)|Mike Rodriguez]] (22nd); [[Byron Sigcho-Lopez]] (25th); [[Andre Vasquez]] (40th); [[Matt Martin (politician)|Matt Martin]] (47th) and Maria Hadden (49th).|df=mdy-all|access-date=April 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Chicago City Council (2019\u2013present) ==\nHadden was sworn in as a member of Chicago City Council on May 20, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/blogs/ward-room/Chicagos-Inauguration-Day-Lightfoot-Aldermen-Sworn-In-510165461.html|title=Chicago's Inauguration Day in Photos|last=|first=|last2=|date=|website=NBC Chicago|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ward49.com/news/congratulations-to-maria-hadden/|title=Congratulations to Maria Hadden|website=Ward 49|language=en-US|access-date=February 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== City-wide issues ===\n\n==== City budget ====\nHadden was one of 11 aldermen who voted against Mayor [[Lori Lightfoot]]'s proposed 2020 budget, alongside either other members of the [[Chicago City Council Progressive Reform Caucus|Progressive Caucus]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/city-hall/2019/11/26/20983774/chicago-city-council-lightfoot-budget-vote|title=City Council approves Lightfoot\u2019s $11.6 billion budget \u2014 with 11 \u2018no\u2019 votes|last=Spielman|first=Fran|date=2019-11-26|website=Chicago Sun-Times|language=en|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref> In a statement about her vote, Hadden stated, \"I\u2019m optimistic about the increased investments in housing, mental health care, homelessness prevention and concrete investments in the South and West sides of our city, but remain concerned that we haven\u2019t exhausted all prospects of progressive revenue in order to take greater strides towards a budget that starts to repair decades of harm and inequity.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://us18.campaign-archive.com/?u=74fbef47485a9e61dfb381788&id=d63284d8c3|title=My Vote on the 2020 Budget|last=Hadden|first=Maria|date=November 26, 2019|website=49th Ward Newsletter|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref> Prior to the vote, Hadden spoke with constituents about the budget at multiple town hall meetings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/alternatives-inc/city-budget-northside-town-hall/528487854564533/|title=City Budget Northside Town Hall|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unitedworkingfamilies.org/upcoming-events/2019/11/23/budget-town-hall-with-ald-maria-hadden|title=Budget Town Hall with Ald. Maria Hadden|website=United Working Families|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/united-church-of-rogers-park/49th-ward-monthly-town-hall/1401562910012267/|title=49th Ward Monthly Town Hall|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\n==== Environmental issues ====\nHadden was an early co-sponsor of legislation to ban single-use plastics and styrofoam in most restaurants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blockclubchicago.org/2020/01/15/chicago-moves-to-ban-all-styrofoam-single-use-plastics/|title=Chicago Moves To Ban All Styrofoam, Single-Use Plastics|last=Bauer|first=Kelly|last2=Alani|first2=Hannah|date=January 15, 2020|website=Block Club Chicago|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\n=== Ward-level issues ===\n\n==== Public health ====\nDuring the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Illinois|2020 coronavirus pandemic]], Hadden coordinated with State Rep. [[Kelly Cassidy]] and local community groups to create the Rogers Park Community Response Team. The Team's stated goal is to help Rogers Park residents stay informed and access resources needed amid the [[social distancing]] and [[Stay-at-home order|shelter-in-place]] measures in place during the crisis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blockclubchicago.org/2020/03/19/rogers-park-residents-form-hotline-300-strong-volunteer-team-to-help-neighbors-during-outbreak/|title=Rogers Park Residents Form Hotline, Huge Volunteer Team To Help Neighbors During Outbreak|last=Ward|first=Joe|date=March 19, 2020|website=Block Club Chicago|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rpcrt.org/|title=Rogers Park Community Response Team \u2013 Local resources for the COVID-19 outbreak|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://us18.campaign-archive.com/?u=74fbef47485a9e61dfb381788&id=82a2b81850|title=49th Ward Weekly Newsletter - March 20, 2020|last=|first=|date=March 18, 2020|website=49th Ward Weekly Update|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> They have offered informational resources online, set up a hotline for residents to request advice, and volunteers trained to safely deliver groceries and prescriptions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://loyolaphoenix.com/2020/04/rogers-park-pulls-together-during-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Rogers Park \u2018Pulls Together\u2019 During Coronavirus Outbreak|last=Padar|first=Kayleigh|date=2020-04-02|website=Loyola Phoenix|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n=== Committees ===\nDuring the 2019\u201323 term, Hadden is a member of eight standing committees in the City Council: Economic, Capital, and Technology Development; Ethics and Government Oversight; Environmental Protection and Energy; Housing and Real Estate; Human Relations and Health; Special Events, Cultural Affairs, and Recreation; Zoning, Landmarks, and Building Standards; and Committees and Rules.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chicago.legistar.com/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=3964780&GUID=958ED219-619B-45B8-BCE0-5B6C327A4130&Options=Advanced&Search=|title=Appointment of chairmen, vice-chairmen and members of standing committees of City Council for Years 2019-2023|last=Office of the City Clerk|date=2019-05-29|website=chicago.legistar.com|series=Resolution #R2019-345|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Alderwoman49/posts/2368503040098877|title=Yesterday I attended my first City Council meeting....|last=Alderwoman Maria Hadden|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-30}}</ref>\n\n=== Alliances and relationships ===\nAfter winning her seat in the first round of the 2019 elections, Hadden endorsed several candidates vying for City Council seats in the run-off elections: [[Andre Vasquez]], who defeated [[Patrick J. O'Connor]] (40th ward); Jessica Gutierrez, who challenged [[Ariel Reboyras]] (30th ward); and two candidates ran in open races: [[Matt Martin (politician)|Matt Martin]] (47th ward) and Robert Murphy (39th ward).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Mariafor49/status/1103795637743767553|title=I want to make sure that my endorsement comes with the people power that helped bring change in the 49th Ward. That is why this cycle I\u2019m focusing on supporting the 4 candidates I\u2019ve announced the past 2 days.|last=Maria for 49th Ward Alderwoman|date=March 7, 2019|website=@Mariafor49|language=en|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref> She also announced support for other candidates in run-off elections who, like her, had been endorsed by [[United Working Families]]: [[Rossana Rodr\u00edguez Sanchez]] (33rd ward), Rafa Ya\u00f1ez (15th ward), and [[Jeanette Taylor]] (20th ward).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Mariafor49/status/1103795640973299714|title=In addition to these races, there are several other opportunities to bring progressive change to City Council. I encourage you to find a candidate you\u2019re passionate about and put in the work to get them elected. I specifically hope you support my fellow @UWFIllinois candidates.|last=Maria for 49th Ward Alderwoman|date=March 7, 2019|website=@Mariafor49|language=en|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref> She declined to make an endorsement in the [[2019 Chicago mayoral election|2019 mayoral election]], citing her goal of being an independent alderman as well as strong support received by both run-off candidates in the 49th ward in the first round.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nAt the start of the 2019\u201323 term, Hadden joined the City Council's [[Chicago City Council Progressive Reform Caucus|Progressive Reform Caucus]], [[Chicago City Council LGBT Caucus|LGBT Caucus]], and [[Chicago Aldermanic Black Caucus|Black Caucus]]. She was selected as the treasurer for the Progressive Caucus.<ref name=\"2019-additions\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/politics/ct-met-chicago-city-council-reform-caucus-20190612-story.html|title=With new members, Chicago City Council members realign Progressive Reform Caucus|last=Chicago Tribune staff|date=2019-06-12|website=chicagotribune.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref> She has also pledged to join the council's women's caucus.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://blockclubchicago.org/2019/03/07/rogers-parks-incoming-ald-maria-hadden-says-no-developer-donations-for-her-more-immigrant-voices-for-neighborhood/|title=Rogers Park\u2019s Incoming Ald. Maria Hadden Says No Developer Donations For Her, More Immigrant Voices For Neighborhood|last=Ballew|first=Jonathan|date=March 7, 2019|website=Block Club Chicago|language=en-US|access-date=March 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHadden's longtime partner and spouse is Natalia Vera.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/mariaelainehadden/posts/10156308538483505|title=Facebook photo by Maria Hadden|last=Hadden|first=Maria|date=March 29, 2019|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=March 29, 2019}}</ref> Vera was elected as a member of the [[Local School Councils|local school council]] for Joyce Kilmer Elementary School in Rogers Park in April 2018.<ref name=\":5\">{{Citation|last=Maria Hadden|title=Meet Maria: Chapter 3|date=January 6, 2019|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ByJOWE4JMPA|access-date=February 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kilmerelementary.org/apps/news/show_news.jsp?REC_ID=506551&id=0|title=LSC Election Results|website=www.kilmerelementary.org|language=en|access-date=February 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{{Election box begin no change|title=[[2019 Chicago aldermanic elections#49th Ward|Chicago 49th ward aldermanic election, 2019]]: General<ref>https://chicagoelections.com/dm/SummaryReport.pdf?v=1551328290737</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|candidate=Maria Hadden|party=Non-partisan|percentage=63.40|votes=7,820}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|party=Non-partisan|candidate=Joe Moore (incumbent)|votes=4,514|percentage=36.60}}\n{{Election box total no change|votes=12,334|percentage=100.00}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Chicago aldermen since 1923]]\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.mariafor49.org/ Campaign website] ([https://web.archive.org/web/20190217193650/https://www.mariafor49.org/ archived pre-election victory version])\n* [https://www.49thward.org/ Official aldermanic website]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Chicago City Council}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hadden, Maria}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:African-American women in politics]]\n[[Category:Chicago City Council members]]\n[[Category:DePaul University alumni]]\n[[Category:LGBT members of the Chicago City Council]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Columbus, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Women city councillors in the United States]]\n[[Category:Women in Illinois politics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{short description|American politician who has been the alderman of the 49th Ward of Chicago since 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Maria Hadden\n|image       = MariaHadden July2018fundraiser.jpg\n|office      = Member of the [[Chicago City Council]]<br>from the 49th ward\n|term_start  = May 20, 2019\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[Joe Moore (politician)|Joe Moore]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_name  = Maria Elaine Hadden\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1981|1|20}}\n|birth_place = [[Columbus, Ohio]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse      = Natalia Vera\n|education   = [[Ohio State University|Ohio State University, Columbus]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[DePaul University]] {{small|([[Master of Science|MS]])}}\n}}\n'''Maria Elaine Hadden''' is a [[Chicago]] politician and community activist.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mariafor49.org/meet-maria|title=Maria Hadden for 49 {{!}} Meet Maria|website=www.mariafor49.org|language=en|access-date=February 27, 2019}}</ref> She is a member of [[Chicago City Council]], serving as alderman for the city's 49th ward.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Toledo |first1=C\u00e9sar |title=Hadden, Maria |url=https://victoryfund.org/candidate/maria-hadden/ |website=LGBTQ Victory Fund |accessdate=12 June 2019}}</ref> She won election to that office after defeating 28-year incumbent [[Joe Moore (politician)|Joe Moore]] in the [[2019 Chicago aldermanic elections#49th ward|2019 aldermanic elections]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blockclubchicago.org/2019/02/26/shell-49-ward-maria-hadden/|title=Maria Hadden Ousts Longtime Ald. Joe Moore In 49th Ward|last=Ballew|first=Jonathan|website=Block Club Chicago|language=en-US|access-date=February 27, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/news/2019-election-results-alderman-40th-ward-49th-44th-47th/|title=North Side challengers oust Moore in 49th, force O'Connor into runoff in 40th|last=Armentrout|first=Mitchell|website=Chicago Sun-Times|language=en|access-date=February 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chicago.cbslocal.com/2019/02/26/draft-maria-hadden-unseats-incumbent-joe-moore-in-49th-ward/|title=Maria Hadden Unseats Incumbent Joe Moore In 49th Ward|date=February 26, 2019|website=chicago.cbslocal.com|language=en|access-date=February 27, 2019}}</ref> The 49th ward includes most of [[Rogers Park, Chicago|Rogers Park]] and portions of [[West Ridge, Chicago|West Ridge]]. While Hadden is affiliated with the [[Democratic Party (U.S.)|Democratic Party]], she has promised to be an [[Independent politician|independent]] alderman.<ref name=:8/> She is affiliated with the [[Chicago City Council Progressive Reform Caucus|Progressive Caucus]], [[Chicago Aldermanic Black Caucus|Black Caucus]], and [[Chicago City Council LGBT Caucus|LGBT Caucus]] in City Council.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nHadden was born in [[Columbus, Ohio]] in 1981.<ref name=\":0\" /> She earned her bachelor's degree in International Peace and Conflict Studies from the [[Ohio State University]], and subsequently moved to [[Waukegan, Illinois]] to begin a job with the [[AmeriCorps VISTA]] program in 2003.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://scene-chicago.com/scene/index.php/chicago-meet-maria-hadden-civic-leader-board-of-director-member-advocate/|title=Chicago, Meet Maria Hadden Civic Leader, Board of Director Member, Advocate|last=SCENE Magazine|date=April 15, 2018|website=SCENE Chicago|language=en-US|access-date=February 28, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://vote-il.org/Intro.aspx?State=IL&Id=ILHADDENMARIA&nc=1&X=63685757428|title=Maria Hadden {{!}} Previous Candidate for Chicago Ward 49 Board of Aldermen, Chicago Ward 49, Multiple Counties, Illinois {{!}} Vote-IL|website=vote-il.org|access-date=February 27, 2019}}</ref> She moved to Chicago in 2004.<ref name=\":6\" /> She later earned a master's degree in International Public Service Management from [[DePaul University]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Early activist and political career ==\nHadden was a founding board member of the Participatory Budgeting Project, where she worked from 2010 to 2018 to bring [[participatory budgeting]] to cities in the Midwest and the South.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ourcityourvoice.org/who-we-are.html|title=Who We Are|website=Our City Our Voice|language=en|access-date=February 27, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://voqal.org/our-story/leadership/|title=Leadership|website=Voqal|language=en-US|access-date=February 27, 2019}}</ref> She later served as the executive director of the non-profit Our City Our Voice.<ref name=\":2\" /> She also served on the boards of directors of the non-profit Voqal and of [[BYP100|Black Youth Project 100]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.windycitymediagroup.com/lgbt/Maria-Hadden-aiming-to-be-first-Black-queer-Chicago-alderman-in-2019/61624.html|title=Maria Hadden aiming to be first Black queer Chicago alderman, in 2019 - Gay Lesbian Bi Trans News Archive|last=Baudler|first=Liz|website=Windy City Times|access-date=February 27, 2019}}</ref> She has been an active member of Network 49, an independent political organization based in Rogers Park, and of [[United Working Families]].<ref name=\":6\" />[[File:2019 Chicago Hadden logo.jpg|thumb|Logo for Hadden's 2019 campaign for 49th ward alderwoman|alt=]]On January 20, 2018, Hadden announced her campaign to run for alderman in the 49th ward, which covers most of [[Rogers Park, Chicago|Rogers Park]] and portions of [[West Ridge, Chicago|West Ridge]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.windycitymediagroup.com/lgbt/Hadden-holds-fundraiser-ahead-of-2019-elections/61661.html|title=Hadden holds fundraiser ahead of 2019 elections - Gay Lesbian Bi Trans News Archive|last=Baudler|first=Liz|website=Windy City Times|access-date=February 28, 2019}}</ref> After the submission and processing of ballot petitions, Hadden and incumbent Joe Moore were the only candidates to make it on the ballot for the [[2019 Chicago aldermanic elections#49th ward|February 2019 election]]. Hadden's campaign emphasized development without displacement, funding local public schools, and supporting a strong local economy as key issues in the race.<ref name=\":1\" /> She received several endorsements from progressive activist groups, labor unions, and local politicians such [[Chuy Garc\u00eda]] and [[David Orr]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mariafor49.org/endorsements|title=Maria Hadden for 49 {{!}} Endorsements|website=mariafor49.org|language=en|access-date=February 28, 2019}}</ref> Although both candidates self-identified as progressives, observers and media outlets generally characterized Hadden as challenging Moore from [[Left-wing politics|the left]].<ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/blogs/ward-room/49th-ward-alderman-joe-moore-maria-hadden-506106081.html|title=49th Ward Election: Hadden Ousts Moore|last=Bremer|first=Shelby|website=NBC Chicago|language=en|access-date=February 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chicagomag.com/city-life/January-2019/Chicago-Alderman-Races/|title=Ten Chicago City Council Races to Watch|last=McClelland|first=Edward|date=|website=Chicago Magazine|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 28, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/chicago-mayoral-election-results-2019-maria-hadden-elected-49th-ward-alderman|title=Chicago\u2019s Election Signals Break from the Past \u2014 in Wards and at City Hall|last=Dumke|first=Mick|date=February 27, 2019|website=ProPublica|language=en|access-date=February 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/socialists-progressives-chicago-election-rahm-emanuel/|title=Socialists Win Big in Chicago|last=Kampf-Lassin|first=Miles|date=February 28, 2019|access-date=March 2, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0027-8378}}</ref> Hadden won the election on February 26, 2019, with 63% of the vote. She won a majority of the vote in 32 out of 33 precincts in the ward.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rogersedgereporter.com/2019/02/28/hadden-sweep-was-across-the-ward/|title=Hadden Sweep Was Across the Ward|last=rogersedgereporter|date=February 28, 2019|website=RogersEdge Reporter|language=en-US|access-date=March 1, 2019}}</ref> With her win, Hadden is the first [[queer]] [[woman of color]] to be elected to Chicago City Council.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/HeatherCherone/status/1100590390468595713|title=With 75 percent of precincts reporting, and nearly 65 percent of the vote, Hadden declares victory over 49th Ward Ald. Joe Moore, who is in his 28th year in office. She would be the first LGBT woman of color to be elected to the City Council.|last=Cherone|first=Heather|date=February 26, 2019|website=@HeatherCherone|language=en|access-date=February 27, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":8\" />\n\nAfter her election, Hadden said that in her first few months in office, she will pursue a full assessment of infrastructure and services in the ward and set up an advisory committee for community engagement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://loyolaphoenix.com/2019/03/hadden-gears-up-to-take-over-as-alderwoman/|title=Hadden Gears up to Take Over as Alderwoman|last=Yassine|first=Leen|date=2019-03-20|website=Loyola Phoenix|language=en|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref> On April 10, 2019, Hadden joined six other newly-elected members of the City Council in protesting against the approval of [[tax increment financing]] for the [[Lincoln Yards (development)|Lincoln Yards]] and [[The 78]] real estate developments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/business/lincoln-yards-the-78-lori-lightfoot-subsidies/|title=City Council OKs $1.6 billion in subsidies for Lincoln Yards, 'The 78'|last=Spielman|first=Fran|date=April 10, 2019|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/77mI3DzpB?url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/business/lincoln-yards-the-78-lori-lightfoot-subsidies/|archivedate=April 20, 2019|quote=Joining the protesters were seven newly-elected progressive aldermen: [[Daniel La Spata]] (1st); [[Michael Rodriguez (politician)|Mike Rodriguez]] (22nd); [[Byron Sigcho-Lopez]] (25th); [[Andre Vasquez]] (40th); [[Matt Martin (politician)|Matt Martin]] (47th) and Maria Hadden (49th).|df=mdy-all|access-date=April 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Chicago City Council (2019\u2013present) ==\nHadden was sworn in as a member of Chicago City Council on May 20, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/blogs/ward-room/Chicagos-Inauguration-Day-Lightfoot-Aldermen-Sworn-In-510165461.html|title=Chicago's Inauguration Day in Photos|last=|first=|last2=|date=|website=NBC Chicago|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ward49.com/news/congratulations-to-maria-hadden/|title=Congratulations to Maria Hadden|website=Ward 49|language=en-US|access-date=February 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== City-wide issues ===\n\n==== City budget ====\nHadden was one of 11 aldermen who voted against Mayor [[Lori Lightfoot]]'s proposed 2020 budget, alongside either other members of the [[Chicago City Council Progressive Reform Caucus|Progressive Caucus]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/city-hall/2019/11/26/20983774/chicago-city-council-lightfoot-budget-vote|title=City Council approves Lightfoot\u2019s $11.6 billion budget \u2014 with 11 \u2018no\u2019 votes|last=Spielman|first=Fran|date=2019-11-26|website=Chicago Sun-Times|language=en|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref> In a statement about her vote, Hadden stated, \"I\u2019m optimistic about the increased investments in housing, mental health care, homelessness prevention and concrete investments in the South and West sides of our city, but remain concerned that we haven\u2019t exhausted all prospects of progressive revenue in order to take greater strides towards a budget that starts to repair decades of harm and inequity.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://us18.campaign-archive.com/?u=74fbef47485a9e61dfb381788&id=d63284d8c3|title=My Vote on the 2020 Budget|last=Hadden|first=Maria|date=November 26, 2019|website=49th Ward Newsletter|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref> Prior to the vote, Hadden spoke with constituents about the budget at multiple town hall meetings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/alternatives-inc/city-budget-northside-town-hall/528487854564533/|title=City Budget Northside Town Hall|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unitedworkingfamilies.org/upcoming-events/2019/11/23/budget-town-hall-with-ald-maria-hadden|title=Budget Town Hall with Ald. Maria Hadden|website=United Working Families|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/united-church-of-rogers-park/49th-ward-monthly-town-hall/1401562910012267/|title=49th Ward Monthly Town Hall|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\n==== Environmental issues ====\nHadden was an early co-sponsor of legislation to ban single-use plastics and styrofoam in most restaurants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blockclubchicago.org/2020/01/15/chicago-moves-to-ban-all-styrofoam-single-use-plastics/|title=Chicago Moves To Ban All Styrofoam, Single-Use Plastics|last=Bauer|first=Kelly|last2=Alani|first2=Hannah|date=January 15, 2020|website=Block Club Chicago|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\n=== Ward-level issues ===\n\n==== Public health ====\nDuring the 2020 coronavirus pandemic, Hadden coordinated with State Rep. [[Kelly Cassidy]] and local community groups to create the Rogers Park Community Response Team. The Team's stated goal is to help Rogers Park residents stay informed and access resources needed amid the [[social distancing]] and [[Stay-at-home order|shelter-in-place]] measures in place during the crisis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blockclubchicago.org/2020/03/19/rogers-park-residents-form-hotline-300-strong-volunteer-team-to-help-neighbors-during-outbreak/|title=Rogers Park Residents Form Hotline, Huge Volunteer Team To Help Neighbors During Outbreak|last=Ward|first=Joe|date=March 19, 2020|website=Block Club Chicago|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rpcrt.org/|title=Rogers Park Community Response Team \u2013 Local resources for the COVID-19 outbreak|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://us18.campaign-archive.com/?u=74fbef47485a9e61dfb381788&id=82a2b81850|title=49th Ward Weekly Newsletter - March 20, 2020|last=|first=|date=March 18, 2020|website=49th Ward Weekly Update|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> They have offered informational resources online, set up a hotline for residents to request advice, and volunteers trained to safely deliver groceries and prescriptions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://loyolaphoenix.com/2020/04/rogers-park-pulls-together-during-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Rogers Park \u2018Pulls Together\u2019 During Coronavirus Outbreak|last=Padar|first=Kayleigh|date=2020-04-02|website=Loyola Phoenix|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n=== Committees ===\nDuring the 2019\u201323 term, Hadden is a member of eight standing committees in the City Council: Economic, Capital, and Technology Development; Ethics and Government Oversight; Environmental Protection and Energy; Housing and Real Estate; Human Relations and Health; Special Events, Cultural Affairs, and Recreation; Zoning, Landmarks, and Building Standards; and Committees and Rules.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chicago.legistar.com/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=3964780&GUID=958ED219-619B-45B8-BCE0-5B6C327A4130&Options=Advanced&Search=|title=Appointment of chairmen, vice-chairmen and members of standing committees of City Council for Years 2019-2023|last=Office of the City Clerk|date=2019-05-29|website=chicago.legistar.com|series=Resolution #R2019-345|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Alderwoman49/posts/2368503040098877|title=Yesterday I attended my first City Council meeting....|last=Alderwoman Maria Hadden|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-30}}</ref>\n\n=== Alliances and relationships ===\nAfter winning her seat in the first round of the 2019 elections, Hadden endorsed several candidates vying for City Council seats in the run-off elections: [[Andre Vasquez]], who defeated [[Patrick J. O'Connor]] (40th ward); Jessica Gutierrez, who challenged [[Ariel Reboyras]] (30th ward); and two candidates ran in open races: [[Matt Martin (politician)|Matt Martin]] (47th ward) and Robert Murphy (39th ward).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Mariafor49/status/1103795637743767553|title=I want to make sure that my endorsement comes with the people power that helped bring change in the 49th Ward. That is why this cycle I\u2019m focusing on supporting the 4 candidates I\u2019ve announced the past 2 days.|last=Maria for 49th Ward Alderwoman|date=March 7, 2019|website=@Mariafor49|language=en|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref> She also announced support for other candidates in run-off elections who, like her, had been endorsed by [[United Working Families]]: [[Rossana Rodr\u00edguez Sanchez]] (33rd ward), Rafa Ya\u00f1ez (15th ward), and [[Jeanette Taylor]] (20th ward).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Mariafor49/status/1103795640973299714|title=In addition to these races, there are several other opportunities to bring progressive change to City Council. I encourage you to find a candidate you\u2019re passionate about and put in the work to get them elected. I specifically hope you support my fellow @UWFIllinois candidates.|last=Maria for 49th Ward Alderwoman|date=March 7, 2019|website=@Mariafor49|language=en|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref> She declined to make an endorsement in the [[2019 Chicago mayoral election|2019 mayoral election]], citing her goal of being an independent alderman as well as strong support received by both run-off candidates in the 49th ward in the first round.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nAt the start of the 2019\u201323 term, Hadden joined the City Council's [[Chicago City Council Progressive Reform Caucus|Progressive Reform Caucus]], [[Chicago City Council LGBT Caucus|LGBT Caucus]], and [[Chicago Aldermanic Black Caucus|Black Caucus]]. She was selected as the treasurer for the Progressive Caucus.<ref name=\"2019-additions\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/politics/ct-met-chicago-city-council-reform-caucus-20190612-story.html|title=With new members, Chicago City Council members realign Progressive Reform Caucus|last=Chicago Tribune staff|date=2019-06-12|website=chicagotribune.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref> She has also pledged to join the council's women's caucus.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://blockclubchicago.org/2019/03/07/rogers-parks-incoming-ald-maria-hadden-says-no-developer-donations-for-her-more-immigrant-voices-for-neighborhood/|title=Rogers Park\u2019s Incoming Ald. Maria Hadden Says No Developer Donations For Her, More Immigrant Voices For Neighborhood|last=Ballew|first=Jonathan|date=March 7, 2019|website=Block Club Chicago|language=en-US|access-date=March 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHadden's longtime partner and spouse is Natalia Vera.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/mariaelainehadden/posts/10156308538483505|title=Facebook photo by Maria Hadden|last=Hadden|first=Maria|date=March 29, 2019|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=March 29, 2019}}</ref> Vera was elected as a member of the [[Local School Councils|local school council]] for Joyce Kilmer Elementary School in Rogers Park in April 2018.<ref name=\":5\">{{Citation|last=Maria Hadden|title=Meet Maria: Chapter 3|date=January 6, 2019|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ByJOWE4JMPA|access-date=February 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kilmerelementary.org/apps/news/show_news.jsp?REC_ID=506551&id=0|title=LSC Election Results|website=www.kilmerelementary.org|language=en|access-date=February 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{{Election box begin no change|title=[[2019 Chicago aldermanic elections#49th Ward|Chicago 49th ward aldermanic election, 2019]]: General<ref>https://chicagoelections.com/dm/SummaryReport.pdf?v=1551328290737</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|candidate=Maria Hadden|party=Non-partisan|percentage=63.40|votes=7,820}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|party=Non-partisan|candidate=Joe Moore (incumbent)|votes=4,514|percentage=36.60}}\n{{Election box total no change|votes=12,334|percentage=100.00}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Chicago aldermen since 1923]]\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.mariafor49.org/ Campaign website] ([https://web.archive.org/web/20190217193650/https://www.mariafor49.org/ archived pre-election victory version])\n* [https://www.49thward.org/ Official aldermanic website]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Chicago City Council}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hadden, Maria}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:African-American women in politics]]\n[[Category:Chicago City Council members]]\n[[Category:DePaul University alumni]]\n[[Category:LGBT members of the Chicago City Council]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Columbus, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Women city councillors in the United States]