{"title_page": "DJ Static (American DJ)", "text_new": "{{mi|{{BLP sources|date=June 2013}}\n{{notability|date=January 2019}}\n}}\nSean '''DJ Static''' Moore (b. October 9, 1972, St. Louis.Mo) is an American DJ and record producer in the St.Louis Area and Kansas City area. He worked with [[hip hop]] artists and rappers..\n\n== Early life ==\nHe was born and raised in Carr Square Village. He attended Blewett Middle School and [[Vashon High School]] as well as [[Jennings, Missouri|Jennings High School]]. He returned to Vashon where he played sports. \n\n== Career ==\nHe started in the entertainment business in the early 1990s. His big break came in the fall of 1993 to appear on the radio to Clear Channel and Chapter Communication. He left the music business to work in security, then returned to music. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Static, Dj}}\n[[Category:American DJs]]\n[[Category:American record producers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n{{US-DJ-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{mi|{{BLP sources|date=June 2013}}\n{{notability|date=January 2019}}\n}}\nSean '''DJ Static''' Moore (b. October 9, 1972, St. Louis.Mo) is an American DJ and record producer in the St.Louis Area and Kansas City area. He worked with [[hip hop]] artists and rappers..\n\n== Early life ==\nHe was born and raised in Carr Square Village. He attended Blewett Middle School and [[Vashon High School]] as well as [[Jennings, Missouri|Jennings High School]]. He returned to Vashon where he played sports. \n\n== Career ==\nHe started in the entertainment business in the early 1990's. His big break came in the fall of 1993 to appear on the radio to Clear Channel and Chapter Communication. He left the music business to work in security, then returned to music. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Static, Dj}}\n[[Category:American DJs]]\n[[Category:American record producers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n{{US-DJ-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DJ_Static_(American_DJ)"}
{"title_page": "Mark A. Brennan", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian landscape artist|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{about||the soap opera character|Mark Brennan (Neighbours)|the footballer|Mark Brennan (footballer)|the Roman Catholic Bishop|Mark E. Brennan}}\n[[File:Mark A. Brennan.jpg|thumb|right|Mark A. Brennan]] \n'''Mark Brennan''' (born 1968) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] landscape [[Painting|artist]] known for his work depicting Canadian National parks and wilderness areas using painting, sound and fine art photography.<ref name=\"Local painter taking his art to the silver screen \" />\n\n==Biography==\nBrennan was born in [[Swindon]], [[England]] in 1968.<ref name=\"Biography\">{{cite web|url=http://www.markbrennanfineart.ca/prof.htm |title=Biography |publisher=Mark Brennan |accessdate=2008-08-02 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080501183434/http://www.markbrennanfineart.ca/prof.htm |archivedate=2008-05-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He grew up on the West Coast of [[Scotland]], where he spent much of his time exploring the [[Scottish Highlands]].<ref name=\"Local painter taking his art to the silver screen\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ngnews.ca/index.cfm?sid=99573&sc=49|title=Local painter taking his art to the silver screen|date=July 1, 2008|publisher=News, The (Nova Scotia)|accessdate=2008-08-02|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130115121517/http://www.ngnews.ca/index.cfm?sid=99573&sc=49|archive-date=January 15, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1984, after leaving high school at  age 16 he joined the British Royal Navy, just as the Cold War was ending. This was where his introduction to artistic expression came into being, manifesting in the form of documenting overseas deployments in the North Atlantic and Arctic as a ships photographer. During an Arctic patrol, Mark began to explore painting at age 18 which continued later when he worked in London, borrowing art books from the library during quiet night watches to teach himself painting. In 1985, aged 17, while on deployment in Middle East during the Gulf War, he witnessed the edge of the Ethiopian Famine, when the ship he was serving on, HMS Charybdis visited Djibouti. In July 1988 he photographed the Piper Alpha oil rig explosion in the North Sea where 167 men died whilst serving as ships photographer on HMS Phoebe.\n\nAt the age of 19 he emigrated to [[Pictou County]] in [[Nova Scotia]], Canada,<ref name=\"Isolating creativity\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ngnews.ca/index.cfm?sid=99573&sc=49|title=Isolating creativity|last=McIntyre|first=Cait|date=January 18, 2008|accessdate=2008-08-02|publisher=News, The (Nova Scotia)|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130115121517/http://www.ngnews.ca/index.cfm?sid=99573&sc=49|archive-date=January 15, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>  and painted his first landscape in the early 1990s at Perch Lake near [[Trafalgar, Nova Scotia]].<ref name=\"Isolating creativity\" />\n\nBrennan\u2019s main focus has been to record Canada's wilderness areas and [[National Parks]] through landscape painting.<ref name=\"Isolating creativity\" /> In 2010 he began working with sound, recording the bio-phony of intact wilderness areas as a way to both connect to nature and use during his solo art shows. In 2016  Brennan returned to traditional film photography to work on a series of landscape photographs depicting the wild coastline of Nova Scotia, Canada.\n\nIn 2006 he ran for the federal Green Party as a parachute candidate in the riding of Random, Burin, St George's, Newfoundland.\n\nHe has had 13 solo art shows.\n\nHis work can be found in the Nova Scotia Government Public Art Bank Collection as well as private and corporate collections.<ref name=\"Isolating creativity\" /><ref name=\"Art Bank Collection\">{{cite news|url=http://www.gov.ns.ca/news/details.asp?id=20080417001|title=Nova Scotia Artwork Purchased for Art Bank Collection|date=April 16, 2008|publisher=Tourism, Culture and Heritage (Nova Scotia)|accessdate=2008-08-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608041732/http://www.gov.ns.ca/news/details.asp?id=20080417001|archive-date=June 8, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2009 he was included in the book ''From Land & Sea, Nova Scotia's Contemporary Landscape Artists'', published by Nimbus Publishing.\n\n== Gallery ==\n\n{{Empty section|date=November 2018}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.markbrennanfineart.ca Mark Brennan]\n* [http://www.cbc.ca/canadavotes/riding/005/#MarkBrennan CBC Canada Votes Election  Coverage 2006]\n* [http://daryl.chin.gc.ca/basis/aich/user/www/sf Canadian Heritage Information Network, Artists in Canada]{{dead link|date=October 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brennan, Mark A.}}\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian painters]]\n[[Category:Canadian male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian painters]]\n[[Category:Canadian landscape painters]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:Newfoundland and Labrador candidates for Member of Parliament]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian landscape artist|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{about||the soap opera character|Mark Brennan (Neighbours)|the footballer|Mark Brennan (footballer)|the Roman Catholic Bishop|Mark E. Brennan}}\n[[File:Mark A. Brennan.jpg|thumb|right|Mark A. Brennan]] \n'''Mark Brennan''' (born 1968) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] landscape [[Painting|artist]] known for his work depicting Canadian National parks and wilderness areas using painting, sound and fine art photography.<ref name=\"Local painter taking his art to the silver screen \" />\n\n==Biography==\nBrennan was born in [[Swindon]], [[England]] in 1968.<ref name=\"Biography\">{{cite web|url=http://www.markbrennanfineart.ca/prof.htm |title=Biography |publisher=Mark Brennan |accessdate=2008-08-02 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080501183434/http://www.markbrennanfineart.ca/prof.htm |archivedate=2008-05-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He grew up on the West Coast of [[Scotland]], where he spent much of his time exploring the [[Scottish Highlands]].<ref name=\"Local painter taking his art to the silver screen\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ngnews.ca/index.cfm?sid=99573&sc=49|title=Local painter taking his art to the silver screen|date=July 1, 2008|publisher=News, The (Nova Scotia)|accessdate=2008-08-02|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130115121517/http://www.ngnews.ca/index.cfm?sid=99573&sc=49|archive-date=January 15, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1984, after leaving high school at  age 16 he joined the British Royal Navy, just as the Cold War was ending. This was where his introduction to artistic expression came into being, manifesting in the form of documenting overseas deployments in the North Atlantic and Arctic as a ships photographer. During an Arctic patrol, Mark began to explore painting at age 18 which continued later when he worked in London, borrowing art books from the library during quiet night watches to teach himself painting. In 1985, aged 17, while on deployment in Middle East during the Gulf War, he witnessed the edge of the Ethiopian Famine, when the ship he was serving on, HMS Charybdis visited Djibouti. In July 1988 he photographed the Piper Alpha oil rig explosion in the North Sea where 167 men died whilst serving as ships photographer on HMS Phoebe.\n\nAt the age of 19 he emigrated to [[Pictou County]] in [[Nova Scotia]], Canada,<ref name=\"Isolating creativity\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ngnews.ca/index.cfm?sid=99573&sc=49|title=Isolating creativity|last=McIntyre|first=Cait|date=January 18, 2008|accessdate=2008-08-02|publisher=News, The (Nova Scotia)|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130115121517/http://www.ngnews.ca/index.cfm?sid=99573&sc=49|archive-date=January 15, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>  and painted his first landscape in the early 1990's at Perch Lake near [[Trafalgar, Nova Scotia]].<ref name=\"Isolating creativity\" />\n\nBrennan\u2019s main focus has been to record Canada's wilderness areas and [[National Parks]] through landscape painting.<ref name=\"Isolating creativity\" /> In 2010 he began working with sound, recording the bio-phony of intact wilderness areas as a way to both connect to nature and use during his solo art shows. In 2016  Brennan returned to traditional film photography to work on a series of landscape photographs depicting the wild coastline of Nova Scotia, Canada.\n\nIn 2006 he ran for the federal Green Party as a parachute candidate in the riding of Random, Burin, St George's, Newfoundland.\n\nHe has had 13 solo art shows.\n\nHis work can be found in the Nova Scotia Government Public Art Bank Collection as well as private and corporate collections.<ref name=\"Isolating creativity\" /><ref name=\"Art Bank Collection\">{{cite news|url=http://www.gov.ns.ca/news/details.asp?id=20080417001|title=Nova Scotia Artwork Purchased for Art Bank Collection|date=April 16, 2008|publisher=Tourism, Culture and Heritage (Nova Scotia)|accessdate=2008-08-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608041732/http://www.gov.ns.ca/news/details.asp?id=20080417001|archive-date=June 8, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2009 he was included in the book ''From Land & Sea, Nova Scotia's Contemporary Landscape Artists'', published by Nimbus Publishing.\n\n== Gallery ==\n\n{{Empty section|date=November 2018}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.markbrennanfineart.ca Mark Brennan]\n* [http://www.cbc.ca/canadavotes/riding/005/#MarkBrennan CBC Canada Votes Election  Coverage 2006]\n* [http://daryl.chin.gc.ca/basis/aich/user/www/sf Canadian Heritage Information Network, Artists in Canada]{{dead link|date=October 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brennan, Mark A.}}\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian painters]]\n[[Category:Canadian male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian painters]]\n[[Category:Canadian landscape painters]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:Newfoundland and Labrador candidates for Member of Parliament]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_A._Brennan"}
